<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 00:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls, Japanese Stocks Up  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- The U.S. dollar fell against the yen Monday morning, pushed
down by slumping U.S. stock prices. Tokyo shares moved slightly higher.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.S. dollar bought 109.68 yen in late morning, down 1.16 yen from late
Friday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level of 110.47 yen on Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which was down some 45 points
early in the session, gained 38.54 points, or 0.19 percent, to 19,856.42 at the
end of the morning session. On Friday, the average closed up 246.44 points, or
1.26 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   In currency dealings, the dollar came under selling pressure after the Dow
Jones industrial average fell 230.51 points, or 2.3 percent, to 9,862.12 at
Friday's close.
</P>
<P>
	   It was the first close below 10,000 since April 6, 1999, and the lowest
close since April 1, 1999, when it finished at 9,832.51.
</P>
<P>
	   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 106.14 yen, down from 109.51 yen
late Friday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
	   On the stock market, prices started lower Monday following sharp falls in
U.S. blue-chip stocks Friday, but later moved into positive territory led by a
rise in Japanese blue chip issues.
</P>
<P>
	   Kunihiro Hatae, general manager at Tokyo Securities Co., said Japanese
investors have already factored U.S. worries about rising interest rates into
stock prices, and said the Tokyo market would not necessarily continue to move
in tandem with New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Strong demand would continue to support share prices in Tokyo, Hatae said.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors would not buy shares in Arabian Oil, whose stock price stood at
750 yen (dlrs 6.88) at late morning, compared to 850 yen (dlrs 7.80) at Friday's
close.
</P>
<P>
	   The company said its drilling rights with Saudi Arabia expired early Monday
after renewal negotiations broke down over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
	   Japan's trade minister Takashi Fukaya said in a news conference Monday
morning that oil supplies to Japan from Saudi Arabia will continue unchanged.
</P>
<P>
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the first
section was up 15.69 points, or 0.91 percent, to 1,740.19. The TOPIX closed up
34.45 points, or 2.04 percent, on Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell to 1.8450
percent from Friday's finish of 1.8800 percent. Its price rose 0.30 point to
99.62.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
