<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canucks 2, Coyotes 1  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- Todd Bertuzzi scored for the third time
in three games and Felix Potvin stopped 27 shots as the Vancouver Canucks beat
Phoenix 2-1 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   Bertuzzi opened the scoring with a beautiful solo effort just 1:36 into the
second period. Bertuzzi cut hard around Coyotes defenseman Jyrki Lumme on the
right side, then moved quickly back into the middle and through the crease
before tucking the puck behind goaltender Sean Burke.
</P>
<P>
	   Darby Hendrickson made it 2-0 on a wraparound with 53 seconds left in the
period. Hendrickson also assisted on Bertuzzi's goal and now has three goals and
three assists in his last five games.
</P>
<P>
	   Potvin was two minutes away from his second shutout of the year and first
with Vancouver before Deron Quint scored into a wide-open net on a rebound.
</P>
<P>
	   Phoenix finished a four-game, all-Canadian road trip 0-3-1 and dropped to
32-23-7-1 overall. The Coyotes are now just 1-12-3 this year when Jeremy Roenick
fails to record a point. Phoenix is 28-8-3 when Roenick gets on the scoresheet.
</P>
<P>
	   The Canucks improved to 6-3-1 since the All-Star break. They are eight
points behind Colorado and San Jose for the final Western Conference playoff
spot.
</P>
<P>
	   Potvin wasn't tested often in the first period, but faced 11 shots in the
second and made several big saves in the third. He made his best save of the
night less than one minute into the third period when he stopped 20-goal scorer
Shane Doan on a partial breakaway.
</P>
<P>
	   Potvin also got a little help from the goal post when Louie DeBrusk got a
wrist shot behind him with 5:27 left. He has posted a 4-2-1 record since
returning from a knee injury after the All-Star break.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
