<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diallo juror describes 'unhappy' decision  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Clearing four white police officers of murder in the
slaying of an unarmed black man wasn't easy, according to some jurors.
<P>
	   But the law made the jury's decision "very clear - not happy, but clear,"
juror Helen Harder said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   Speaking publicly for the first time since Friday's verdict in the racially
charged case, Harder said that the jury deliberated without discord before
announcing its dramatic decision.
</P>
<P>
	   "It turned out the only way it could turn out," Harder, 71, told The
Associated Press in a brief interview in the kitchen of her Albany County home.
</P>
<P>
	   Added Harder: "I'm not saying it's a happy verdict. I know the cops are
happy. None of (the jurors) are very happy. But that's the way it worked out."
</P>
<P>
	   In an interview on Sunday with NBC, juror Tim DeTraglia agreed with Harder's
assessment, even saying "tears were shed" during deliberations.
</P>
<P>
	   Officers Sean Carroll, Edward McMellon, Kenneth Boss and Richard Murphy were
cleared of murder and other charges in the slaying of Diallo, a West African
immigrant.
</P>
<P>
	   The plainclothes officers claimed they fired 41 bullets at the victim on
Feb. 4, 1999, after he refused orders to halt for questioning and pulled out a
black object they thought was a small handgun. Diallo was hit 19 times in the
vestibule of his Bronx apartment before the defendants realized the object was a
wallet.
</P>
<P>
	   Apparently, the officers' testimony was a crucial point for the jurors.
</P>
<P>
	   "He looked at the police officers, they identified themselves, and as they
moved toward him, he turned and backed away," juror Tom Knowles said to NBC.
"Why? Why? We won't know those answers."
</P>
<P>
	   Juror Ed Powell also told NBC the jury believed that the officers thought
that their lives were in danger.
</P>
<P>
	   "If I were to pull something out of my pocket, you couldn't identify that
quickly whether it was a gun or a wallet," Powell said, adding that the officers
had a legal right to defend themselves if they thought Diallo was attacking
them.
</P>
<P>
	   The death of Diallo - and now the not-guilty verdict - has flamed tensions
between police and minorities and touched off protests around New York City.
Because of pre-trial publicity, an appeals court moved the murder case from the
Bronx to Albany, where Harder, who is white, served on a jury that also had four
black women and seven white men.
</P>
<P>
	   Jurors have remained mostly silent since the verdict, despite constant
hounding by network television, New York City newspapers and major news
organizations.
</P>
<P>
	   The jury's black forewoman, who once lived in the Bronx, told the New York
Post that the three-day deliberation had "nothing to do with race." She declined
further comment.
</P>
<P>
	   Harder, who has nine children and 17 grandchildren, described the heartbreak
of seeing Diallo's parents sitting in the front row each day of the month-long
trial.
</P>
<P>
	   The juror didn't mention race. But her husband, attorney George Harder, said
his wife told him that it was not an issue in the jury's deliberations.
</P>
<P>
	   The defense case hinged on the emotional testimony of the officers. All
claimed they were convinced that they had to shoot Diallo in self-defense.
</P>
<P>
	   The judge instructed jurors several times that by law if they concluded that
the officers "reasonably believed" Diallo was armed and dangerous, they must
acquit.
</P>
<P>
	   About the officers, Harder said, "I thought they were quite believable."
</P>
<P>
	   The juror also said she was relieved that the trial is over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-28-00 0114 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000228.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> In pulpits and streets, appeals for justice and change  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Demonstrators marched down Broadway chanting "it's a
wallet not a gun" on the second day of protests over the acquittal of four
police officers in the shooting death of Amadou Diallo.
<P>
	   The reference was to the wallet the officers said they mistook for a gun. In
what was billed as a day of prayer Sunday, political leaders and activists
criticized the not-guilty verdict as inappropriate for a case in which police
fired 41 bullets and hit the African immigrant 19 times, only to learn that he
was unarmed.
</P>
<P>
	   More than 1,000 people joined a vigil outside the United Nations, where
civil rights activist the Rev. Al Sharpton said he hoped to bring the Diallo
case to international attention. Afterward, about 450 people - accompanied by a
phalanx of police - marched to City Hall.
</P>
<P>
	   "We hope to express our feelings - I must see justice done," said marcher
Omar Jalloh.
</P>
<P>
	   The march was similar to Saturday's protest, although it was smaller and not
as tense. Police said there was one arrest for disorderly conduct and one
summons issued for using a megaphone without a permit.
</P>
<P>
	   Sharpton said he was "calling for another jury to hear evidence" on the
policies of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
	   "Come November, the jury is going to render its decision," he said,
referring to Giuliani's probable run for the U.S. Senate. "We're going to
boycott in this city. We are afraid to spend money with certain people because
we are considered suspects. Let's hold our wallets, let's hold our wallets."
</P>
<P>
	   Later, Sharpton's spokeswoman, Rachel Noerdlinger, said Sharpton and his
National Action Network are investigating which companies contribute to the
Patrolmen's Benevolent Association. The PBA helped finance the defense for the
officers.
</P>
<P>
	   Later this week, Sharpton will release the names of the companies and ask
citizens to boycott them, his spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
	   The four officers, acquitted of second-degree murder and lesser charges by a
jury in Albany on Friday, still face a departmental inquiry and possibly federal
charges if Attorney General Janet Reno finds evidence that Diallo's civil rights
were violated.
</P>
<P>
	   At St. Patrick's Cathedral, Auxiliary Bishop James McCarthy, filling in for
an ailing Cardinal John O'Connor, told parishioners Diallo's death should cause
people to "re-examine our own tendencies toward violence, toward fear and
perhaps toward prejudice - racial prejudice at that."
</P>
<P>
	   The Rev. Calvin Butts, pastor of Harlem's Abyssinian Baptist Church, urged
his followers to vote against Giuliani, saying the mayor had failed to thank him
for urging calm in the wake of the Diallo shooting a year ago.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm not blaming Giuliani for pulling the trigger but for creating a climate
that's divisive," Butts said in a telephone interview. "And I'm not calling for
calm. I think black people ought to be agitated, they ought to be active."
</P>
<P>
	   Bruce Teitelbaum, a spokesman for Giuliani's Senate campaign, questioned
Butts' motives, saying he had "hugged Mayor Giuliani" at an interfaith service
at St. Patrick's soon after the shooting and "now he is exploiting Amadou
Diallo's death for partisan political reasons."
</P>
<P>
	   City Council Speaker Peter Vallone, speaking at Harlem's Bethel AME church,
said that to make sure Diallo's death was not in vain, the police department
needed to continue making "fundamental, meaningful change, so that people aren't
afraid that the police are going to shoot them."
</P>
<P>
	   Vallone, a Democrat, said the city council had budgeted funds for that
purpose and "even the mayor is recognizing that changes have to be made."
</P>
<P>
	   Norman Siegel, executive director of the New York Civil Liberties Union,
told 200 parishioners at a Congregational church in Queens that the Diallo case
was giving new impetus to his group's proposals for police misconduct reform.
</P>
<P>
	   Key provisions of the plan would make federal and state funding for local
police contingent on the police meeting strict performance standards in
community relations and create a permanent special prosecutor to handle police
brutality incidents.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to seeking a criminal investigation to determine whether
Diallo's civil rights were violated, he said the NYCLU intends to sue the city
on grounds that poor training and racial stereotyping led to the shooting.
</P>
<P>
	   Also Sunday, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, seeking the Democratic
nomination for U.S. Senate, urged New Yorkers not to let the verdict divide
them.
</P>
<P>
	   Whatever the result of a Justice Department inquiry, "we must reach across
those lines of mistrust and division and join to ensure that no tragedy like
this ever happens again to anyone's son or daughter," she told several hundred
people at a national Dominican-American conference at City College.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-28-00 0115 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000228.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Christian Democrats Lose Vote  </HEADLINE>
   By PAUL GEITNER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BERLIN (AP) -- Voters chastised Germany's Christian Democrats in the first
electoral test since a slush fund scandal exploded around former Chancellor
Helmut Kohl and his party.
</P>
<P>
	   However, the losses were not as bad as the battered conservatives feared.
</P>
<P>
	   Polls from late last year -- before the scandal -- showed the Christian
Democrats would easily oust the center-left coalition in the northern state of
Schleswig-Holstein, continuing a string of statehouse victories at the expense
of Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's Social Democrats.
</P>
<P>
	   Instead, support for the Christian Democrats fell in Sunday's voting for the
state legislature to 35 percent, from 37 percent in the last election four years
ago, according to projections. Because the legislators elect the governor, the
results mean Social Democratic Gov. Heide Simonis will hold onto her job for a
third term.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, challenger Volker Ruehe's showing was enough to keep alive his
behind-the-scenes campaign to take over the national party at a convention in
April.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We lost because of this scandal,'' he told German television. ``But I'm
proud that we've been able to ... connect with our voters and avoid a
catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Starting now I'm a federal politician again.''
</P>
<P>
	   Current party chairman Wolfgang Schaeuble, who faced an internal rebellion
over his handling of the scandal, announced Feb. 16 he would not seek
re-election in order to allow his party a ``new beginning.''
</P>
<P>
	   Angela Merkel, the party's general secretary, is considered the
front-runner, but is opposed by right-wingers because of her more progressive
stance on social issues and roots in former communist East Germany.
</P>
<P>
	   Party leaders are scheduled to vote for a new chairman March 20.
</P>
<P>
	   Kohl has admitted hiding millions in undeclared, and therefore illegal,
campaign contributions and refuses to name the sources, leading to speculation
about possible influence peddling. Parliament and prosecutors have targeted Kohl
for investigation.
</P>
<P>
	   The Christian Democrats are ``out of the bottom of the valley,'' Merkel told
a news conference in Berlin, noting that the results were less punishing than
had been predicted. ``It's back in step and will naturally continue to fight.''
</P>
<P>
	   Early results showed the Social Democrats garnering 43 percent, up from 40
percent in 1996, while their coalition partner, the environmentalist Greens,
dropped to 6 percent from 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Social Democratic party secretary Franz Muenterfering hailed the showing as
a vote of renewed confidence in Schroeder's government as well. A series of
local defeats last year cost Schroeder control of the upper house of parliament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
