<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Group Helps Farmers Find Companions  </HEADLINE>
    By MARGERY BECK Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) -- As if a faltering farm economy weren't enough of a
burden to bear, many in agriculture face another problem -- loneliness.
</P>
<P>
	   Single farmers and ranchers have a tough time meeting other people with
similar interests, say those who would know best.
</P>
<P>
	   "The thing about agriculture, it's usually in an area where you don't have
many neighbors," said Kay Remus, 63, who lived on a ranch outside North Platte
until her husband retired. He died shortly afterward in 1991.
</P>
<P>
	   Widowed and alone with her children grown up and leading their own lives,
Remus became more isolated in the three years following her husband's death.
Then she spotted a newspaper ad for a gathering of people like herself.
</P>
<P>
	   Six years later, Remus chaired the 14th annual national convention of
Singles in Agriculture, held in Lincoln over the weekend. The itinerary was
packed with social events including dances, group meals and tours of local
sites, the Quilt Research Institute and the nation's only tractor-testing
laboratory among them.
</P>
<P>
	   Singles in Agriculture got its start in 1984, after one farmer complained in
a letter to Farm Journal that it was hard for him to meet women interested in
rural life.
</P>
<P>
	   That year, the trade magazine offered to accept names, addresses and short
biographies from single people in the farm industry and put them in touch with
each other.
</P>
<P>
	   It received 2,700 responses, more than the journal could handle.
</P>
<P>
	   In June 1986, 23 people gathered in Peoria, Ill., for Singles in
Agriculture's first meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   The group now has a dozen state and regional chapters with about 1,150
members nationwide, including 55 in Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
	   "We have people from their mid-20s on up," Remus said. "And they come from
all over the country -- even in places where there isn't a chapter."
</P>
<P>
	   The group's national chairman, Morris Bilskie of Chicago, spent much of his
life working for ConAgra, which transferred him around the country 11 times.
</P>
<P>
	   The mobile lifestyle left him little time to date, much less marry.
</P>
<P>
	   "I met and dated some great gals along the way, but ultimately we ended up
going our own ways," Bilskie said.
</P>
<P>
	   Although about 50 of the group's members have met and married each other,
the organization is not a dating service, members insist. Rather, it's a support
group that gives isolated members events to attend year-round and
"long-distance" neighbors they can depend on.
</P>
<P>
	   "Members can really count on each other in good times and in bad --
especially in times of tragedy," Bilskie said. "It's like a chain reaction. The
information gets out pretty quick."
</P>
<P>
	   One of the oldest members at 74, Mary Ellen Maschmeier of Turpin, Okla., has
taken a lead in the organization, serving twice as the Oklahoma chapter
president in her seven years as a member. She serves on the group's national
board.
</P>
<P>
	   "You'll will notice if you look around that everybody is so happy to see
each other," she said, sweeping the Lincoln hotel lobby with an outstretched
arm.
</P>
<P>
	   "Farm life is a lonely life if you don't have people you can count on."
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Singles in Agriculture can be reached at 402-896-5419 or 815-443-2002.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 0130 </TRAILER>
