<DOCNO> APW20000228.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 01:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jazz singer struggles, keeps her dream alive  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - A low hum resonates from the capacity crowd at the
Village Vanguard. Snippets of conversation mix with murmured drink orders in the
triangle-shaped basement room that was home to the likes of Charlie "Bird"
Parker and Miles Davis.
<P>
	   With its pictures of John Coltrane and Roland Kirk on the walls, this is the
place where jazz performers dream of taking the stage.
</P>
<P>
	   Teri Thornton is one of those dreamers, has been since she decided as a
little girl in Detroit that jazz would be the soundtrack of her life. Her dream
took her to critical acclaim as a singer 40 years ago; then through three failed
marriages, near-oblivion as a performer and bouts with alcoholism, depression
and cancer; and finally back into the spotlight as winner of one of jazz's most
prestigious awards.
</P>
<P>
	   "I just know that there's nothing else for me to do," said Thornton. "God
gave me this talent and I knew he meant for me to do something with it and I
just couldn't give up."
</P>
<P>
	   And she hasn't. After years of taking whatever small singing jobs she could
get - and even a stint as a taxi driver - Thornton released "I'll Be Easy to
Find" on Verve Records last year, her first release since the early '60s.
</P>
<P>
	   On a recent night, after the band members have done their solos, the
saxophonist reaches for the microphone.
</P>
<P>
	   "Ladies and Gentleman - Teri Thornton."
</P>
<P>
	   The black sequins on her beret catch some light and sparkle as Thornton
slowly makes her way onstage, flanked by a man who holds her arm in support. She
sinks onto her chair, a long, dark, animal-print shirt hanging off her gaunt
frame.
</P>
<P>
	   This is night three of a six-night gig at the Vanguard, with Thornton doing
two sets a night. The mother of three and grandmother looks frail.
</P>
<P>
	   Thornton was diagnosed with bladder cancer in 1997. Her treatment -
chemotherapy, radiation, and finally surgery - has been exhausting. Now she has
painful blood clots in her legs that make walking difficult.
</P>
<P>
	   But there's no sign of illness in her voice when she starts singing. The
low-pitched sound is true as Thornton doles out bits of wisdom to an
appreciative audience.
</P>
<P>
	   "He who is wise never tries to revise what is past and gone," she sings in
"Devil May Care."
</P>
<P>
	   It was never supposed to be this difficult to get a big break for Thornton,
now a gracious, elegant woman of 65 with a wide smile and smoky voice.
</P>
<P>
	   An only child, she grew up in a house filled with music. Her grandmother
sang in church, and her mother had a radio show. Her mother wanted Thornton to
become a classical pianist but supported her decision to sing jazz, even making
sure Thornton saw all the big-name musicians who passed through town.
</P>
<P>
	   "My mother would think it was so important for me to see them, she'd kind of
snatch me off the schoolgrounds" to go watch the greats of the day, the singer
recalled.
</P>
<P>
	   She started performing in the 1950s and made her way to Chicago. The Windy
City was good to her, with plenty of work and plenty of friends in the jazz
scene. She worked in Canada, too, then went east to New York in 1960.
</P>
<P>
	   In the Big Apple it was instant luck, Thornton said. The day of her arrival,
she went to look for a friend at a jazz club and ended up taking the stage for a
song.
</P>
<P>
	   Her performance impressed a woman in the audience who helped get her a job
singing on national television. TV led to club dates, and an introduction by
some jazz friends to a record company led to a contract.
</P>
<P>
	   "Devil May Care" was released in 1961 on Riverside Records, followed by
"Somewhere in the Night," the theme for the television show "Naked City," in
1962 on Dauntless, and "Open Highway" on Columbia in 1963.
</P>
<P>
	   But despite critical acclaim, Thornton's career never came up to speed. Soon
even the club dates began drying up.
</P>
<P>
	   "It was the kind of thing where you're too little to be big and too big to
be little," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Plus, like the song says, the times they were a-changing. The '60s were the
age of rock 'n' roll, and Thornton was a jazz singer.
</P>
<P>
	   "I really didn't fit in," she said, recalling that even when she tried to
take to the new music, she was ignored by producers at Columbia Records.
</P>
<P>
	   "They had decided what kind of material I should do and they ... wouldn't
let me go over the line," Thornton said. "I always liked rock 'n' roll ... and I
could have performed it, but they refused to let me do that. So I wound up off
the label."
</P>
<P>
	   Thornton stayed in New York until 1975, singing the occasional gig,
sometimes living off the kindness of friends. She moved to Los Angeles to be
near her son after her ex-husband would not let the boy return from a visit.
</P>
<P>
	   It was in LA she was reduced to driving a cab. "Unfortunately there wasn't
very much work out there for me," she recalled.
</P>
<P>
	   She got some singing jobs, she said, but "it was just kind of from one job
to the next and one paycheck to the next."
</P>
<P>
	   Her return to New York with her son in 1983 didn't make things any better.
Her old jazz friends had drifted away or didn't want to see her. "I didn't know
how I was going to make it here. I wasn't about to drive a cab in this town,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Living in an apartment above a bar, she began drowning her troubles in
alcohol. She remembers waking up in the morning facing "my own alcoholic
breath." She thought of suicide but decided that she couldn't leave her son,
then 14.
</P>
<P>
	   And once she decided she was going to live, she said, life started looking
up. She stopped drinking and sang with small jazz bands, work that was steady if
not spectacular.
</P>
<P>
	   "There would be lean times, but I could always maintain," she said. "I could
never feel like I had a whole lot of bad luck because there were so many things
that were good in the realm of that bad luck."
</P>
<P>
	   But the good was hard to find in the summer of 1998. Thornton was recovering
from surgery after having been diagnosed with cancer the year before.
</P>
<P>
	   When her manager Suizi Reynolds called and asked her if she wanted to enter
a singing competition, it seemed like a joke. Especially when Thornton found out
it wasn't just any contest but the Thelonius Monk International Jazz
Competition.
</P>
<P>
	   An age limit that would have made Thornton ineligible had been dropped, and
it would be the perfect showcase for her. Thornton agreed even though she wasn't
sure she was well enough.
</P>
<P>
	   Her manager sent in a CD of Thornton's songs, and she was chosen as one of
the five finalists to perform live in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
	   Thornton spent the week before the contest lying down to conserve energy. It
paid off. According to published accounts, she tore the house down with her
rendition of "I'll Be Easy to Find."
</P>
<P>
	   Recalling her reaction when she was announced as winner, Thornton said, "I
was weak in the knees. ... It was just so heady. I still experience it over and
over again."
</P>
<P>
	   Does she wonder about the life she might have had if stardom had come during
her first go-round? A little, but Thornton is philosophical.
</P>
<P>
	   "It didn't happen then. The life that I had, as bad as may it seem to
somebody else, it's still good," she said. "There's a lot of growing in the
process and I think that you're not ready until you're ready."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-28-00 0132 </TRAILER>
