<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 01:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manmade Landmark Gets Facelift  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   AP Photo WX101
By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON Associated Press Writer-
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Looking straight up from the Capitol Rotunda's stone
floor, the circular white-plastic shape resembles a giant powdered doughnut, its
hole framing a painting of George Washington serenely presiding over the
heavens.
</P>
<P>
	   It's a surreal vision, almost as if Christo, the Bulgarian-born artist who
wraps famous structures like the Reichstag in Berlin, had left his mark on the
preeminent symbol of the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   But there has been no art attack on Capitol Hill. ``This is serious business
for us,'' says James Ellison, an assistant to the Architect of the Capitol, even
as he concedes that the rotunda now looks ``like Christo had struck.''
</P>
<P>
	   The architect's office is engaged in the first phase of an ambitious $44
million rehabilitation project to reverse the effects of decades of seeping
water, rust and layer upon layer of paint that has accumulated since the Capitol
dome was completed just after the Civil War,
</P>
<P>
	   That means identifying and documenting hundreds of cracks and breaks in the
dome's cast iron plates and scraping away toxic lead-based paint.
</P>
<P>
	   The plastic doughnut is the visible layer of a four-layer custom-designed
safety netting deployed, just below the Washington painting in the eye of the
dome, to keep debris from falling on the heads of people below. That allows the
rotunda to remain open for tourists and congressional ceremonies while work goes
on above.
</P>
<P>
	   Behind the outer plastic, Ellison explains, is a 3 1/2-inch diamond netting
able to withstand a 500-pound impact. Behind that is a finer  3/4-inch webbing.
And behind that is plastic sheeting to contain the dust.
</P>
<P>
	   Initially assembled on the rotunda floor, it took three weeks to hoist in
place. ``It's there simply in the event a piece of iron should fall, Ellison
said, adding that the only feasible alternative was to build a scaffold from the
floor up.
</P>
<P>
	   Weighing nearly 9 million pounds, the Capitol dome rises 287 feet from
ground level to the feathered head of the Statue of Freedom, which has crowned
it since 1863. The dome, which replaced an earlier structure, was the finishing
touch of an extension in the mid-19th century that added new House and Senate
wings to the original building.
</P>
<P>
	   The office of the Architect of the Capitol says it's probably ``the most
famous manmade landmark in America.''
</P>
<P>
	   Although painted to resemble the white marble of the new wings, the dome is
actually cast iron, a material chosen for its relatively light weight, low cost
and ease of fabrication. The dome was designed, as were the new wings, by Thomas
U. Walter. Army Capt. Montgomery Meigs of the Corps of Engineers ran the
building project even as he feuded with Walter for control.
</P>
<P>
	   The current crop of engineers and architects has no fault to find with their
work.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Those guys 140 years ago did a superb job of designing and building it --
and it has stood the test of time,'' Ellison said.
</P>
<P>
	   The cracks and breaks are essentially surface abrasions. ``We're not talking
about structural problems,'' Ellison said. ``The dome is perfectly safe.''
</P>
<P>
	   Work on the second phase of the project could begin in October 2001 if
Congress provides the required $37 million, the largest part of the overall $44
million cost.
</P>
<P>
	   That will require a far more elaborate support structure inside the rotunda,
built out from the main stone base of the dome to support scaffolding. The
rotunda will be closed for three months while it is installed.
</P>
<P>
	   When in place it will be used as a base to repair the cracks and breaks in
the iron; ease paint removal and recoating with a modern, non-toxic paint; and
install an array of mechanical improvements, including a new ventilation system
to prevent condensation and make the dome's interior a drip-free zone.
</P>
<P>
	   All of this must be done while carefully protecting the canopy 180 feet
above the rotunda floor that supports the eye-of-the-dome painting that the
nation's founder raised to glory.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Lawrence L. Knutson has covered the White House, Congress
and Washington history for more than 30 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 0137 </TRAILER>
