<HEADLINE> Alleged Prison Camp Heads on Trial  </HEADLINE>
   By JEROME SOCOLOVSKY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) -- The discovery of battered and emaciated
Bosnian inmates at Omarska prison camp in 1992 marked a turning point in
international willingness to intervene in the Balkan conflict.
</P>
<P>
	   Today, the Bosnian Serbs who allegedly ran the detention camp were scheduled
to go on trial. Prosecutors say hundreds of prisoners were murdered, raped and
tortured at the camp in northern Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
	   Miroslav Kvocka, Milojica Kos and Mlado Radic are charged with war crimes
and crimes against humanity for presiding over the atrocities at Omarska. A
fourth defendant, Zoran Zigic, is accused of torturing and murdering prisoners.
</P>
<P>
	   A conviction on any count at the tribunal carries a maximum life sentence,
although 40 years is the stiffest sentence imposed so far. All four defendants
have pleaded innocent.
</P>
<P>
	   The Yugoslav war crimes tribunal was established in 1993 amid the global
outcry following the discovery of the camps.
</P>
<P>
	   The Omarska case is the first dealing directly with what prosecutors
characterize as ``a system of concentration camps'' as a deliberate strategy to
drive out Muslims and Croats from the area in order to create an ethnically pure
Serb state.
</P>
<P>
	   Serb forces swept through the Prijedor region of northern Bosnia at the
outset of the 1992-95 war and herded more than 6,000 non-Serbs into Omarska and
the nearby Keraterm and Trnopolje camps.
</P>
<P>
	   In a pretrial brief, prosecutors Grant Niemann, a former Australian war
crimes investigator, and Brenda Hollis, a retired U.S. Air Force colonel,
painted a horrifying picture of the camps.
</P>
<P>
	   New arrivals were beaten with batons and rifle butts and jammed into
stiflingly hot rooms with no beds and meager sanitary facilities, prosecutors
say. Hundreds allegedly died as a result of the treatment.
</P>
<P>
	   At Omarska, a converted iron ore mine, the dead bodies piled up on a daily
basis, the prosecutors wrote.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Battered corpses were visible virtually every morning before they were
loaded onto trucks and removed from the camp,'' the brief says.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors hold Kvocka responsible for much of what happened at Omarska,
describing him as commander through June 1992 and later deputy commander. Kos
and Radic, alleged shift commanders, ordered guards to beat prisoners and
sometimes participated themselves, prosecutors maintain.
</P>
<P>
	   The three men, the brief says, ``exercised the power of life and death over
the detainees.''
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors also maintain the commanders bear responsibility for atrocities
at the two satellite camps because they ``actively participated in a common,
widespread and repressive system designed for the persecution of non-Serbs.''
</P>
<P>
	   The U.N. tribunal has convicted 13 Serbs, Croats and Muslims of war crimes
and crimes against humanity. Dozens of suspects are in custody at its seaside
detention center, while key figures still at large include Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic, former Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic and military
chief Ratko Mladic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 0202 </TRAILER>
