<HEADLINE> Clinton Hosts Governors Minus Bush  </HEADLINE>
   By ANNE GEARAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton reflected on his waning days in office
and asked politicians who will serve after him not to waste a rare moment of
national economic prosperity and promise.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In 11 months I will be a private citizen,'' Clinton said as he toasted
most of the nation's governors at the White House. ``Most of you will still be
serving. Think of that,'' and use the opportunity wisely.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton, who claims much of the credit for the economic boom that coincided
with his elevation from Arkansas governor to president, meets with the state
leaders three times this week, including a discussion session scheduled today at
the White House.
</P>
<P>
	   The president was likely to focus on the successful economy in his annual
address to the National Governors' Association, but would also touch on the
problem of rising oil prices, White House spokesman Jim Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton also planned to address Democratic governors separately tonight.
</P>
<P>
	   He will hear ideas about how to keep the good times going, but he will
likely hear a few complaints, too. Many of the 50 governors worry that the
federal government will stymie states' individual innovations in a variety of
areas, including health care and taxation.
</P>
<P>
	   Utah Gov. Michael Leavitt, a Republican and chairman of the bipartisan
governors' association, said the group wants Clinton to hear its debate over
governors' roles in keeping state economies prosperous.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Much of that will reflect our desire that the federal government not
attempt to pre-empt our activities in that regard,'' Leavitt said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   The governors' four-day meeting is centered on the findings in a new
economic report prepared for the group. The report, a copy of which was sent to
the White House weeks ago, concluded that states must aggressively refashion
their governments if they want to continue to compete.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton, who rose to national prominence as governor of Arkansas in the
1980s, toasted a smaller-than-expected group of 34 governors Sunday night and
noted that this is the 200th anniversary of the presidential election of another
former governor, Thomas Jefferson of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
	   Jefferson embraced flexibility in governance, and Clinton urged governors to
do the same as they contend with the challenges of unprecedented prosperity.
</P>
<P>
	   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who wants to follow Jefferson and Clinton into
the White House, was one of those who missed the menu of grilled Arctic char and
rock shrimp served on the Reagan china. Bush was campaigning for president in
Seattle. His brother, Florida Gov. Jeb Bush, was in Washington for the
governors' conference but skipped the White House dinner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
