<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teen Drama Group Teaches Abstinence  </HEADLINE>
    By LOUINN LOTA Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A scene from "No Way to Treat a Lady" opens with Marie,
a pregnant girl, speaking of love and loss.
</P>
<P>
	   "He was older, and he was so good-looking," Marie explains to the audience.
"He told me that if two people really love each other, they shouldn't be afraid
to show it to each other."
</P>
<P>
	   A voice answers her sternly.
</P>
<P>
	   "They can show it to each other," it says. "Too bad some girls like you,
Marie, are ignorant enough to think that the only way a guy thinks you can show
him love is through sex."
</P>
<P>
	   The dialogue is spoken as part of the performance of a Southern California
troupe of teen-agers who teach sexual abstinence, resistance to peer pressure
and cultural tolerance to thousands of urban students through
true-life-situation theater.
</P>
<P>
	   Every actor in the Phantom Projects troupe has faced the pressures or
situations they portray on stage. After each play, the sixth- to eighth-grade
audience members can speak candidly about their own problems.
</P>
<P>
	   "The center of all of our shows is that everything comes down to
self-control," said Steve Cisneros, the group's producer-director. "It's natural
to have feelings of wanting to have sex. It's natural to be intolerant to what
others are and do. The actors are going through these same peer pressures
themselves at their schools."
</P>
<P>
	   The plays have been so effective that schools from New York to Arizona have
asked for the troupe.
</P>
<P>
	   In California, about 75 schools in Los Angeles, Orange and Santa Barbara
counties have booked the shows over four years.
</P>
<P>
	   Another 15 schools, most of them Christian parochial, have asked for the
sexual abstinence play, "No Way to Treat a Lady."
</P>
<P>
	   The actors, who are from half a dozen schools, have a 3.7 grade point
average, rehearse on weekends and receive permission to miss class on
performance days. Some schools give them credit for their work.
</P>
<P>
	   While the actors are unpaid, Cisneros, 21, remains thousands of dollars in
credit-card debt from staging the productions. The troupe charges up to $550 for
three performances at a location, but that doesn't meet expenses.
</P>
<P>
	   Phantom Projects began when Cisneros was age 17 and a student of Bruce
Gevirtzman, an English teacher at La Mirada High School, about 20 miles from Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
	   Gevirtzman, a playwright since 1976, wrote "No Way To Treat a Lady" and
other works now performed by the group.
</P>
<P>
	   Teens "should be able to depend on family, to always know that they are
loved," Gevirtzman said. "But that's not the case anymore. There are a lot of
substitutes for the love they're not getting: violence, sex, drugs."
</P>
<P>
	   Tired of seeing many such misguided teens at his school, Cisneros believed
he and his peers could reach out to urban middle-schoolers and teach them
survival tools for their turbulent years.
</P>
<P>
	   At a recent performance of "No Way to Treat a Lady," students raved about
the life lessons it offered. They asked that their last names not be used,
worried that their use might link them with problems addressed in the play.
</P>
<P>
	   "I learned some interesting and important facts about sex and the effects it
could have on my life that I didn't know," said Jason, 14. "I've been pressured
to have sex with someone more times than I can remember. Sometimes it's so hard
to resist."
</P>
<P>
	   Veronica, another middle-schooler, said the show "almost made me, cry just
because it's such a scary world -- STDs, AIDS, pregnancy."
</P>
<P>
	   "My mind was set to not have sex until I'm married," she said, "but now it's
written in stone."
</P>
<P>
	   Some parents have been unhappy with the frankness of the troupe's plays.
One, who identified himself as a former actor in a Christian drama company,
praised the cast in a comment sheet but also said "they are not qualified to
field students' questions on this sensitive subject."
</P>
<P>
	   But Cisneros defended the effort.
</P>
<P>
	   "I wanted to combine my passions for theater and the power to teach," he
said. "This is the way I could do it."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 0205 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
