<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Boxing Officials Like Chances  </HEADLINE>
By ED SCHUYLER JR.-
AP Boxing Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	MASHANTUCKET, Conn. (AP) -- With a team of 12 boxers who have international
tournament experience and were toughened in the Olympic trials and box-offs,
officials and coaches are feeling good about them qualifying for Sydney.
</P>
<P>
	`Twelve guys are going to Sydney, I believe that,'' head coach Tom Mustin said
after the U.S. Olympic team was determined in the box-offs Thursday through
Saturday at Foxwoods Casino.
</P>
<P>
	Those 12 boxers now must compete with boxers from North, South and Central
America and the Caribbean for 54 spots in the Olympic tournament at Sydney in
September.
</P>
<P>
	Many of the box-offs between Olympic trials champions and winners of the
losers' bracket in that double-elimination tournament were hotly contested.
</P>
<P>
	``In three days, you got to see the best boxers in the United States and I
believe some of the best boxers in the world,'' said Gary Toney, president of
USA Boxing.
</P>
<P>
	There are four world champions on the team -- Brian Viloria of Waipahu, Hawaii,
106 pounds; Ricardo Juarez of Houston, 125; Michael Simms Jr. of Sacramento,
Calif., 178; and Michael Bennett of Chicago, 201.
</P>
<P>
	Mustin noted that since the 1996 Olympics, which U.S. boxers won one gold and
five bronze medals, ``we've sent boxers to more tournaments. It gives them the
feel of having to win more than once and how to box against different styles.''
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. goal now is to qualify all the boxers in the first of three Americas
qualifying tournaments at Tampa, Fla., March 27-April 1. There, the 20 boxers to
reach the finals in 10 weight classes from 106 to 178 and the winners of the
heavyweight and super heavyweight classes will go to the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
	Those who don't qualify in Tampa will get another chance April 27-22 at Mexico
City, where 22 more boxers will earn trips to Sydney. The final 10 Olympians
from the Americas will be the 10 winners of the weight classes from 106 through
178 in competition May 23-28 at Buenos Aires.
</P>
<P>
	As the world's No. 1 team, Cuba is exempt from qualifying.
</P>
<P>
	The other U.S. team members are Jose Navarro of Los Angeles, 112; Clarence
Vinson of Washington, D.C., 119; Marshall Martinez of Vista, Calif., 132;
Ricardo Williams Jr. of Cincinnati, 139; Dante Craig of Cincinnati, 147; Jermain
Taylor of Little Rock, Ark., 156; Jeff Lacy of St. Petersburg, Fla., 165; and
Calvin Brock of Charlotte, N.C., super heavyweight.
</P>
<P>
	``We'll have three weeks of training camp getting ready for the Americas,''
Mustin said. ``We have a lot of work to do, working on keeping hands up, staying
of the corner, staying off the ropes.''
</P>
<P>
	Mustin also said there would computer scoring of sparring sessions so that the
boxers would be able to see what blows count and to work at getting credit for
punches.
</P>
<P>
	``The Olympics are the big one,'' said Mustin, who turned 54 on Sunday. He was
head coach for the 1993 and 1999 world championship teams and the 1991 and 1995
Pan American Games squads. He is an assistant manager of packaging for the
Tacoma News Tribune.
</P>
<P>
	Assisting Mustin will be 46-year-old Israel Acosta of Milwaukee and 45-
year-old Candelario Lopez of San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
	Israel Acosta, who works for the Housing Authority for the City of Milwaukee
was an assistant coach for 1999 world championships team. He was an elite
amateur boxers for 12 years and U.S. champion in 1977. His record was 340-16.
</P>
<P>
	Lopez, a police sergeant, was an assistant coach for the 1999 Pan Am Games
team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 0222 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
