<DOCNO> APW20000228.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 02:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Dreams Born, Die in S.C.  </HEADLINE>
By PETE IACOBELLI-
AP Sports Writer-
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- Anne Marie Lauck saw an Olympic dream born as her own
was dying.
</P>
<P>
	Leading Saturday's marathon trials for nearly 17 miles, Lauck was starting to
think she might hang on for her second straight Olympic berth.
</P>
<P>
	But just past the 20-mile mark, little-known Christine Clark pulled alongside,
looking fresher and stronger down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
	``She took off and I said, `There's goes our team,''' Lauck said.
</P>
<P>
	Clark's surprising 2-hour, 33-minute, 31-second trip -- the Anchorage
pathologist had never run faster than 2:40 before -- made her America's lone
marathon representative for the Sydney Games in September.
</P>
<P>
	She could not better the Olympic standard of 2:33. Because of USA Track and
Field rules, America will send a one-woman team for the first time in five
Olympiads.
</P>
<P>
	``When you're growing up, you always dream about a moment like this,'' Clark
said. ``But to actually accomplish it, that's so unfathomable to me.''
</P>
<P>
	Only Libbie Hickman and Kristy Johnston reached the Games ``A'' standard before
the trials. But Hickman finished 6 minutes behind in eighth on a humid Southern
day where temperatures on the street hit 80 degrees. Johnston was runner-up,
almost 2 minutes in back.
</P>
<P>
	Had Clark broken 2:33 and no else dipped under that time, then Johnston and
Hickman also would have gotten tickets to Sydney. Had the top three finishers
gone faster than 2:33, all would have gone.
</P>
<P>
	The weather was the determining factor. The sweltering conditions slowed the
170-woman field -- 141 finished -- and very few ran personal bests.
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very disappointed about not making the team,'' Johnston, the fifth-place
finisher in 1996, said after running 2:35:36. ``It's very hard. I will try and
fight some of the rules, but do it in a positive way so I don't take anything
away from the first-place finisher. I don't know if that means going to the IAAF
...''
</P>
<P>
	Lauck held on for third, collapsing as she crossed the finish line from the
brutal pace she set for nearly two-thirds of the race. She was given fluids and
appeared chipper and smiling at a postrace awards ceremony a few hours later.
</P>
<P>
	Walter Hickman, Libbie's husband, spoke for his disappointed wife, who ran
2:39:57.
</P>
<P>
	``The last six miles were like a death march for her,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	Craig Mossback, executive director of USATF, defended the choice of Columbia as
the site, saying that in February the city's weather usually approximates the
conditions the marathoners would be expected to face at Sydney in September.
</P>
<P>
	``Eighty-six degrees turned out to be about 25 degrees warmer than you'll
probably get in Sydney,'' Mossback said..
</P>
<P>
	``The story of the race is that a woman ran 7 minutes faster than her personal
best. Today, it was extremely fair and it was extremely unfair.''
</P>
<P>
	Clark came into the race the 22nd-fastest qualifier and let Lauck, 10th-place
finisher at the 1996 Olympics, set the pace through the first 20 miles. Once in
the lead, like unknown winner Jenny Spangler four years ago, Clark pushed to the
finish line.
</P>
<P>
	Joan Benoit Samuelson, 42, the American record-holder at 2:21:21 and 1984
Olympic gold medalist, placed ninth at 2:39:59, her best finish in six years.
</P>
<P>
	Many runners wore red, white and blue ribbons on their race singlets in protest
of the Confederate flag atop the Statehouse, but no problems relating to that
situation were reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 0226 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
