<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 02:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wind Not at the America's Cup  </HEADLINE>
By BERNIE WILSON-
AP Sports Writer-
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUCKLAND, New Zealand (AP) -- Everyone's talking about the weather at the
America's Cup. As usual, there's nothing anyone can do about it.
</P>
<P>
	Sailing's biggest extravaganza has lost its steam. Not on the waterfront, where
tens of thousands of fans turn out to send off the racing yachts in the morning
and the bars remain packed long into the night.
</P>
<P>
	Out on the water, it's another story. In the last 10 days, three races have
been postponed because the wind hasn't blown with enough gusto to push the
75-foot sailboats around the course on the fluky, flaky Hauraki Gulf.
</P>
<P>
	That, coupled with four lay days built into the schedule dictated by TV rights
holders, and the momentum seem shot. Team New Zealand's speedy Black Magic has
routed Italy's Luna Rossa in the three races that have gone off, and a 5-0 sweep
seems imminent -- whenever they can squeeze in the next two races needed to keep
the America's Cup in Auckland.
</P>
<P>
	Race 4 in the best-of-9 series had to be abandoned Sunday, and the forecast for
Tuesday doesn't look good.
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to Fiji for five days and I'll be back for Race 4 on Sunday,''
joked eliminated American skipper Paul Cayard.
</P>
<P>
	He might not be far off the mark.
</P>
<P>
	Because of a high pressure system that's parked itself over Auckland, this may
be the America's Cup that never ends.
</P>
<P>
	``The centers are close to us so we have breeze to the north and the south, and
not much here,'' said Bob Rice, the New Englander who works as chief
meteorologist for Team New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
	Even without the high pressure, the wind in Auckland, the self-described ``City
of Sails,'' is an interesting phenomenon. In what's called the ``Battle of the
Breezes,'' the southwesterlies coming off the Tasman Sea and the northeasterlies
off the Pacific try to dominate each other over the Hauraki Gulf. If they cancel
each other out, they also kill the racing.
</P>
<P>
	``It's entirely logical,'' Rice said Monday. ``The idea of some sort of evil
spirit living on the Hauraki Gulf ... it's just weather doing weather things.
When you have all this water and land terrain and so forth, you have things like
this going on. It's perfectly natural.
</P>
<P>
	``It's like if you put Los Angeles 10 miles over from New York. Both of them
have their own regime.''
</P>
<P>
	The tame winds have even whipped up controversy. Race committee chairman Harold
Bennett was accused of favoring the Kiwis when he abandoned Race 3 on Thursday,
saying the light wind was too shifty toward the top of the course. The Italians,
whose boat is believed to be strong in light air, wanted to race so badly that
they cruised up and down in the starting area with sails hoisted.
</P>
<P>
	Bennett dismissed the suggestions that his decisions to abandon races have been
influenced by Team New Zealand, calling them ``slurs on my integrity.''
</P>
<P>
	Bennett did admit that he'll probably have more gray hairs by the time this
thing finally ends.
</P>
<P>
	``I mean, it's pretty unsettling for everyone involved, not just the crews, but
us,'' he said. ``It's difficult.''
</P>
<P>
	Even Black Magic tactician Brad Butterworth agreed with one of the criticisms
of sailing.
</P>
<P>
	``Light days are pretty much like you see it on TV -- it's like watching the
grass grow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	Said Kiwi grinder Craig Monk: ``The final 60 minutes before a race can be
called off is the worst. That hour always feels like six hours.''
</P>
<P>
	Event organizer Tony Thomas said the finals couldn't have started much earlier
because they were preceded by the four-month challenger elimination series,
capped with Luna Rossa's dramatic win over AmericaOne.
</P>
<P>
	What's been griping to some is that there has been plenty of wind on some lay
days, the days off built into the schedule.
</P>
<P>
	But Thomas said he was bound by TV contracts and couldn't move racing to
scheduled non-race days unless the series was at risk of going beyond its March
9 deadline.
</P>
<P>
	``This is the biggest event ever in New Zealand,'' America's Cup spokesman
Murray Taylor said. ``We're in no hurry for it to end.''
</P>
<P>
	At this rate, it might not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 0228 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000228.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 02:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clarke Beats Tiger at Match Play  </HEADLINE>
    By TIM DAHLBERG AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CARLSBAD, Calif. (AP) -- Darren Clarke hardly seemed the type to be at La
Costa playing Tiger Woods for $1 million. Overweight and underhyped, smoking a
cigar between shots, he looked more like he belonged on a stool in the
neighborhood pub.
</P>
<P>
	   Only the night before, he had to be told his Match Play Championship final
against Woods was 36 holes, not 18 as he had thought.
</P>
<P>
	   Yet there he was on Sunday, chugging down the fairway after another
perfectly placed tee shot. There he was, keeping the pressure on Woods with iron
shots snuggled close to the pins.
</P>
<P>
	   And there he was, accepting a handshake from Woods on the 33rd hole of the
day after doing what everyone else failed to do all week -- beat the world's
best player in the format he plays best.
</P>
<P>
	   "He did to Tiger Woods what Tiger Woods does to everybody else," swing guru
Butch Harmon said.
</P>
<P>
	   The most unlikely looking challenger to Woods might have been the one least
intimidated by the best golfer in the world.
</P>
<P>
	   It was Clarke keeping the pressure on Woods, who could do little as Clarke
made four birdies in five holes during the front nine of the afternoon round to
turn an even match into a rout.
</P>
<P>
	   This time, Woods sputtered when he tried to mount one of his famous
comebacks, and Clarke became the first full-time European Tour player to win on
U.S. soil since Lee Westwood won in New Orleans in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   "Darren just flat outplayed me," Woods said. "He played beautifully."
</P>
<P>
	   The fans who turned out for what they thought would be another Woods'
coronation at La Costa found that out early.
</P>
<P>
	   Even when Woods nearly aced the par-3 third hole to go up quickly, Clarke
never seemed intimidated. He came out with five front-nine birdies to start the
morning match and missed only one fairway all day.
</P>
<P>
	   Woods, meanwhile, was making mistakes he didn't make all week. Staying even
after the first 18, he played only 1-under the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
	   "To play as well as that under the circumstances today, against the best
player in the world, is certainly very gratifying," Clarke said.
</P>
<P>
	   Clarke came into the tournament ranked 19th in the world, and he spent much
of the winter working hard on his game under the tutelage of Harmon, who has
coached Woods since he was 16.
</P>
<P>
	   The week before, both players worked with Harmon in Las Vegas. Before
Sunday's final, Harmon was on the practice range working on Woods' swing when
Clarke yelled over to him.
</P>
<P>
	   "Don't bother coming over here, I'm hitting it perfect," he told Harmon.
</P>
<P>
	   The remark was half in jest, but Clarke had it right. He drilled his drives
down the middle of the fairway and put his irons close. When he needed to make
big putts, he drained them.
</P>
<P>
	   He was playing so well, he skipped the driving range, where Woods spent the
45 minutes between rounds. He went up to the clubhouse instead and had a nice
lunch.
</P>
<P>
	   "He was too tired," Harmon said. "He didn't want to go to the range because
he would have had to walk back up that hill again."
</P>
<P>
	   Woods, meanwhile, couldn't find the swing he wanted. He misfired while
trying to get back in the match, leaving a sand shot in the bunker on No. 12,
and Clarke finally closed him out with a two-putt par on the 15th hole.
</P>
<P>
	   "I was just trying to find my golf swing," Woods said. "I did a lot of it
with smoke and mirrors today, with a lot of my hands and timing it well, and
made a lot of putts in the morning just to keep myself in the ballgame."
</P>
<P>
	   Still, the two were even until Clarke rolled in a birdie putt on No. 4 in
the afternoon round, the beginning of a Tiger-like run of four birdies in five
holes that put him 4-up as he walked off the eighth green.
</P>
<P>
	   Clarke, though, figured Woods had one more run left in him.
</P>
<P>
	   "I was expecting Tiger to do a couple of special things and have a go at
me," he said. "I wasn't relaxing any."
</P>
<P>
	   He won't be doing much relaxing in the near future, either. Clarke was
headed to play in the Dubai Desert Classic, and promised Harmon that he would
also dust off the gym equipment in his garage to take off some pounds added over
the winter.
</P>
<P>
	   The added pounds don't come close to the added confidence of beating the top
64 players in the world after a nine-year career that included only five
European tour wins.
</P>
<P>
	   "Confidence-wise, this will be the greatest thing that ever happened to
him," Harmon said. "I saw a Darren Clarke I've never seen before. I knew he was
capable of it. I just never saw him put it together."
</P>
<P>
	   The tournament was sponsored by Andersen Consulting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 0229 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000228.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 02:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jim Carter Wins Tucson Open  </HEADLINE>
    By MEL REISNER AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- The biggest obstacle Jim Carter had to clear was self
doubt.
</P>
<P>
	   Carter, who made his debut on the PGA Tour in 1987 and then went 291
tournaments without a victory, ended the string Sunday when he won the Tucson
Open by making up four shots on third-round leader Tom Scherrer.
</P>
<P>
	   Then, his face streaked with tears, he talked about life as a non-winner.
</P>
<P>
	   "All the players are a great support for each other, but they are kind of
out there beating your brains out. There's no guarantee that you ever get to sit
up here and take home some hardware, so there's tons of doubt," Carter said.
</P>
<P>
	   He said he hit a low point a week ago when he played well, but still missed
the cut in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
	   "I was like, 'Geez, I don't know if I can do it -- maybe it's not supposed
to be for me,"' said Carter, who closed with a 6-under-par 66 that left him two
shots ahead of Scherrer, Chris DiMarco and Jean Van de Velde.
</P>
<P>
	   Instead of quitting, he gave himself a pep talk on the way to Tucson
National, where the former Arizona State golfer won a college tournament in
1984. The previous year, he was the NCAA medalist.
</P>
<P>
	   It was his best result as a pro -- the $540,000 winner's share is about
$80,000 more than Carter earned last year, his best season, and shot him to
sixth on the money list with $580,763.
</P>
<P>
	   His best finish until this event was third four times -- in 1989, 1995, 1996
and 1998 -- and he hadn't had a top 10 finish since last June.
</P>
<P>
	   The field was diluted by the absence of the top stars who played in the
Match Play Championship, but Carter didn't back in. His 19-under 269 matched
David Duval's winning score of two years ago -- the lowest in four years since
the tournament abandoned a two-course format and settled on Tucson National.
</P>
<P>
	   He also beat players of the caliber of Van de Velde, last year's runner-up
at the British Open, and 1996 U.S. Open winner Steve Jones, who bogeyed the last
hole and wound up tied with Rick Fehr for fifth at 272.
</P>
<P>
	   First-round leader Steve Lowery, Woody Austin, Steve Flesch and Kirk
Triplett, who won his first title last week in Los Angeles, were grouped at 273,
with Kevin Sutherland and Ted Purdy at 274.
</P>
<P>
	   Rookie Casey Martin, who has a circulatory disease in his right leg and is,
by court, order, allowed to ride a cart on tour, had his best performance in
five starts. Martin finished with a 71 for a 276 total, and tied seven other
players for 17th.
</P>
<P>
	   Scherrer bogeyed two of the first four holes, but made his second birdie of
the round on the ninth hole and reached 18-under with another birdie on No. 10.
</P>
<P>
	   That was as far as his clubs would take him, and all it did was get him
within one stroke of Carter, who opened a 2-shot lead when he rolled in a 3-foot
birdie putt on the 11th hole.
</P>
<P>
	   "Someone was going to make a run," said Scherrer, who finished with a 72
after three bogeys. He had one in the first three rounds. "I didn't know who it
would be, and it turned out to be Jim. That was a great round of golf he had
today. I knew someone would do it, and I just didn't quite keep pace."
</P>
<P>
	   Carter birdied the first three holes, starting with a 45-foot putt from the
fringe on No. 1, and got to 17-under on the eighth hole with another difficult
birdie -- a chip from 20 feet.
</P>
<P>
	   "Right away, those thoughts jump in your head," he said. "And then you have
to slap yourself around because you can't think like that. I've done that before
-- get all excited -- and it just turns into a mess, so I did a very good job of
keeping my mind empty."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
