<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Here's Sammy: Sosa Late But in Camp  </HEADLINE>
    By RICK GANO AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MESA, Ariz. (AP) -- Late-arriving star player and strong-willed, no-nonsense
manager met for the first time this spring. Hugged, in fact. Even posed for a
picture.
</P>
<P>
	   Sammy Sosa and Don Baylor were lobbing compliments at each other like
batting practice fastballs Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   Sosa, with 129 homers over the last two seasons, will gladly steal more
bases if that's what Baylor wants and the Chicago Cubs need.
</P>
<P>
	   Baylor's initial response to Sosa's being more than a week behind the rest
of the position players was: ``It's a big deal.'' But he softened that stance
Sunday, saying he wasn't upset and that he gave Sosa permission to report two
days after the Feb. 25 deadline because of the flu.
</P>
<P>
	   They both predicted they will get along just fine. Of course, it's still
February.
</P>
<P>
	   ``You hit 66 homers and I don't think you will have any problems with the
guy,'' Baylor said. ``I think we are both after the same thing. That's why I
feel there will not be a problem with a guy who plays every day. And the
magnitude of Sammy Sosa, I'm not getting in the way of that.''
</P>
<P>
	   And Sosa said he would not have any problems with Baylor, whom he called a
``tough guy.''
</P>
<P>
	   In 1993 and 1995, a slimmer Sammy was a 30-steal, 30-homer man with the
Cubs. But then he weighed 198. Now he's up to 230.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Remember, I'm a slugger,'' Sosa said, predicting he can still steal 30
bases, despite the bulk added for power.
</P>
<P>
	   Whatever Baylor asks, Sosa said he will try to provide.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He's a guy who knows how to deal with superstars and I'm willing to come
here and do everything he wants me to do,'' Sosa said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm an employee like everybody else and I'm willing to sacrifice myself to
go out there and win the game.''
</P>
<P>
	   Baylor said he and Sosa exchanged pleasantries throughout the day and would
sit down later and talk. He's said since taking the job he wants Sosa to be a
more all-around player.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We'll have our conversation about what I expect. I think he understands
after all the running we are doing. I want him to hit third in our lineup, be
very productive and take a few more chances,'' Baylor said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There are going to be a lot of guys given the green light to steal a bag
and he will be one of those guys. I'm not stupid either in making him do some
things he's not comfortable in doing.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Through the course of the season, I believe he will be a little more
comfortable with what we are trying to accomplish -- take the extra base, move
runners up. He's a smart player.''
</P>
<P>
	   Sosa took part in just about everything his first day. He hit against real
pitchers Matt Karchner and Rodney Myers and broke three bats. In another session
of batting practice against pitching coordinator Lester Strode, he hit 13 homers
in 31 swings.
</P>
<P>
	   But when it came to doing 10 wind sprints at the end, Sosa had to beg off on
one in the middle to catch his breath. He's in pretty good shape, he said, but
not that good.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I was a little tired on the first day. I'm not going to lie to you,'' Sosa
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Sosa pronounced himself healthy and offered assurances he's ``still hungry''
after two straight years of 60-plus homers.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is a new millennium and a new year and I can't sit down and relax
because I had two great years,'' Sosa said,
</P>
<P>
	   ``I feel like a rookie. I'm never satisfied and I always want to go to the
next level. This is the year I have to go out and put everything together. We
have new coaches, new faces and a new manager.''
</P>
<P>
	   Sosa also said he is not worried about a new contract after his current
four-year, $42.5 million deal expires in two years.
</P>
<P>
	   He denied a report that he might seek $160 million in a new deal.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If I play great, I'll never have a problem going out there and getting a
good contract,'' Sosa said. ``I need to take care of business first and then the
money will be there.'' Notes: 3B Willie Greene became ill during Sunday's
conditioning exercises, was carted off the field and taken to a hospital because
of dehydration. Greene missed the first week of spring training because of
illness in his family.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
