<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 03:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton urges reconciliation between cops and citizens  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Hillary Rodham Clinton urged New Yorkers to reach across
the "trust divide" in the wake of the Diallo verdict but offered no opinion on
whether the case warrants a federal investigation.
<P>
	   "There are still too many people in this city who believe they are
considered guilty just because of the color of their skin, and there are also
too many police officers who believe they are mistrusted because of the color of
their uniforms," Clinton told several hundred people Sunday at a City College
conference on the political concerns of Dominican-Americans.
</P>
<P>
	   She added: "The police must strive for a better understanding of the
communities they serve, and the communities must strive for a better
understanding of the risks that the police face in their service on behalf of us
every day."
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton noted that the U.S. Department of Justice is looking into whether
federal civil rights charges should be brought against the four white officers
who were acquitted of wrongdoing in the shooting of Amadou Diallo, an unarmed
black African immigrant.
</P>
<P>
	   She did not offer an opinion on whether she thought a federal case was
merited, saying: "No matter the outcome of that investigation, there is more for
all of us to do to respond to this tragedy. We must not allow the verdict to
divide New Yorkers. We must reach across those lines of mistrust and division
and join to ensure that no tragedy like this ever happens again."
</P>
<P>
	   She also called for an effort "to recruit and train a police force that
truly reflects the racial and ethnic diversity of this great city. We must
support efforts to expand community policing so that more police officers can
walk the beat and really know people they serve."
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton is running for U.S. Senate against Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
Giuliani's spokesman, Bruce Teitelbaum, bristled at the notion that the police
force needs reforming.
</P>
<P>
	   "Mrs. Clinton is obviously unaware that New York City recently spent over
$10 million on a new recruiting program designed to create a more diverse police
department," he said. "As a result of the plan, the new police class will be the
most diverse ever and will better reflect the ethnic and racial diversity of our
city."
</P>
<P>
	   Teitelbaum did not have the breakdown for the academy's latest class, and
the police department could not immediately provide it. But overall, the force
is about two-thirds white, while the city's population is less than half white.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-28-00 0345 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000228.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 04:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Huddled masses? Not on the new Lower East Side  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - The Lower East Side of Manhattan is famous for its
tenements, its pastrami sandwiches and its proud history as the first American
home to millions of immigrants.
<P>
	   Until recently, trendy nightclubs, posh art galleries and $3,000-a-month
studio apartments were definitely NOT part of the picture.
</P>
<P>
	   But with a little help from New York's through-the-roof real estate market,
the old Lower East Side has become something its former residents would never
have recognized - a hip downtown hotspot.
</P>
<P>
	   The narrow streets where vendors once pushed carts piled high with clothing,
vegetables, household goods and even eyeglasses are now home to scores of bars,
cafes and glitzy shops that might look more at home in upscale SoHo or artsy
Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
	   "Now it's pretty much a well-known fact that if you want to move to a really
cool, hip neighborhood, you're going to move down here," said artist Peter
Marco, who sells brightly colored Keith Haring-esque T-shirts and paintings from
a shop on Orchard Street. "If you come down here on a weekend, there's no better
place to party. The streets are just mobbed with 20-somethings having the time
of their life."
</P>
<P>
	   A century ago, the Lower East Side's crowded tenements and filthy living
conditions inspired muckraking journalist Jacob Riis' expose "How the Other Half
Lives."
</P>
<P>
	   Waves of immigrants passed through the area, fresh from Ellis Island - first
Irish, then Italians, eastern European Jews, Russians, Poles and Greeks, later
Puerto Ricans, Dominicans, Chinese.
</P>
<P>
	   Immigration still shapes the neighborhood. Today it's not clear where
Chinatown begins and the old Lower East Side ends. Hispanic families have a
significant presence, and many recent arrivals hail from Bangladesh and
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
	   But scattered among the Asian fishmongers and elderly Jewish men selling
socks, underwear and discount clothing is a new kind of migrant - young
professionals drawn to the area by low rents and a vibrant arts and
entertainment scene.
</P>
<P>
	   "The grandchildren and great-grandchildren of the immigrants who first moved
to this neighborhood and worked all their lives to get out ... are back in the
neighborhood," laughed Fred Austin, owner of the venerable Katz's Delicatessen,
which now stays open till 3 a.m. on weekend nights to accommodate hungry young
club-goers.
</P>
<P>
	   "We have a host of new shops, new clubs, even theaters, bars, design houses
- a lot of young people, fresh blood, giving the neighborhood a shot in the arm,
a revitalization that we haven't seen for many, many years."
</P>
<P>
	   It wasn't always that way.
</P>
<P>
	   Popular for years as a bargain shopping district, the Lower East Side fell
on hard times during the fiscal crisis of the 1970s. By the time recession hit
in the early '90s, it was known more for its problems with crime and drugs than
its history. Hundreds of old apartment buildings sat vacant, sealed by landlords
who couldn't be bothered to spend money fixing them up.
</P>
<P>
	   Salvation came in the form of New York's late 1990s real estate boom.
</P>
<P>
	   With Wall Street's bull market driving commercial and residential rents to
eye-popping levels in more established Manhattan neighborhoods, young New
Yorkers started noticing the Lower East Side's cheap housing and great location.
</P>
<P>
	   "Now that SoHo has really gentrified into something that the average person
can't afford, I think a lot of people are looking for that SoHo kind of flavor
at a reasonable price," said Bob Levy, the owner of Harris Levy Inc., a family
linen store whose discounted sheets and bedding have been a fixture on Grand
Street since 1894.
</P>
<P>
	   Artists and writers moved in - along with bars, restaurants and boutiques -
and upscale young professionals soon followed.
</P>
<P>
	   "When I moved down here, the broker had 35 keys and he was like, 'Pick a
store,"' recalled Marco, whose art shop is now an overwhelming avalanche of
color. "It was a block full of empties."
</P>
<P>
	   Some longtime residents were suspicious.
</P>
<P>
	   "They used to say, 'Oh, you're not going to make a dollar, what are you
doing opening an art gallery on Orchard Street?"' Marco said. "'This is where
you sell underwear and socks."'
</P>
<P>
	   That's just what's on display next door at J. Hauptman Haberdashery, along
with men's suits and sportswear. Jack Hauptman, whose parents started the store
40 years ago, worries he won't make it on the new Lower East Side.
</P>
<P>
	   Hauptman says the busy bar and club scene is driving away his longtime
customers. Young people "come here to drink," he said. "It's upsetting because
it's taking away my livelihood."
</P>
<P>
	   Some worry gentrification is beginning to drive out the immigrants and other
poor and working class residents who have long been part of the Lower East Side.
Late-night carousing at the area's dozens of bars and clubs has also raised
concerns.
</P>
<P>
	   "People who are low income feel that eventually they will be priced out of
the neighborhood," said Marcia Lemmon, who heads the Ludlow Block Association.
"And when you have a lot of noise, street traffic, that's not conducive to
raising a family."
</P>
<P>
	   The low rents that first drew young people to the neighborhood are already
vanishing. In the Beckenstein Fabrics building on Orchard Street - still
surrounded by storefronts displaying girdles, handbags and discount hosiery -
newly renovated one-bedroom apartments rent for $5,000 a month, and studios top
out at $3,000.
</P>
<P>
	   Who's paying those prices?
</P>
<P>
	   "Wall Street guys," said Faith Hope Consolo, an executive at the real estate
firm handling rentals in the Beckenstein building. "Even lawyers and
accountants, if you can believe it. ... It's amazing. We just don't have enough
space for everybody."
</P>
<P>
	   Still, some old-time Lower East Siders couldn't be happier. Levy said a park
near his linen store was once a hangout for drug dealers and is now clean and
safe.
</P>
<P>
	   "I remember years ago that if I had to stay in the store late, ... at 10
o'clock at night, I'd start thinking, 'I'd better get going,"' he said. "Now I
can stay till 12 o'clock and I don't think twice about it."
</P>
<P>
	   What does the future hold for the ever-evolving Lower East Side?
</P>
<P>
	   More change, predicts artist Marco.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's the only thing you can count on," he said. "Eventually somebody's
going to come down here and change us again."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
