<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 05:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Whole Nine Yards' Tops Box Office  </HEADLINE>
    By DAVID GERMAIN AP Entertainment Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The hit men remain on target.
</P>
<P>
	   "The Whole Nine Yards," a comedy about hired killers, held onto first place
at the box office for the second straight weekend, taking in $9.6 million,
according to industry estimates Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   The teen comedy "Snow Day" also held strong at No. 2 with $8.5 million in
its third weekend.
</P>
<P>
	   "Reindeer Games," a casino-heist caper starring Ben Affleck, Gary Sinise and
Charlize Theron, was the only new movie to debut in the top five. Directed by
John Frankenheimer, it overcame generally poor reviews to open in third place
with $8 million.
</P>
<P>
	   The comic drama "Hanging Up," which ran a close second to "The Whole Nine
Yards" last weekend, fell to No. 4 with $7.5 million.
</P>
<P>
	   The sci-fi thriller "Pitch Black" rounded out the top five with $7.1 million
in its second weekend.
</P>
<P>
	   The top movies were bunched tightly, unlike a few weeks ago when the horror
hit "Scream 3" debuted and far outpaced the competition.
</P>
<P>
	   "Light, escapist fare rules the day right now," said Paul Dergarabedian,
president of Exhibitor Relations Co. Inc., which tracks movie attendance.
</P>
<P>
	   "But the top five's got a real mix of genres. The industry's putting enough
different films into the marketplace that each one is picking up its own
audience segment," Dergarabedian said.
</P>
<P>
	   Another new movie, "Wonder Boys," debuted in seventh place with $5.9
million. Starring Michael Douglas as a novelist and professor whose life is in
shambles, "Wonder Boys" played in narrower release than the other top films and
scored the best per-theater average.
</P>
<P>
	   Playing in 1,253 cinemas, "Wonder Boys" averaged $4,669 per theater,
compared to an average of $3,299 in 2,910 theaters for "The Whole Nine Yards"
and $3,630 in 2,204 theaters for "Reindeer Games."
</P>
<P>
	   Paramount plans to expand "Wonder Boys" next weekend.
</P>
<P>
	   "American Beauty" and "The Cider House Rules" continued to trade on their
top status among Oscar nominees. Re-released last week, "American Beauty" was in
ninth place with $4.7 million, pushing its total gross to $87.7 million. The
movie has added about $13 million to its take since Oscar nominations were
announced last week.
</P>
<P>
	   At 1,346 theaters, "The Cider House Rules" went into its widest release yet
and had $4.1 million in ticket sales to rank No. 10. The film has grossed $32
million, up about $9 million since the nominations.
</P>
<P>
	   "The Beach," the new movie from teen heartthrob Leonardo DiCaprio, dropped
out of the top 10 after just three weekends. It was No. 11 with $3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
	   Estimated ticket sales for Friday through Sunday at North American theaters,
according to Exhibitor Relations Co. Inc. Final figures were to be released
today.
</P>
<P>
	   1. "The Whole Nine Yards," $9.6 million.
</P>
<P>
	   2. "Snow Day," $8.5 million.
</P>
<P>
	   3. "Reindeer Games," $8 million.
</P>
<P>
	   4. "Hanging Up," $7.5 million.
</P>
<P>
	   5. "Pitch Black," $7.1 million.
</P>
<P>
	   6. "The Tigger Movie," $6.3 million.
</P>
<P>
	   7. "Wonder Boys," $5.9 million.
</P>
<P>
	   8. "Scream 3," $5 million.
</P>
<P>
	   9. "American Beauty," $4.7 million.
</P>
<P>
	   10. "The Cider House Rules," $4.1 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
