<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 08:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diallo juror describes 'unhappy' decision  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Clearing four white police officers of murder in the
slaying of an unarmed black man wasn't easy, according to some jurors.
<P>
	   But the law made the jury's decision "very clear - not happy, but clear,"
juror Helen Harder said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   Speaking publicly for the first time since Friday's verdict in the racially
charged case, Harder said that the jury deliberated without discord before
announcing its dramatic decision.
</P>
<P>
	   "It turned out the only way it could turn out," Harder, 71, told The
Associated Press in a brief interview in the kitchen of her Albany County home.
</P>
<P>
	   Added Harder: "I'm not saying it's a happy verdict. I know the cops are
happy. None of (the jurors) are very happy. But that's the way it worked out."
</P>
<P>
	   Amadou Diallo's mother, Kadiatou Diallo, who cried as the jury announced the
not-guilty verdict 24 times, said today her son was forgotten at the trial.
</P>
<P>
	   "The judge said to the jury they should put themselves in the shoes of the
police officers, but Amadou did not come alive during the trial," she said in an
interview on NBC's "Today" show. "No one talked about him really."
</P>
<P>
	   She was disappointed in the jury's decision but said she still has faith in
the American justice system. "Something tells me to keep on having faith because
right now we are calling for a federal investigation to see what can be done
about it," she said. The family also plans to file a civil lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
	   In an interview on Sunday with NBC, juror Tim DeTraglia agreed with Harder's
assessment, even saying "tears were shed" during deliberations.
</P>
<P>
	   Officers Sean Carroll, Edward McMellon, Kenneth Boss and Richard Murphy were
cleared of murder and other charges in the slaying of Diallo, a West African
immigrant.
</P>
<P>
	   The plainclothes officers claimed they fired 41 bullets at the victim on
Feb. 4, 1999, after he refused orders to halt for questioning and pulled out a
black object they thought was a small handgun. Diallo was hit 19 times in the
vestibule of his Bronx apartment before the defendants realized the object was a
wallet.
</P>
<P>
	   Apparently, the officers' testimony was a crucial point for the jurors.
</P>
<P>
	   "He looked at the police officers, they identified themselves, and as they
moved toward him, he turned and backed away," juror Tom Knowles said to NBC.
"Why? Why? We won't know those answers."
</P>
<P>
	   Juror Ed Powell also told NBC the jury believed that the officers thought
that their lives were in danger.
</P>
<P>
	   "If I were to pull something out of my pocket, you couldn't identify that
quickly whether it was a gun or a wallet," Powell said, adding that the officers
had a legal right to defend themselves if they thought Diallo was attacking
them.
</P>
<P>
	   The death of Diallo - and now the not-guilty verdict - has flamed tensions
between police and minorities and touched off protests around New York City.
Because of pre-trial publicity, an appeals court moved the murder case from the
Bronx to Albany, where Harder, who is white, served on a jury that also had four
black women and seven white men.
</P>
<P>
	   Jurors have remained mostly silent since the verdict, despite constant
hounding by network television, New York City newspapers and major news
organizations.
</P>
<P>
	   The jury's black forewoman, Arlene Taylor, who once lived in the Bronx, told
the New York Post that the three-day deliberation had "nothing to do with race."
</P>
<P>
	   She told the Daily News that the public outrage over the jury's decision was
"like getting a kick in the teeth."
</P>
<P>
	   Harder, who has nine children and 17 grandchildren, described the heartbreak
of seeing Diallo's parents sitting in the front row each day of the month-long
trial.
</P>
<P>
	   The juror didn't mention race. But her husband, attorney George Harder, said
his wife told him that it was not an issue in the jury's deliberations.
</P>
<P>
	   The defense case hinged on the emotional testimony of the officers. All
claimed they were convinced that they had to shoot Diallo in self-defense.
</P>
<P>
	   The judge instructed jurors several times that by law if they concluded that
the officers "reasonably believed" Diallo was armed and dangerous, they must
acquit.
</P>
<P>
	   About the officers, Harder said, "I thought they were quite believable."
</P>
<P>
	   The juror also said she was relieved that the trial is over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
