<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 08:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dissent Reported in FBI Waco Siege  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- A memo written during the weeks-long standoff by the Branch
Davidian cult in 1993 details dissent within the FBI over whether to use tear
gas to end the ordeal, The Dallas Morning News reported today.
</P>
<P>
	   The standoff near Waco ended April 19, 1993, in the fiery deaths of more
than 80 cult members after agents launched a tear gas attack. The standoff had
begun Feb. 28, more than seven weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
	   A memo dated March 23, 1993, was obtained by the newspaper. Danny O.
Coulson, then deputy assistant FBI director, wrote that he feared bureau
officials in Waco were lobbying to use tear gas against the Davidians because
they were frustrated, tired and under pressure from the agency's hostage rescue
team commander, Richard Rogers.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Bottom line, I suggest that it is not time to ask the AG (attorney
general) or the president for permission to assault the compound with gas,'' he
wrote. ``Progress is still being made.''
</P>
<P>
	   Coulson wrote that negotiations were being hurt by an inconsistent tactical
strategy, including repeated punishment of sect members just when they appeared
to be cooperating.
</P>
<P>
	   The government has maintained that the Davidians were responsible for their
own deaths. But several of the sect's survivors and relatives have filed a
wrongful death lawsuit against the government.
</P>
<P>
	   The trial is set for May 14 in Waco federal court.
</P>
<P>
	   Rogers was the agency's on-scene commander in Waco and also had a key role
in the deadly 1992 standoff at Ruby Ridge, Idaho.
</P>
<P>
	   In Ruby Ridge, an FBI sniper under Rogers' command killed the wife of white
supremacist Randy Weaver after Rogers relaxed bureau rules of engagement and
pushed for an all-out tank and tear-gas assault on the Weavers' cabin.
</P>
<P>
	   In Waco, Coulson wrote, ``a lot of pressure (to use tear gas) is coming from
Rogers.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``We had similar problems in Idaho with him and he argued and convinced the
SACs (local FBI special agents in charge) that Weaver would not come out. That
proved to be wrong. I believe he is a significant part of the problem here.''
</P>
<P>
	   Rogers has declined interview requests.
</P>
<P>
	   Attorney General Janet Reno approved a plan to gas the compound on April 19,
1993. It began with a gradual tear-gas insertion but escalated to an all-out
tear gas assault after the sect began shooting at FBI tanks.
</P>
<P>
	   Later, agents increased pressure by sending tanks deep into the building.
Six hours after the gas assault began, the compound burned with sect leader
David Koresh and more than 80 followers inside. Some died from fire, others from
gunshots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 0841 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
