<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U S West Loses Long-Distance Battle  </HEADLINE>
   By LAURIE ASSEO Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- U S West, one of the major regional phone companies,
today failed to win the Supreme Court's permission to sell another firm's
long-distance service to its local customers.
</P>
<P>
	   The court, without comment, turned away U S West's argument that the
arrangement is authorized by a 1996 federal law intended to open local phone
markets to full competition.
</P>
<P>
	   AT&AMP;T's long-standing monopoly over phone service was broken up by a 1982
agreement that created competition in long-distance service while setting up
regional phone companies to provide local service on a monopoly basis.
</P>
<P>
	   The 1996 Telecommunications Act overhauled that system and sought to open
local phone service to competition for the first time.
</P>
<P>
	   Among other things, the law let local phone companies provide long-distance
service if they opened their local markets to competition. Last December, Bell
Atlantic got Federal Communications Commission permission under that provision
to offer long-distance service to its New York customers.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1998, U S West and Ameritech companies negotiated agreements to sell the
long-distance service of Qwest Communications Corp. to their local customers.
Qwest paid U S West and Ameritech a fee for each local phone client who chose
Qwest's long-distance service.
</P>
<P>
	   The FCC blocked the partnerships, saying they violated the 1996 law because
U S West and Ameritech did not open their local markets to competition in
exchange for the right to provide long-distance service.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia agreed last
June. Ameritech did not appeal the ruling.
</P>
<P>
	   U S West's appeal to the Supreme Court said it was not ``providing'' phone
service but was merely selling another company's service. The 1996 law was
clear, and therefore the appeals court should not have deferred to the FCC's
interpretation, the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
	   Justice Department lawyers said the 1996 law created an incentive for local
phone companies to open their markets to competition, and that U S West's
arrangement would circumvent that goal. Government lawyers also noted that U S
West and Qwest have announced plans to merge.
</P>
<P>
	   The case is U S West Communications vs. FCC, 99-869.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
