<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Won't Block Deporting of Nazi  </HEADLINE>
   By LAURIE ASSEO Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today refused to halt the deportation
of a 78-year-old retired foundry supervisor found to have served as a guard at
two Nazi concentration camps during World War II.
</P>
<P>
	   The court, without comment, rejected an appeal in which Ferdinand Hammer
argued that immigration officials should have to show he actively participated
in persecution of the camps' prisoners.
</P>
<P>
	   Hammer, of Sterling Heights, Mich., admits he was a member of the German
army's Waffen-SS during the war but has denied being part of a battalion that
served at concentration camps.
</P>
<P>
	   He came to the United States in 1955 and became a naturalized citizen in
1963. Hammer was stripped of his citizenship by a federal judge in 1996 for
lying about his past.
</P>
<P>
	   The judge found Hammer had served as a guard at the Auschwitz death camp in
Nazi-occupied Poland and the Sachsenhausen concentration camp in Germany.
</P>
<P>
	   Hammer did not appeal his loss of citizenship, and later that year the
government began deportation proceedings.
</P>
<P>
	   An immigration judge ordered him deported in 1997 after finding that Hammer
had assisted in Nazi-sponsored acts of persecution.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.S. Board of Immigration Appeals upheld that order, as did the 6th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals last November.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Over 1 million people were murdered based solely on their religion or
ethnicity at the concentration camps where Hammer stood guard,'' the appeals
court said, adding that the government need not present evidence that Hammer
personally was involved in specific acts.
</P>
<P>
	   In the appeal acted on today, Hammer's lawyer said immigration officials in
his deportation case improperly relied on findings made during the citizenship
case that he was a guard at the death camps.
</P>
<P>
	   His lawyer also said the government should have to prove ``personal active
assistance'' by Hammer in acts of persecution.
</P>
<P>
	   The case is Hammer vs. INS, 99-1310.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
