<HEADLINE> Dow Up 16.21; Nasdaq Down 55.83  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed in early trading today, with blue-chip
shares fluctuating after last week's sharp drop and technology stocks falling as
profit-taking set in.
</P>
<P>
	   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average alternated between positive and negative territory. At 10 a.m., it was
up 16.21 at 9,878.33.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dow closed below 10,000 on Friday for the first time in more than 10
months.
</P>
<P>
	   Broader stock indicators were lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was
down 2.44 at 1,330.92.
</P>
<P>
	   The Nasdaq composite index was down 55.83 at 4,534.67, hurt by weakness in
technology shares. Yahoo! was down 9 13/16 at 155 3/8 and Intel was off 2 1/18
at 111 1/8.
</P>
<P>
	   Much of the stock market has been plagued in recent weeks by fears that the
Federal Reserve will raise interest rates to reduce inflationary pressures in
the robust U.S. economy. Adding to these concerns today was a Commerce
Department report that Americans' personal income rose sharply in January to its
strongest pace in three months.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors worry that as people make more money, they will be inclined to
spend more. Consumer spending accounts for two-thirds of the nation's overall
economic activity.
</P>
<P>
	   The slump in the U.S. stock market prompted selling on financial markets
overseas today. Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.49 percent. In afternoon
trading, Germany's DAX index was down 2.56 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was down
1.49 percent, and France's CAC-40 was down 2.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 134.08 million shares, down from Friday's
early pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index was down 3.42 at 553.32.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
