<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that are moving substantially or trading heavily
today on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
	   The New York-based financial services conglomerate said co-chairman and
co-chief executive John S. Reed will step down in April. Sanford I. Weill, 66,
who has shared the top post with Reed, 61, will become the sole chairman and
CEO. Weill, however, also announced that he planned to leave the company and
will work with the board of directors to find a successor within two years.
</P>
<P>
	   The German-American automaker's earnings rose 32 percent for the fourth
quarter and 19 percent for the year due to vigorous sales of Jeeps and
Mercedes-Benz luxury cars.
</P>
<P>
	   Bass agreed to acquire Bristol Hotels &AMP; Resorts Inc. for $9.50 a share.
Dallas-based Bristol operates 112 hotels. Bass operates or franchises more than
2,800 hotels and 450,000 guest rooms in more than 90 countries and territories.
</P>
<P>
	   The Independent, a London newspaper, reported that online auction giant eBay
Inc. will launch a takeover bid for 200-year-old Sotheby's. But a Wall Street
Journal reporter, appearing Monday on the financial cable network CNBC, said
people familiar with the situation have told him there are no talks under way
between eBay and Sotheby's and no indication that eBay is about to launch a bid
for Sotheby's.
</P>
<P>
	   Columbia Energy Group has accepted a $6 billion takeover offer from
Merrillville, Ind.-based NiSource Inc., four months after rejecting a slightly
higher offer from NiSource as inadequate. The deal will make the new company the
largest gas company east of the Rockies, with access to 4.1 million gas,
electric, water and propane customers stretching from the Midwest to New
England.
</P>
<P>
	   America Online announced that it has selected Westborough, Mass.-based Arch
to provide two-way wireless messaging capabilities for its new AOL Mobile
Messenger service and plans to offer AOL's e-mail and AOL Instant Messenger
services to consumers using devices enabled with Arch's messaging capabilities.
</P>
