<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High court rejects bid for new trial in gas station killing  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - A Massachusetts man who raped and murdered a
Windsor Locks gas station attendant but was spared the death penalty on Monday
lost his state Supreme Court appeal seeking a new trial.
<P>
	   Christopher Hafford, 35, was convicted in June 1996 of murdering Theresa
Rafferty by stabbing her with an ice pick and clubbing her with a shovel.
Rafferty had 61 wounds.
</P>
<P>
	   A three-judge panel convicted Hafford of capital felony, felony murder,
murder, robbery, burglary and first-degree sexual assault. That same panel
conducted a penalty hearing to determine whether Hafford should be executed.
</P>
<P>
	   The Superior Court panel found that the murder was committed in a cruel and
heinous manner. But the judges spared Hafford's life because they found there
were mitigating factors: his mental impairment and willingness to cooperate with
authorities.
</P>
<P>
	   Hafford was sentenced to life in prison without the possibility of parole
and was given an additional 20 years each for burglary and robbery. The
additional terms are to be served consecutively, for an effective prison
sentence of life plus 40 years.
</P>
<P>
	   In his appeal, Hafford had argued, among other things, that the trial court
improperly refused to suppress his confession and that he was denied his right
to a trial by jury.
</P>
<P>
	   In the Supreme Court's 7-0 decision Monday, Chief Justice Francis J.
McDonald wrote that Hafford was well aware of his rights concerning confessions
and was advised of his right to remain silent eight times.
</P>
<P>
	   Aside from his confession, the high court concludes there was "overwhelming
evidence of the defendant's guilt independent of his confession."
</P>
<P>
	   Among other things, the court said that Hafford said, "I did it" when
approached by police; his blood was found at the crime scene; and the victim's
blood was discovered on his clothes and on the knife found in his car.
</P>
<P>
	   As to the claim that his right to a jury trial was denied, the justices said
the transcript clearly shows Hafford waiving that right after discussion of the
issue with the judge.
</P>
<P>
	   During his trial, defense attorneys said Hafford was a sexual sadist who was
in the throes of a mindless rage when he killed Rafferty, who was working alone
in her father's service station when the attack occurred in 1991.
</P>
<P>
	   The evidence showed she fought back and was conscious through at least part
of the attack.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-28-00 1341 </TRAILER>
