<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polls: Bush-McCain tight; Gore big margin in New York  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Two statewide polls out Monday show Texas Gov.
George W. Bush and Sen. John McCain running neck-and-neck among New York's
Republican voters with Al Gore having wide leads over Bill Bradley among
Democrats.
<P>
	   New York's presidential primary is March 7.
</P>
<P>
	   A tracking poll conducted by Zogby International for the New York Post had
McCain favored by 43 percent of likely Republican voters with Bush favored by 42
percent, a statistical tie. Alan Keyes trailed at 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   On the Democratic side, the vice president led former New York Knicks star
Bradley, 53 percent to 32 percent, in the Zogby poll.
</P>
<P>
	   A second poll, conducted by the Siena College Research Institute had Bush
supported by 43 percent of Republicans to 40 percent for McCain, also a
statistical tie. Other candidates - both Keyes and Steve Forbes also have their
names on the New York ballot - gained 4 percent of the support.
</P>
<P>
	   On the Democratic side, Gore led Bradley, 52 percent to 27 percent, in the
Siena poll.
</P>
<P>
	   Zogby's telephone poll, conducted Saturday and Sunday, sampled 450 likely
Republican primary voters and 455 likely Democratic primary voters. The margin
of error for each was plus or minus 4.5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
	   Siena College's telephone poll, conducted Feb. 23-26, had a margin of error
of plus or minus 7 percentage points for the sample of 189 registered Democrats
considered likely to vote in the November election and 8 percentage points for
the 152 Republican voters sampled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
