<HEADLINE> Family describes ordeal in which two died  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -A man who killed two people and critically wounded
his pregnant ex-girlfriend was upset about her plans to move away, police said
Monday.
<P>
	   An Onondaga County grand jury will consider the case against Angel
Carrasquillo on Wednesday and could raise the charges against him to
first-degree murder, which would allow prosecutors to seek the death penalty
against the 38-year-old.
</P>
<P>
	   According to statements from survivors and witnesses, Carrasquillo had
complained that his former girlfriend, Nancy Jacinto, had lied to him and was
planning to move to Florida.
</P>
<P>
	   "He was upset with Nancy concerning the living arrangements that Nancy was
conducting or planning to conduct. It appears to be domestic related over the
children that they had together," Sgt. Joseph Sweeny said.
</P>
<P>
	   Carrasquillo also fathered a 9-month-old daughter with Jacinto.
</P>
<P>
	   Jacinto remained hospitalized Monday. Doctors removed her spleen following
the attack and her condition was improving. Her fetus was not injured, Sweeny
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Court papers provided details about the seven-hour siege Thursday at
Leonardo and Margarita Salvador's apartment that left Margarita, 25, and her
17-year-old brother, Rumenige Jacinto, dead.
</P>
<P>
	   Dalia Santos, a relative staying with the Salvador's, told police she woke
up Thursday morning about 10:30 a.m. and found Carrasquillo in the apartment. He
had a shotgun and tied her hands and legs, she told police. Nancy and Rumenige
Jacinto also were bound.
</P>
<P>
	   Nancy Jacinto and Carrasquillo began to argue and he stabbed her in the
chest. Rumenige spoke out and Carrasquillo stabbed him in the back with a
kitchen knife.
</P>
<P>
	   "He left Rumenige there to die and took Nancy into the bedroom," Santos told
police.
</P>
<P>
	   Carrasquillo made the Salvador's two children - ages 9 and 3 - watch
television while the victims were tied up in the bedroom.
</P>
<P>
	   Santos' husband arrived home about 3 p.m. The gun-toting Carrasquillo
ordered Julio Cesar Magana to lie on the floor and tied him up with the others.
</P>
<P>
	   "There was a lot of blood on the bed," Magana said. "We both lay there and
Nancy was too weak to speak. She just kept struggling with her breathing and
cried a little."
</P>
<P>
	   A short time later, the Salvador's returned home. Margarita began arguing
with Carrasquillo, who wanted her to lie on the floor.
</P>
<P>
	   "Angel pointed the gun at her and told her if she moved he would kill her,"
Santos told police. "Margarita did not want to get tied up so she said, 'What
are you waiting for? Shoot!"'
</P>
<P>
	   Carrasquillo did, hitting once in the chest with a shotgun blast.
</P>
<P>
	   Leonardo Salvador ran from the house, and Carrasquillo fled in another
direction. He was arrested Friday night near his mother's house after police
received an anonymous tip.
</P>
<P>
	   Carrasquillo will be held without bail while his case is pending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
