<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 291.94; Nasdaq Up 20.67  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow industrials soared more than 290 points today as
bargain hunters grabbed shares at reduced prices following last week's big
selloff. Technology issues, which slumped amid a bout of profit-taking early
today, bounced back in later trading.
</P>
<P>
	   In late afternoon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was up
291.94 at 10,154.06, climbing above the 10,000-mark that it fell below Friday
for the first time in more than 10 months.
</P>
<P>
	   The Nasdaq composite index, which fell 124 points earlier today, was up
20.67 at 4,603.79 as technology stocks made a comeback in the final hour of the
session.
</P>
<P>
	   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 11.83 at 1,345.19.
</P>
<P>
	   Much of the stock market has been plagued in recent weeks by fears that the
Federal Reserve will raise interest rates to reduce inflationary pressures in
the robust U.S. economy. Adding to these concerns today was a Commerce
Department report that Americans' personal income rose sharply in January to its
strongest pace in three months.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors worry that as people make more money, they will be inclined to
spend more. Consumer spending accounts for two-thirds of the nation's overall
economic activity.
</P>
<P>
	   But investors brushed such fears aside today and took advantage of the cheap
deals available thanks to the sharp decline in blue-chip stocks over the last
few weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, analysts warned that the Dow's dramatic rise might be short-lived and
many expect the index to fall back into its volatile pattern in coming weeks as
investors continue to shift money into companies with the best chance for rapid
earnings growth.
</P>
<P>
	   That should bode well for the Nasdaq, which comprises many companies that
are on the forefront of the new economy.
</P>
<P>
	   "Investors are asking 'Where can I find earnings growth?" said Alan
Skrainka, chief market strategist at Edward Jones of St. Louis. "They know that
they can find such growth in technology, Internet and telecom stocks. Those are
outperforming the old economy stocks."
</P>
<P>
	   Brian G. Belski, chief investment strategist at George K. Baum &AMP; Co., in
Kansas City, Mo., added that "the momentum of this market still rests on the
shoulders of the Nasdaq. This is just a one-day flip from Nasdaq into Dow."
</P>
<P>
	   The volatility in the U.S. stock market prompted selling on financial
markets overseas today. Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.49 percent,
Germany's DAX index fell 1.95 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 dropped 1.97 percent,
and France's CAC-40 declined 1.38 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Leading the Dow's rise today was American Express, which gained 9 3/16 at
133 15/16 and General Electric, up 5 13/16 at 131 13/16.
</P>
<P>
	   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by narrow margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 827.86 million shares, down from 857.3
million shares on Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index was down 2.08 at 558.82.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
