<DOCNO> APW20000228.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain forced to use unknowns in New York battle against Bush  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - In New York's presidential primary, George W. Bush
has elected state GOP lawmakers, famous names like Teddy Roosevelt IV and
millionaire lawyers running as prospective delegates.
<P>
	   John McCain has a sandhog.
</P>
<P>
	   Two statewide polls on Monday showed McCain and Bush in a statistical dead
heat in New York. But with New York's complicated election laws set up to make
it as easy as possible for the state party's favorite to carry the state, the
Super Tuesday battle comes down to a fight between Bush's famous friends and
McCain's brigade of nobodies.
</P>
<P>
	   But Christopher Conroy, a 40-year-old tunnel digging "sandhog" who says he's
most at peace when he's 800 feet underground working on the water tunnel from
New York City to the Catskills, isn't worried about name recognition.
</P>
<P>
	   "If people are going to go into that booth and go for McCain, I don't really
believe that even if you put Governor George Pataki's name there, it would
really matter," Conroy, who is working to educate McCain supporters on how the
state's ballot process works, said.
</P>
<P>
	   In Conroy's Brooklyn congressional district, Bush has Roosevelt, the
great-grandson of the nation's 26th president and New York's 33rd governor,
Teddy Roosevelt, as one of his possible delegates.
</P>
<P>
	   "People don't have a problem votin' for me, as long as John McCain comes out
the winner," Conroy said. "We're calling people, sending them mailings, letting
them know that you don't go into that booth looking for John McCain, you have to
look for his delegates."'
</P>
<P>
	   In New York, Republicans vote for delegates - not presidential candidates -
in each of the state's 31 congressional districts. Each district sends three
delegates to the Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
	   Making things even more difficult for McCain is the fact that delegate names
are printed in bold type. In smaller type are advisories telling voters who each
prospective delegate is committed to.
</P>
<P>
	   Because of that, having big-name delegates is considered a powerful
political plus. Bush, with the backing of Pataki and state GOP Chairman William
Powers, has the names.
</P>
<P>
	   "Republicans walk into a voting booth in a Republican primary, they will see
names they recognize and that they trust," Powers said.
</P>
<P>
	   In just one eastern New York congressional district, the Bush delegate slate
includes state Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, Lt. Gov. Mary Donohue and
U.S. Rep. John Sweeney. Another upstate district has state Sens. James Wright
and Ronald Stafford as well as former state Sen. H. Douglas Barclay, a
millionaire Syracuse-area lawyer.
</P>
<P>
	   In New York City, the Bush names aren't as well known in large part because
of the much smaller number of Republicans - "I think we're outnumbered 15-to-1
in Brooklyn," Conroy said - but names like Roosevelt do show up.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain's prospective delegates aren't as well known. While U.S. Rep. Peter
King is a McCain supporter, the Long Island congressman came on board too late
to become a delegate. The best-known McCain backer with his name on the ballot
is Staten Island Borough President Guy Molinari, a former congressman and the
father of ex-congresswoman Susan Molinari.
</P>
<P>
	   Even McCain's eight-member paid political staff in New York is largely made
up of people with only local political experience. "They have the generals, but
we have the footsoldiers," Gerry O'Brien, McCain's New York political director,
said.
</P>
<P>
	   To counter their delegates' low name recognition, O'Brien and other McCain
supporters have been pitching the life stories of delegates such as Conroy,
hoping voters may remember some of the names once in the voting booths.
</P>
<P>
	   Bruno, who said he favors making the ballot clearer by making the
candidate's name bigger than the delegate's, said he nonetheless thinks
Republican voters are smart enough to pick out the candidate they want to vote
for.
</P>
<P>
	   "They know there's a big name and there's a small name, and they're going to
look for that small name," the Bush-backing Bruno said. "Now, will some people
follow me or the lieutenant governor or Congressman Sweeney and feel like, 'I
could go either way, so I'd like to go with people I know?' I hope so."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-28-00 1524 </TRAILER>
