<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wild Styles at Mugler, Yamamoto  </HEADLINE>
    By SUZY PATTERSON AP Fashion Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PARIS (AP) -- It was serious business at Yves Saint Laurent's fall-winter
show for the Rive Gauche collection Monday, with jovial designer Alber Elbaz
showing enough black to make his last show look funereal, a kind of dark swan
song.
</P>
<P>
	   Tom Ford -- creative head of Gucci -- is expected to take over this
prestigious ready-to-wear collection now that Gucci owns YSL. Haute couture,
though, will still be controlled by Yves Saint Laurent and Pierre Berge.
</P>
<P>
	   Though dark, Elbaz's show at the Louvre's Carrousel was very handsome,
featuring knee-length tailored coats, belted coats and leather suits.
</P>
<P>
	   The return of fitted coats was marvelous, especially one tobacco-brown tweed
number worn with high boots. Model Alec Wek looked regal in a knee-length belted
leather coat dress in dark chocolate brown.
</P>
<P>
	   Fluid dresses featured high-wrapped necks and gathered fronts -- like some
of the chiffon blouses for haute couture done by Saint Laurent himself.
</P>
<P>
	   One belted coat shimmered with golden ochre highlights. A suit in deep rose
topped a pair of boots. And an ochre skirt flared beneath a yellow chiffon
blouse.
</P>
<P>
	   Evening wear glittered, starting with gold suits and coats in soft leather
and featuring silver lame, sparkling sheaths and ostrich feathers. Though not as
original as the collections of Saint Laurent, Elbaz's commercial offering was
well-suited to the elegant women.
</P>
<P>
	   What's new, pussycat? was Thierry Mugler's theme this time in an amusing
parade that showed off plenty for cat fans -- including fuzzy angora coats and
wraps, and cat ears on hats and hairdos.
</P>
<P>
	   Mugler, whose shows are usually either spectacular or bare-bones, went for a
compromise this time. Though there were plenty of hot and fitted numbers,
offerings were still tame compared to some of his nuttier creations of the past.
</P>
<P>
	   Little two-piece black skirt outfits showed a bit of midriff, and
Davy-Crockett-style fur hats -- cat ears, tails and all -- crowned the ensemble.
Three-piece outfits in soft moleskin broadcloth were fun, as were the glacier
blue trouser outfits with wide decollete collars on top.
</P>
<P>
	   Fuzzy mohair in colorful wraps covered up smooth pants or skirt outfits.
</P>
<P>
	   Mugler went techno too, combining natural fabrics and shiny threads in
convertible dresses. Hidden stud fasteners and zippers made pants flare and
skirts turn inside out.
</P>
<P>
	   With his Bordeaux velvet and silver lame reversible off-shoulder sheaths, or
the moss green velvet gown with crystal neck plastron and wrist details, Mugler
hit his usual high for sexy, glamorous evening wear.
</P>
<P>
	   Wildlife also intrigued Yohji Yamamoto, who showed at one of his favorite
sites, Pigalle's Moulin Rouge space. But Toulouse Lautrec would have thought
Paris was having a cold wave. Instead of the prancing, dancing girls usually on
display here, the crowd saw wrapped-up beauties, Doctor Zhivago style.
</P>
<P>
	   Film director Wim Wenders ("Paris, Texas," among others) was there to admire
the creator he filmed in a documentary.
</P>
<P>
	   Warm and voluminous, the clothes were reminiscent of a Persian rug or a
Mongolian tapestry.
</P>
<P>
	   But models also came out wearing the softest chamois suede, some sleek black
jerseys and fox trim. The butter-soft leather skirts were jagged at the hems and
worn over flat boots.
</P>
<P>
	   With the fur hoods, muffs and hats -- in fox, wolf, coyote and synthetics --
the models at Louvre's Carrousel looked like they were on a stylish trek to the
Siberian Taiga, though Yamamoto has never been to the far north, his press
office said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
