<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Few Clues in 1947 Argentine Crash  </HEADLINE>
   By KEVIN GRAY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRES QUEBRADAS, Argentina (AP) -- A frozen hand with long fingernails. Human
bones and torsos preserved in ice. The ripped and faded tatters of uniforms from
a bygone era.
</P>
<P>
	   Fifty-two years after a British passenger plane vanished in a snowstorm over
the Andes, a rescue team has recovered human remains and pieces of debris in a
risky operation that may help determine what happened to the flight.
</P>
<P>
	   The plane, called Stardust and operated by the defunct British South
American Airways, carried five crew members and six passengers. It was headed to
Santiago, Chile, on a flight originating in London, when radio contact was
suddenly lost Aug. 2, 1947.
</P>
<P>
	   More than half a century later, mountaineers stumbled upon the wreckage of
the four-engine Avro Lancastrian. Using their clues, the expedition led by the
Argentine army embarked this month on a five-day trek to recover the remains.
</P>
<P>
	   On Feb. 22, members of the armed forces -- bundled in heavy mountain gear
and working with oxygen tanks strapped to their backs -- struggled for nearly
nine hours at 16,500 feet to gather bits and pieces of the plane's fuselage, a
fuel pump and other artifacts investigators hope will shed new light on the
fatal flight.
</P>
<P>
	   But their work came at the end of a harrowing trip: four hours by four-wheel
vehicle, nine hours by foot and mule, then a seven-hour hike up the 21,848-foot
Tupungato volcano, where debris and human remains were strewn across a glacier.
</P>
<P>
	   Local climbers insist ascending the volcano is more challenging than scaling
Aconcagua, the Andes' highest peak. The trip really requires trekking up two
peaks, first winding up to the top of the Portezuelo del Azufre, a mountain
whose peak sits at roughly 14,000 feet, before making a rapid and treacherous
descent to the base of Tupungato. From there, it's all uphill again.
</P>
<P>
	   Reaching the wreckage took its toll. A soldier suffering from breathing
problems had to be brought down, while others struggled to adjust to abrupt
changes in altitude. Some vomited. Blood dripped from their noses in the
oxygen-thin air. Their heads pounded, their balance was thrown off.
</P>
<P>
	   Stubborn mules, weary from grueling climbs through rocky terrain with
hundreds of pounds of equipment on their back, frequently rebelled. Riders were
bucked off. Other mules ran off or lost their footing, stumbling down a
boulder-filled decline.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We knew this would be difficult, especially since we have a group of
journalists who've never climbed before,'' said Lt. Col. Ricardo Bustos, the
expedition leader. ``We in the military do this a lot, and it's tough on us.''
</P>
<P>
	   After reaching the site, officers labored to collect the mummified remains
of at least three passengers, which authorities hope to identify through DNA
testing.
</P>
<P>
	   Working against rapidly changing temperatures -- clouds covering the sun
could cause rapid cooling -- and a beating mountaintop wind, soldiers chipped
away at ice that had kept some remains nearly perfectly preserved.
</P>
<P>
	   ``A soldier found this small piece of clothing with a bone attached sticking
up in the ice,'' Bustos said. ``He used an ice pick to chip away at it.''
</P>
<P>
	   The recovered remains -- a frozen hand with long fingernails, several
torsos, and bones -- were placed in brown leather satchels. As soldiers
inspected the pieces, covered in dirt and ice, Bustos asked for a moment of
silence.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We want to remember these people who are no longer with us and the
families who waited for them although they never arrived,'' he said solemnly as
soldiers and journalists bowed their heads. The passengers aboard the plane
included three Britons, a German woman, a Palestinian and a Swiss man.
</P>
<P>
	   The human remains and those of the aircraft were brought down by mule.
</P>
<P>
	   Luis Estrella, an air force official on the expedition, said authorities
were trying to determine if the plane crashed into the face of the volcano. He
said the way the debris was littered might reveal the direction from which the
plane came.
</P>
<P>
	   With little else other than an indecipherable final message, investigators
until now had few details to work from. Some had wondered if the plane had been
sabotaged to kill a British diplomatic messenger reportedly on board.
</P>
<P>
	   But the prevailing assumption of the cause was severe weather. Records
indicate heavy snow fell for three days when the plane vanished, and aviation
experts said the plane -- a converted World War II bomber -- did not have
deicing capability.
</P>
<P>
	   Strangely enough, it was a change in the weather that turned out to be the
biggest break in the decades-long investigation. Higher temperatures in recent
years atop Tupungato forced the ice fields downward and may have helped uncover
the remains, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
	   Investigator Carlos Sorini said he hoped to have a final report within
months.
</P>
<P>
	   Sorini said he thought this experience could help investigators learn how to
approach solving other plane disappearances in the Andes, a virtual graveyard of
aircraft from the early days of aviation.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There were a lot of accidents around World War II, and those planes are
still in the mountains somewhere,'' he said, estimating at least five or six
other aircraft are still to be found. ``But we're glad to have at least made
progress on this one.''
</P>
<P>
	   --------
</P>
<P>
	   EDITORS: APTN correspondent Miguel Gil contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 1530 </TRAILER>
