<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Mixed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean prices were mixed Monday in choppy trading
on the Chicago Board of Trade.
</P>
<P>
	   Wheat led the declining commodities, falling on the outlook for continued
wet weather in much of the U.S. winter wheat belt. Prices fell about 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Corn also fell, pressured by the threat of large deliveries being made
against the March contract. The delivery day is Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Soybeans rebounded from last Friday's fallback, when prices hit their lowest
level in more than a month. But trading was quiet and the gains were limited by
beneficial crop weather in South America over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
	   Wheat for May delivery fell 2 1/2 cents to $2.56 3/4 a bushel; May corn fell
 3/4 cent to $2.20 3/4 a bushel; May oats rose  1/2 cent to $1.15 1/2 a bushel;
May soybeans rose  3/4 cent to $5.06 1/4 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
	   Beef and pork futures advanced on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
	   April live cattle rose .15 cent to 71.47 cents a pound; March feeder cattle
rose .20 cent to 83.47 cents a pound; April lean hogs rose .70 cent to 58.35
cents a pound; March pork bellies rose .52 cent to 90.52 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
