<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Puerto Rico Gov. Supports Clinton  </HEADLINE>
   By KEVIN GALVIN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite growing protests at home, the governor of Puerto
Rico met with White House officials Monday and reaffirmed his support for
President Clinton's plan to resume limited Navy exercises on the island of
Vieques.
</P>
<P>
	   Gov. Pedro Rossello also took possession Monday of 110 acres of land on the
western end of Vieques that the Navy transferred to local control, part of a
deal to allow renewed training before island residents decide whether to
permanently bar the exercises.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The first step in the overall resolution of the issue was taken today,''
White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said following the meeting between
Rossello and White House chief of staff John Podesta. ``There's obviously a
number of other steps that will have to be taken, including a referendum where
the people of Vieques will decide their future.''
</P>
<P>
	   Last week, some 85,000 people demonstrated against the training in San Juan,
Puerto Rico. But Rossello insisted that the administration's proposal was the
best solution to the standoff between Vieques islanders and the Navy's need to
maintain combat readiness.
</P>
<P>
	   He said that as details of the proposal become more widely known, ``it will
allow much more support for all aspects of that presidential order.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Navy has not announced a date for resuming training, but Rossello
pledged the Puerto Rican government's full cooperation in clearing the test
range of protesters. ``We will take any steps that are appropriate to make sure
that the range is available,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Protests about the safety and environmental risks posed by the Navy's use of
Vieques have placed a hold on the training exercises.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton and Rossello agreed last month to allow the Navy to resume limited
training using inert bombs. The pact calls for a referendum, likely to be held
in 2001, that will allow Vieques residents to choose between the unfettered
resumption of training with live bombs and exercises with dummy bombs until a
Navy withdrawal in May 2003.
</P>
<P>
	   Rossello's opponents criticized him for abandoning a pledge to stop all
bombings on Vieques immediately.
</P>
<P>
	   Additionally, the Clinton administration is seeking $40 million to address
the health and environmental concerns raised by the training on Vieques.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The people of Vieques have placed on the table concerns as to what has
happened to their health, to their environment, to their opportunity for
economic development,'' Rossello said. ``The funds that are requested are
precisely to respond to those very valid concerns.''
</P>
<P>
	   The 110 acres transferred on Monday were to be used to extend an airport on
Vieques to allow larger aircraft to use the facility and to stimulate growth.
</P>
<P>
	   A deed for the land was drawn up and signed by Rossello and Adm. Kevin
Green, commander of Naval Forces South, in a small ceremony, said Maria
Echaveste, deputy White House chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The governor believes that actually taking steps to implement the
president's directives would be helpful in helping reduce the level of
opposition down in Puerto Rico,'' Echaveste said. ``We thought it would be good
if (they) formalized those steps.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 1547 </TRAILER>
