<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cops in Diallo shooting undecided about future, lawyers say  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Three days after they were acquitted of murdering Amadou
Diallo, four police officers are all "decompressing," and have not yet decided
whether they will return to the force, their lawyers said Monday.
<P>
	   If they do return to duty, will they be able to do their jobs? Maybe, say
criminologists.
</P>
<P>
	   "They may really want to go back to police work and now that they've been
acquitted, feel they have a right to do so," said Geoffrey Alpert, a criminal
justice professor at the University of South Carolina. "But rightfully or
wrongfully, they've killed someone. They should go through some serious
psychological testing to see if they're fit for duty."
</P>
<P>
	   But would they be safe on New York City streets? So far, the NYPD thinks
it's worth posting police outside the officers' homes because they've received
threats. Amid the angry response of thousands since the "not guilty" verdicts
were announced, the answer may be "no."
</P>
<P>
	   "Killer Cops!" screamed signs at weekend rallies, with pictures of all four
officers plastered on them.
</P>
<P>
	   "We can't let them get away with it!" read another sign.
</P>
<P>
	   Currently, the four officers - Kenneth Boss, Sean Carroll, Edward McMellon
and Richard Murphy - remain on modified duty, meaning they are assigned to desk
jobs and their badges and guns have been taken away. Pending departmental
reviews of the shooting as well as possible federal civil rights action, it
could be months before Police Commissioner Howard Safir considers restoring the
officers to full duty.
</P>
<P>
	   Although Carroll reportedly has expressed an interest in returning to the
force, his lawyer said the final decision has yet to be made.
</P>
<P>
	   "He's reflecting and he is trying to decompress," John Patten said. "I just
told him chill out, stay calm, be at peace. He needs to make his thought process
become a little clearer first."
</P>
<P>
	   Attorneys for the three other officers said the same thing.
</P>
<P>
	   "My guy is really taking these next couple of days to think," said
McMellon's attorney, Stephen Worth.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's too early for Rich to decide what he wants to do," said Murphy's
attorney, James Culleton.
</P>
<P>
	   "He really wants his 15 minutes to be up and he wants to fade back and live
his life," said Boss's attorney, Steven Brounstein.
</P>
<P>
	   It wouldn't surprise criminologist William Geller if one or all of the
officers decided to leave the force for good.
</P>
<P>
	   "A study done some years ago found that officers involved in fatal
encounters had a much higher likelihood of retiring prematurely," said Geller,
co-author of "Deadly Force: What We Know," a book about police shootings
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
	   A police shooting is an "immense event in the life of a cop," Geller said.
</P>
<P>
	   "Unlike soldiers, cops are not taught to kill, they are taught to protect,"
he said. "Once he's been involved in a shooting, the cop can find himself
questioning the 'God complex. Who am I to take a life,' he asks."
</P>
<P>
	   But Geller, Alpert and others say the NYPD's concern should not be whether
the officers are restored to full duty, but how to prevent another Diallo
tragedy. The officers fired 41 times at Diallo in the vestibule of his Bronx
apartment building, mistakenly thinking the wallet he was holding was a gun.
</P>
<P>
	   At the time of the February 1999 shooting, the officers were all part of the
Street Crime Unit, a band of plainclothes officers who roamed citywide looking
for illegal guns and patrolling high crime neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
	   "A lot of problems with a case like Diallo is having citywide police units
that can't possibly know all the neighborhoods and parachute in," Geller said.
</P>
<P>
	   "However many inches thick the manual for police rules is, the most often
ignored rule is the 'Golden Rule' when it comes to approaching people," he added
- meaning treat people as you would have them treat you. "Police need to think,
'Suppose that was my brother, my sister,' when they approach people. That might
make encounters a lot safer."
</P>
<P>
	   Michael Meyers, executive director of the New York Civil Rights Coalition,
agrees, but concedes that it's a hard thing to teach.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't know of any training that will make a police officer perfect,"
Meyers said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-28-00 1548 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
