<DOCNO> APW20000228.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Ventura Mull Cuba Trade  </HEADLINE>
   By FREDERIC J. FROMMER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura urged President Clinton to
increase funding for special education and questioned why the United States
doesn't establish normal trade relations with Cuba during a visit to the White
House Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   He also said Clinton commended him for having the ``courage'' to leave the
Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
	   As usual, Ventura was the celebrity of the annual National Governors
Association meeting, drawing a pack of journalists, admiring hellos from Secret
Service officers, and at least one request for a photograph.
</P>
<P>
	   And he did nothing to dampen his place in the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Washington is always receptive to Minnesota because we're really the
leader of the country, when it comes to making decisions and electing rogue
governors and taking chances and having courage and intestinal fortitude,'' he
declared after the meeting with Clinton and other governors.
</P>
<P>
	   Ventura said Reform Party politics came up in a conversation with the
president.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He commended me for my courage in my decision to step away from the Reform
Party,'' Ventura said. ``He said that took a lot of guts, but it was the right
thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
	   Ventura's most important message to the White House was to increase funding
for special education.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Quit dilly-dallying around with all the feel-good stuff; fund their
mandate with special ed, and we in the states will have the best education
systems we possibly can if they do that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Trade also came up at the meeting, and Ventura said he supports Clinton's
efforts to allow China into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
	   ``To me, in light of our world of technology, you can't build a wall around
your country,'' he said. ``You go out and you compete.''
</P>
<P>
	   But he called it a ``bit of hypocrisy'' to pursue normal trade relations
with China while maintaining a trade embargo against Cuba. Several lawmakers
from farm states like Minnesota have made similar arguments, seeing Cuba as a
potential market for agriculture.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I wanted a clearer message on why China and not Cuba,'' Ventura said.
``They gave me a lot of reasons that didn't hold a lot of water.''
</P>
<P>
	   At one point, the chairman of the governors association, Republican Gov.
Mike Leavitt of Utah, had to literally move Ventura along.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I've never been able to figure out how to move Jesse Ventura aside, but we
have to report on the meeting,'' he said with a laugh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 1549 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000228.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DaimlerChrysler Earns, Revenues Up  </HEADLINE>
    By HANS GREIMEL Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   STUTTGART, Germany (AP) -- Savings from combined operations and hot-selling
Jeeps and Mercedes-Benz luxury cars helped push earnings at automaker
DaimlerChrysler AG up 32 percent for the fourth quarter and 16 percent over last
year.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts applauded the results Monday of the firm's first year as a merged
entity. Daimler-Benz bought out Auburn Hills, Michigan-based Chrysler Corp. in
late 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors also liked the figures, bidding shares up 2.4 percent, or 1.60
euros, in Frankfurt to close at 67.40 euros ($65.37). In New York, shares were
also up $2 to $65,50 in afternoon trading.
</P>
<P>
	   The German-American company said Monday it earned $1.6 billion, or $1.60 a
share, excluding one-time charges and gains in the last three months of 1999
compared to $1.21 billion, or 61 cents a share, in the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
	   Revenue for the quarter also rose 20 percent to $41.7 billion from about
$34.8 billion a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
	   For the year, DaimlerChrysler earned $5.8 billion, or $5.77 a share, up from
$4.8 billion, or $5.05 a share, a year ago.
</P>
<P>
	   DaimlerChrysler said it beat estimates of $1.54 a share for the quarter and
$6 a share for the year.
</P>
<P>
	   "All the major figures were encouraging," said Andrew Blair-Smith, an auto
analyst with Commerzbank in London. "Any differences are not enough to make me
worry."
</P>
<P>
	   Excluding one-time gains from the sale of a stake in Debitel communication
services and charges from restructuring at its Adtranz train division, the auto
giant reported net income rose to $6.27 billion or $6.25 a share for the year.
</P>
<P>
	   That compares with $5.387 billion, or $5.62 a share, in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   "1999 was our first full year as a combined company and it was very
successful," said co-chairman Juergen Schrempp. "But size is not an end in
itself. Profitable growth is the yardstick of success."
</P>
<P>
	   "We have created a solid foundation for a company that will also be a medium
and long-term winner," Schrempp said. "We launched nine new models last year,
and they became success stories. In 2000, we will bring another 12 car and truck
models to the market."
</P>
<P>
	   For the year, revenues rose 14 percent to $151 billion from $132.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   Key to the report was nearly $1.2 billion in savings achieved by combined
efforts on back office functions and purchasing. Still, it was disappointing
that these savings merely helped the company maintain its profit margins instead
of improving them, said Georg Stuerzer, an auto analyst at Hypo-Vereinsbank in
Munich.
</P>
<P>
	   A one-time tax hit also helped suppress the bottom line in 1999. Due to
changes in German tax law, the company's tax bill rose 50 percent from 1998 to
$4.56 billion. A weak euro also hurt results.
</P>
<P>
	   All figures are based on the exchange rate of $1.007 per euro in effect on
Dec. 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   During 1999, the company said its Chrysler car division revenues climbed 14
percent to $64.5 billion. Its adjusted operating profit was up 22 percent, to
$5.2 billion. Revenues were helped by a 20 percent increase in Jeep sales, to an
all-time high of 680,700 units.
</P>
<P>
	   The Mercedes-Benz and Smart car division had an operating profit in 1999 of
$2.7 billion, up 36 percent, on record revenues of $38.4 billion. Sales of
Mercedes-Benz passengers cars were up more than 10 percent for the year. Sales
of the compact Smart car, available only in Europe, achieved its goal of 80,000
units for the year.
</P>
<P>
	   The company's commercial vehicles division had operating earnings of $1.1
billion, a 13 percent increase over last year. Its services division posted an 8
percent gain in operating earnings, to $1.03 billion. Those results exclude a
one-time gain of $1.15 billion from the sale of Debitel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
