<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Chooses German IMF Candidate  </HEADLINE>
    By PAUL AMES Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The European Union took action Monday to prevent a
non-European from becoming the next head of the International Monetary Fund,
naming a German as its unanimous choice to face rivals from the United States
and Japan.
</P>
<P>
	   Finance ministers from the 15 European Union nations backed Caio Koch-Weser
after weeks of wrangling over the German deputy finance minister's
qualifications to replace Michel Camdessus as IMF managing director.
</P>
<P>
	   "Koch-Weser is a strong candidate for the role and we ... support him,"
Britain's Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown said. Britain and France had
previously expressed reservations about his nomination.
</P>
<P>
	   The job has traditionally been reserved for the Europeans' chosen candidate,
but after the EU nations began bickering over Koch-Weser, other names emerged.
</P>
<P>
	   Japan has won Asian support for its nominee, Eisuke Sakakibara, a former
deputy finance minister, and African nations are backing the IMF's deputy
managing director, Stanley Fischer of the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Monday that President Clinton would
not support Germany's candidate and would hold out for a more prominent
European, despite Fischer's presence in the race.
</P>
<P>
	   Lockhart said Clinton told German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder that he does
not believe Koch-Weser meets criteria the IMF post requires: "a strong candidate
of maximum stature" who would enjoy broad support from other countries.
</P>
<P>
	   French Finance Minister Christian Sautter said his government backed
Koch-Weser rather than see an American get the job.
</P>
<P>
	   "What accelerated the EU decision was (partly) the presence of a candidate
with American nationality, which provoked a very strong European reaction,"
Sautter said. "That pushed us into reaching a consensus on the German
candidate."
</P>
<P>
	   The appearance of competing candidates has raised concerns the 182-nation
IMF could be in for a bruising leadership battle similar to the one that left
the World Trade Organization with a power vacuum for months last year.
</P>
<P>
	   Koch-Weser acknowledged it would be difficult to win over the rest of the
world. "It's important now to create consensus and trust," he said. "My chances
are not bad, but there's a lot of work to be done."
</P>
<P>
	   Koch-Weser, 55, worked at the World Bank for 25 years before joining the
center-left government in Berlin last year. He was strongly supported by
Schroeder, but ran into France and British concerns about his low political
profile and lack of experience at the highest level of international finance.
</P>
<P>
	   Asian, Latin American and African officials are unhappy with the customary
carving up of top jobs at the international financial bodies between the United
States and Europe. The head of the World Bank is traditionally an American,
while a European, usually a Frenchman, leads the IMF.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 1557 </TRAILER>
