<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 11 Sudan Aid Organizations Withdraw  </HEADLINE>
   By CRAIG NELSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) -- At least 11 international aid organizations were
completing their withdrawal Monday from southern Sudan after refusing rebel
demands for higher taxes and more control over assistance to the war-ravaged
region.
</P>
<P>
	   Nearly 160 aid workers began leaving southern Sudan on Thursday following a
rebel ultimatum to comply with new terms for aid deliveries or face expulsion by
Wednesday, aid officials said in the Kenyan capital, Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
	   The pullout interrupts 75 percent of the non-United Nations aid operations
in southern Sudan and affects up to 1.5 million people at a time when food
stocks are low ahead of the major planting season that begins in late May, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   Care, World Vision and Save the Children were among the organizations that
suspended aid operations in Sudan and withdrew their staff.
</P>
<P>
	   Catholic Relief Services, Lutheran World Federation and 22 other aid groups
have agreed to the rebel conditions and signed the accord, said an official for
Operation Lifeline Sudan, the U.N.-led umbrella organization that oversees the
decade-old aid relief operation.
</P>
<P>
	   U.N. agencies like UNICEF and the World Food Program were not entangled in
the dispute. They operate under a separate accord with the rebels and the
Sudanese government in Khartoum.
</P>
<P>
	   The aid operation in southern Sudan, based in the northern Kenyan town of
Lokichokio, is one of the longest-running and largest in the world, with about
35 groups and 500 expatriate workers delivering a million dollars a day in aid.
</P>
<P>
	   Elijah Malok, who heads the relief arm of the Sudan People's Liberation
Army, acknowledged that the pullout would cause hardship among southern Sudanese
but said the donors would have eventually grown weary and pulled out on their
own.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The people are going to suffer sooner or later,'' he told The Associated
Press. ``We are telling the people, 'You must be self-reliant.' We are telling
the people, 'You must produce your own food.'''
</P>
<P>
	   Aid groups have paid taxes to the rebels since 1995. An Aug. 19 draft
memorandum of understanding called for additional fees for the use of airstrips,
roads and trucks in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
	   It also recommended rebel control over the hiring of Sudanese staff by the
relief organizations.
</P>
<P>
	   Talks over the draft memorandum continued until Jan. 12, when the rebels
unexpectedly issued their ultimatum.
</P>
<P>
	   The war between government forces and southern-based rebels is Africa's
longest running conflict. Since 1983, the fighting has killed more than 2
million Sudanese and chased another 4 million from their homes.
</P>
<P>
	   While the civil war is often perceived as a religious war between the
Islamic north and the Christian south, it is the southern rebels' drive for
political autonomy from the Khartoum government that is at the core of the
conflict.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 1558 </TRAILER>
