<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> O'Connor still ailing  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Cardinal John O'Connor was still ailing Monday but
remained in his residence under doctors' care.
<P>
	   "At this point they're not looking at hospitalization," said his spokesman
Joe Zwilling. "They do want to evaluate how he's doing and determine what they
might need to do if anything."
</P>
<P>
	   Zwilling added that O'Connor, who missed the public Mass at St. Patrick's
Cathedral on Sunday, is "suffering from some pronounced weakness. He has not
been able to function as he has in the last several weeks. ... He's not been
able to work normally at his residence. The doctors don't know what is causing
that. But they are looking at it and seeing if it progresses. He spends a good
deal of time in bed, but he's not bedridden."
</P>
<P>
	   Zwilling also said that O'Connor was aware of the contents of the letter
sent to him over the weekend by George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
	   "He has not made any comment on the letter at all," Zwilling said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Republican presidential candidate sent the letter to explain his
appearance at Bob Jones University, a South Carolina institution associated with
anti-Catholic views.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush's decision to contact the cardinal 10 days before the New York primary
shows just how much influence the cardinal continues to wield, despite the
decline in his health. He is considered one of the most powerful Catholics in
the United States, and at age 80, is the country's oldest active bishop.
</P>
<P>
	   Although O'Connor offered his retirement to the Vatican when he turned 75,
as church rules require, the pope did not accept it then. However, cardinals
lose their power to vote for a new pope when they turn 80, and John Paul II is
widely expected to name a replacement for O'Connor some time in the next few
weeks. Those announcements are traditionally made in Rome on a Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Edwin O'Brien, who heads the Archdiocese for the U.S. Military, and
Buffalo's Bishop Henry Mansell are said to be among those under consideration to
replace O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
	   The Daily News reported Monday that the bishop of the Fall River, Mass.,
diocese, a Franciscan friar named Sean O'Malley, is high on the list of likely
candidates.
</P>
<P>
	   John Kearns, spokesman for the Fall River diocese, said: "There's always a
lot of speculation about who might go where. In the past he's been rumored to go
to other places. We don't know."
</P>
<P>
	   Zwilling said it was impossible to predict who the next cardinal would be,
pointing out that O'Connor - then the bishop of Scranton, Pa. - was a surprise
choice when he was picked to replace Cardinal Terence Cooke.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
