<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prosecution charges cops with 'web of lies' to protect Schwarz  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - A federal prosecutor ripped into ex-cop Charles Schwarz
and two other police officers on Monday for spinning a "web of lies" to conceal
Schwarz's role as an accomplice in the precinct house sodomy assault of Abner
Louima.
<P>
	   In a 2 1/2 hour summation of the government's case, Assistant U.S. Attorney
Lauren Resnick reviewed a flurry of frenetic phone calls and statements to
authorities as proof that the trio tried to invent a plausible alibi for
Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
	   "It has been proven beyond a reasonable doubt that that is exactly what
these officers did," she told jurors hearing the officers' trial for conspiring
to obstruct justice.
</P>
<P>
	   Resnick said that as representatives of the public trust, the officers were
obligated to tell the truth, but instead, "they told one story ... then another,
and yet another story here at the trial. They concocted a story to protect one
of their own."
</P>
<P>
	   She said there was no doubt, based on evidence, that Schwarz took part in
the Aug. 9, 1997 incident, which she called "one of the most brutal acts ever
committed by a uniformed police officer."
</P>
<P>
	   Schwarz denied on the stand that he was in the 70th precinct house lavatory
when the attack occurred, but outside inspecting his patrol car for possible
hidden contraband.
</P>
<P>
	   Former Officer Justin Volpe was sentenced to 30 years in prison last year
after pleading guilty to violating Louima's civil rights by ramming a broomstick
into his rectum following his arrest during a street riot. The Haitian immigrant
suffered severe injuries.
</P>
<P>
	   Schwarz, 34, who was convicted in that trial of holding Louima down during
the attack and faces a possible life sentence, is now accused along with
officers Thomas Wiese, 34, and Thomas Bruder, 37, of conspiring to conceal his
own role. The conspiracy charge carries a term of up to five years.
</P>
<P>
	   Resnick ridiculed Wiese for subjecting himself to "the least amount of
personal risk" by volunteering to investigators that he entered the bathroom
during the assault and tried to rescue Louima, but never saw Schwarz there.
</P>
<P>
	   Wiese's lawyer, Joseph Tacopina, launched the defense summation by disputing
that.
</P>
<P>
	   "Why would Thomas Wiese take the risk, risk his family, his career, exposing
himself to possible indictment ... if he was not there?" Tacopina asked.
</P>
<P>
	   "You've never heard the term, 'blue wall of suicide,"' he said. "You don't
put yourself at the murder scene when two people are wanted and they only have
one."
</P>
<P>
	   The few phone calls and other actions involving Bruder show that he had no
part in any conspiracy, said his attorney, Stuart London.
</P>
<P>
	   He said the government glossed over lies and omissions by its own witnesses,
including Louima, to make its case against the three officers. "These people are
all part of 'Team Government,"' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   In her summation, Resnick slammed Volpe as a "sadistic, lying animal" whose
testimony two weeks ago was filled with falsehoods, contradictions and an
attempt to justify his acts by blaming Louima for being defiant.
</P>
<P>
	   "He didn't want to answer direct questions ... he wiggled and waggled and
went off on tangents," she told the jury. "You knew Justin Volpe was lying when
he said Thomas Wiese and not Charles Schwarz walked Abner Louima to the
bathroom."
</P>
<P>
	   Resnick focused mainly on the dozens of phone calls among the defendants in
the days and weeks after the Louima attack, which the government has cited as
evidence of feverish efforts to contrive an alibi for Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
	   She said that during the first days after the incident, the three were
"lying low and keeping their mouths shut," watching to see where police Internal
Affairs Bureau detectives were going with the investigation, but keeping in
touch by phone.
</P>
<P>
	   Among the calls were many involving Schwarz himself, with Wiese and a
friend, former officer Anthony Abbate, who described himself as having offered
advice to Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
	   "If Charles Schwarz was not in the bathroom, what was he so worried about?"
Resnick asked. "No one had been indicted yet. What are these defendants so
worried about if Charles Schwarz was not in that bathroom?"
</P>
<P>
	   Resnick also recalled that the officers had met privately with a police
union official, Michael Immitt, who testified he was unaware at the time that
the Louima torture story was front page news in that morning's papers.
</P>
<P>
	   "That is a joke," she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-28-00 1605 </TRAILER>
