<DOCNO> APW20000228.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Limbless Student Defies Disability  </HEADLINE>
   By GINNY PARKER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- Like many 23-year-olds, Hirotada Ototake goes to college,
likes basketball and looks forward to getting married someday.
</P>
<P>
	   But when he cruises down the street, he causes a sensation: girls call out
his name and strangers try to talk to him.
</P>
<P>
	   Ototake, who was born without arms and legs, is one of Japan's most famous
personalities: a best-selling author, a prime-time news anchor, a sought-after
public speaker.
</P>
<P>
	   And he is making Japan think about an issue it has long avoided -- society's
responsibilities toward the disabled.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite its tremendous wealth and technology, Japan is a very difficult
place to live for its estimated 3.2 million people with physical disabilities.
</P>
<P>
	   Obstacles to wheelchairs abound, from flights of stairs to cramped
restaurants and stores. Most train and subway stations do not have elevators --
although a law approved by the Cabinet this month aims to improve the situation.
</P>
<P>
	   By putting a human face on the issue, Ototake has made many Japanese
consider the difficulties the disabled face in a new light.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In Japan, everyone just assumes that the disabled are people you feel
sorry for,'' he said in an interview. ``But I'm not pitiful. I enjoy my life,
and I want to tell people that.''
</P>
<P>
	   Ototake gained nationwide fame in 1998 after publishing a hugely popular
autobiography that challenged traditional Japanese notions about disability.
</P>
<P>
	   The book, ``No One's Perfect,'' surprised many with its honest but upbeat
portrayal of living without limbs. With a photo of the smiling Ototake on the
cover, it describes everything from the difficulties of navigating a wheelchair
in the snow to the author's joy at receiving his first love letter.
</P>
<P>
	   The book has sold 4.4 million copies in Japan and has been translated into
three languages. An English version will be released in the United States in
September.
</P>
<P>
	   Ototake writes that he's come to think of disability as nothing more than
being fat or thin, tall or short. He doesn't deny that some things are hard for
him, but tries to keep busy instead of getting depressed.
</P>
<P>
	   And busy he is.
</P>
<P>
	   Along with the writing and TV appearances, Ototake says he particularly
enjoys speaking to grade school students because they aren't afraid to ask blunt
questions.
</P>
<P>
	   He's about to graduate from one of Japan's most prestigious universities,
although he admits his hectic schedule leaves him little time to study for final
exams.
</P>
<P>
	   His high profile is in itself a challenge to tradition in this often
conformist society, where many disabled people stay at home and out of sight, or
are shunted off to special education, where activists say they learn little
about how to function in the real world.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The Japanese have trouble accepting people who are different,'' Ototake
said. ``This makes it a hard place to live.''
</P>
<P>
	   But little by little, that appears to be changing:
</P>
<P>
	   -- The Winter Paralympics in Nagano brought the issue into the national
spotlight in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   -- In Osaka, Japan's second-largest city, Taihen, a group of physically
disabled dancers, is winning attention at home and international acclaim with
their performances.
</P>
<P>
	   -- The most popular prime-time drama on television this season, ``Beautiful
Life,'' tells the story of a love affair between a hairdresser and a young woman
who uses a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
	   Ototake, however, has been the most effective agent of change.
</P>
<P>
	   Thanks to an elementary school teacher who forced him to get out of his
wheelchair, he learned to walk by scooting along the ground. He writes by
holding a pen between his cheek and the stub of his left arm.
</P>
<P>
	   On his first day of middle school, Ototake stunned his parents by joining
the basketball team.
</P>
<P>
	   ``You alone decide if you're going to be happy,'' Ototake said. ``Of course,
I sometimes wish I looked as good as some Hollywood star, but who doesn't?''
</P>
<P>
	   Makoto Nakazawa, a physically disabled activist and employee at a large
manufacturing company, says it's optimism like this that accounts for Ototake's
appeal among the Japanese.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In Japan, the disabled and the able-bodied live in separate worlds,'' he
said. ``This book has lowered the wall a little.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 1607 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000228.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Journal Register Co. To Expand  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Journal Register Co. said Monday it plans to sell its
newspapers in Illinois, Missouri and Ohio to boost its stock.
</P>
<P>
	   The Ohio properties to be sold are four daily newspapers with total daily
circulation of 125,825 and Sunday circulation of 140,532: The News-Herald (Lake
County), The Morning Journal (Lorain), The Times Reporter (Dover-New
Philadelphia) and The Independent (Massillon).
</P>
<P>
	   The Missouri and Illinois properties include the Suburban Newspapers of
greater St. Louis, the largest weekly newspaper group in the United States with
distribution of approximately 1.7 million, and The Telegraph (Alton, Ill.), a
seven-day newspaper with daily circulation of 28,048 and Sunday circulation of
30,110.
</P>
<P>
	   The company said the sale will demonstrate Journal Register's underlying
value, which the board of directors said is not reflected in its stock price.
</P>
<P>
	   "The sale of our Midwest properties will increase our financial flexibility
and enable us to further realize shareholder value," Robert Jelenic, Journal
Register chairman, president and chief executive officer, said in a prepared
statement.
</P>
<P>
	   Shares of the Trenton-based Journal Register Co. were trading at $12.12
1/2,, up 25 cents a share in late trading on the New York Stock Exchange -- near
its 52-week low of $11.37 1/2 and well below the 52-week high of $23.
</P>
<P>
	   The company will not sell any newspaper unless it gets "satisfactory
agreements with respect to price and terms," said Jean B. Clifton, Journal
Register executive vice president. Clifton said the company intends to use the
proceeds initially to reduce debt and for other corporate purposes, including
the company's share buyback program.
</P>
<P>
	   If all of its newspapers in the three states are sold, Journal Register will
be left with 20 daily newspapers with total daily circulation of approximately
483,000 and Sunday circulation of about 449,000, and 143 non-daily publications
with total distribution of more than 2.2 million clustered in five areas in the
Northeast.
</P>
<P>
	   Journal Register's properties include the New Haven Register, Connecticut's
second-largest daily and Sunday newspaper, and 194 non-daily publications. The
company had 1999 total revenues of $470 million.
</P>
<P>
	   It operates in seven regions: Connecticut; Philadelphia and its surrounding
areas; Ohio; Greater St. Louis; central New England; and the Capital-Saratoga
and Mid-Hudson regions of New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Journal Register's announcement is the third large newspaper company
divestiture announcement this month.
</P>
<P>
	   Last Friday, The New York Times Co. said it plans to sell seven of its
smaller newspapers and the nine telephone directories that are part of its
Regional Newspaper Group.
</P>
<P>
	   The Thomson Corp. of Canada announced Feb. 15 that it was selling its U.S.
newspapers, made up mainly of 49 local and regional dailies with circulations of
less than 50,000. Thomson is also putting up for sale five dailies in Canada and
more than 75 non-daily newspapers, most of which are based in the United States.
Its U.S. newspapers have been grouped into 21 regional clusters, the largest
being in Ohio, Wisconsin and Indiana.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
