<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Capano appeals conviction  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) - Lawyers for Thomas Capano filed an appeal Monday
that claims the wealthy, politically connected lawyer convicted of killing his
mistress did not get a fair trial.
<P>
	   Capano was sentenced to death last March for first-degree murder in the 1996
killing of Anne Marie Fahey, a secretary to Gov. Tom Carper.
</P>
<P>
	   The 140-page appeal was based on several arguments, including a claim that
now retired Superior Court Judge William Swain Lee erred when he refused to
instruct jurors on lesser charges such as manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
	   That is important because Capano claimed the killing was an accident.
</P>
<P>
	   "The trial judge made a mistake and should have given the jury more than an
all-or-nothing choice," said Capano attorney Joseph Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors contend Capano shot Fahey, then stuffed her body in a cooler,
loaded it on a boat in Stone Harbor, N.J., and dumped it in the Atlantic Ocean.
Without a body or a murder weapon, prosecutors relied on circumstantial evidence
to prove that Capano planned to kill Fahey because she wanted to end their
affair.
</P>
<P>
	   After denying any knowledge of Fahey's death for 2 1/2 years, Capano
admitted at trial that he disposed of Fahey's body. But he said another
mistress, Deborah MacIntyre, accidentally shot Fahey in a jealous, suicidal
rage.
</P>
<P>
	   MacIntyre denied the allegation and testified for the prosecution. Two of
Capano's brothers also testified against him.
</P>
<P>
	   Fahey's body has never been recovered.
</P>
<P>
	   In their appeal, Capano's lawyers also argued that Lee, who is now running
for governor, made a mistake when he let 11 witnesses recount statements that
Fahey made to them about her volatile, three-year affair with Capano. The appeal
says this was hearsay and should not have been allowed.
</P>
<P>
	   Chief Justice E. Norman Veasey gave Capano's lawyers an extra month to file
the appeal and allowed it to be longer than the 35 pages permitted under state
Supreme Court rules.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
