<HEADLINE> Cuba Festival Lures Cigar Lovers  </HEADLINE>
   By ANITA SNOW Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HAVANA (AP) -- Cuba's world-famous tobacco lured hundreds of cigar
aficionados from around the globe this week for the island's second annual cigar
festival.
</P>
<P>
	   About 800 were expected at the inauguration cocktail party Monday night of
the Second International Habano Festival.
</P>
<P>
	   Those invited included editors of cigar magazines, tobacco sellers and
connoisseurs of Cuba's well-known cigar brands -- including Cohiba, Romeo y
Julieta, Partagas and others.
</P>
<P>
	   Aside from being serenaded by Afro-Cuban rhythms, participants could expect
during the five-day event to visit tobacco fields, cigar factories, and a trade
fair, said Ana Lopez, marketing director of the Cuban tobacco company Habanos
S.A.
</P>
<P>
	   Nine new cigar brands were to make their debut at a final, formal dinner on
Friday at the Pabexpo convention center. Cuba's government-controlled tobacco
industry already markets 34 brands.
</P>
<P>
	   Also during the $350-a-plate dinner, seven wooden humidors fashioned by
Cuban artisans and signed by President Fidel Castro are to be auctioned off.
</P>
<P>
	   Castro himself attended the dinner held last year during the first
international festival.
</P>
<P>
	   The festival is being held as the Cuban government celebrates one of its
best harvests in 20 years. State news reports said the 1999-2000 harvest, which
is ending now, is expected to yield about 40,000 metric tons of tobacco. The
reports did not give statistics from previous harvests.
</P>
<P>
	   Cuba exported 148 million cigars last year, of which 128 million were
hand-rolled and 20 million were machine-rolled, Manuel Garcia, vice president of
Habanos S.A. told a news conference last week.
</P>
<P>
	   He said that western Europe is the largest market for Cuban cigars --
accounting for 90 million cigars, or 65.5 percent of the total. Within Europe,
the biggest consumers in 1999 were Spain, consuming 43 million cigars, and
France, which bought 17.8 million.
</P>
<P>
	   The next largest regional market is the Americas and the Caribbean, which
accounted for 18.1 million cigars last year. That total included cigars sold at
duty free shops in Cuba and airports throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
	   The biggest potential market for Cuban cigars -- the United States --
remains closed because of a U.S. trade embargo nearly four decades old.
</P>
<P>
	   Garcia estimated that six million Cuban cigars enter the United States each
year as contraband.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 1628 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000228.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New bid, questions likely to delay nuke plant sale  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Under criticism from state legislators and
uncertainty about a tempting, 11th-hour counteroffer, the New York Power
Authority is not likely to approve the sale of its two nuclear power plants
Tuesday to a New Orleans company, top executives said.
<P>
	   The Power Authority had signed an agreement in principle earlier this month
to sell the FitzPatrick and Indian Point 3 plants to Entergy Corp. for $638
million. The authority seemed likely to close the deal during a meeting of the
authority's board Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   But a $686 million counteroffer last week from Dominion Resources of
Richmond, Va., muddied the waters. And Democratic legislators on Monday raised a
laundry list of alleged problems with the Power Authority's arrangement with
Entergy that Assemblyman Richard Brodsky said should "blow up" the tentative,
non-binding deal with the Louisiana company.
</P>
<P>
	   Legislators at Monday's hearing urged caution in reaching the sale which
they said would represent the largest liquidation of state holdings in New
York's history.
</P>
<P>
	   Power Authority President Eugene Zeltman agreed at a state Assembly hearing
that several questions about the sale of the two nuclear plants exist, perhaps
too many for the board to go forward with a vote on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   "If it's still as fluid tomorrow morning as it is now, then we probably
won't go forward," Zeltman said.
</P>
<P>
	   One thing complicating the situation is that the Power Authority has been
barred for two weeks ending Tuesday from talking to Dominion or any other
company about purchasing the plants. That came under an exclusivity deal it made
with Entergy when reaching an agreement in principle for the purchase on Feb.
14.
</P>
<P>
	   "How can you responsibly close on a deal when you can't talk to one of the
bidders?" Brodsky asked.
</P>
<P>
	   Zeltman acknowledged that not being able to get more details from Dominion
officials about their counteroffer has hindered the authority's attempt to
analyze it.
</P>
<P>
	   Brodsky and state Assemblyman Paul Tonko, a Democrat who chairs the
Assembly's energy committee, called on Power Authority Chairman Clarence
Rappleyea to not accept any offer for the two nuclear plants without holding an
auction for the facilities or at least running a competitive bidding process.
</P>
<P>
	   The fact that a richer counteroffer for the plants emerged shows the
properties are desirable and no one really knows how much the authority could
ultimately get for them, legislators said.
</P>
<P>
	   "We don't know what it's worth because we never bid it out," Brodsky said.
"We should be going out there and seeing if there is a third party willing to
offer $150 million more."
</P>
<P>
	   Later, he told reporters that the Power Authority "could have done better
with this plant (sale) on eBay."
</P>
<P>
	   Brodsky and Tonko also assailed the tentative Power Authority-Entergy pact
on other grounds.
</P>
<P>
	   They said the two New York plants would be operated by a limited liability
corporation set up by Entergy to reduce its legal exposure in case of a
catastrophic accident, and not Entergy itself. That raises questions whether the
mother company's best talent would be used operating the New York plants.
</P>
<P>
	   The legislators also said the authority, and not Entergy, would be left
liable if decommissioning costs for the plants are higher than expected.
</P>
<P>
	   The James A. FitzPatrick plant is on the shore of Lake Ontario north of
Syracuse. Indian Point 3 is in New York City's northern suburbs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-28-00 1630 </TRAILER>
