<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Navy Assured on Missile Program Role  </HEADLINE>
   By TOM RAUM Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Navy will have an important role in the nation's
eventual national missile defense system, even if early stages envision only
land-based interceptors, the director of the program told Congress on Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Air Force Lt. Gen. Ronald T. Kadish told the Senate Armed Services Committee
that he shares concerns expressed by Adm. Jay Johnson, the chief of naval
operations, that ship-launched interceptors not be ruled out.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We have to be careful we don't put in barriers'' to Navy involvement, he
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Kadish agreed with Republican senators on the committee that a ship-based
missile defense would add to the effectiveness of the program, intended to
provide all 50 states with a limited defense against a ballistic missile attack.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, Kadish said the Pentagon did not envision a Navy component until year
2010 or later.
</P>
<P>
	   He also said Pentagon advisers suggested that including a sea-based option
could be viewed as a violation of the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty with
Moscow. The treaty prohibits either country from building a national missile
defense system, although it allows certain limited defenses.	   Although the
Navy is proceeding with development of a high-altitude intercepter design,
planning for the basic national missile defense program is presently focused on
a land-based decision.
</P>
<P>
	   President Clinton has said he will decide this summer on whether to go ahead
with construction of such a system.
</P>
<P>
	   That timetable still holds, although failure of a scheduled test in May
could make recommending that the president make a decision this summer ``a
difficult argument to make,'' said Kadish.
</P>
<P>
	   Kadish was grilled about the Navy's role after disclosure of a confidential
memo to Defense Secretary William Cohen by Johnson. In the memo, first reported
in Monday's editions of the Washington Post, the Navy's top officer challenged
the Pentagon plan for a land-based-only missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
	   He warned that sticking with a land-based-only system ``would not be in the
best long-term interests of our country.''
</P>
<P>
	   Under the current timetable, the Pentagon hopes to have the first 100
interceptors in Alaska by 2005 if the president gives the go-ahead.
</P>
<P>
	   Although the United States so far has spent some $60 billion on research and
development of the system, test performances have been mixed. An interceptor
failed its most recent test, last Jan. 18, when a plumbing leak caused it to
miss its target.
</P>
<P>
	   A ship-based option has a support among Republicans in Congress.
</P>
<P>
	   Kadish said the Pentagon hoped to incorporate the Navy's high-altitude
interceptor in the overall program ``sometime after 2010.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``No one system can do it all under all circumstances. Even though we may
start off with a land-based system, ... we need a family of systems,'' Kadish
said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``You wouldn't know it, reading this,'' said Sen. Bob Smith, R-N.H., holding
up a Pentagon chart of the program that showed no Navy component.
</P>
<P>
	   The Pentagon is expected to spending some $12.7 billion over the next six
years on the program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 1634 </TRAILER>
