<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hundreds of Ice-Fishermen Rescued  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Hundreds of anxious fishermen spent a night on disintegrating
ice floes in Europe's largest lake, waiting for rescuers to arrive in
helicopters and boats. Six people drowned as the ice broke up, but some 900
others were rescued, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The fishermen were trapped on Lake Ladoga, northeast of St. Petersburg, when
the ice started breaking up Sunday. The lake, which covers 6,700 square miles,
is a popular ice-fishing spot for Russians who gather on its frozen surface
every winter.
</P>
<P>
	   The trapped fishermen huddled in small groups on bobbing ice floes, some
within inches of frigid water that can kill a person in minutes.
</P>
<P>
	   Villagers hurried to bring boats out of winter storage, watched by nervous
relatives on shore. Helicopters circled over the lake, rescuing anglers, but
also kicking up sprays of numbing water with their rotors.
</P>
<P>
	   To get close to the helicopters without slipping, many of the fishermen had
to crawl on their bellies across the ice, pulling themselves along with picks.
</P>
<P>
	   In all, 911 people were rescued, but 759 of them had to wait until Monday to
be taken off the ice, said Marina Ryklina, a spokeswoman for the Ministry of
Emergency Situations. The six people who drowned were all fishermen, said
another ministry spokesman, Viktor Beltsov.
</P>
<P>
	   Seven cars also plunged through the ice on Sunday and Monday, the ITAR-Tass
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
	   Ryklina said Monday that 26 ice-fishermen were rescued in a separate
operation in the Gulf of Finland.
</P>
<P>
	   Ice-fishing is highly popular in Russia, both for sport and as a food
source, and thousands of anglers become stranded on drifting floes every year.
Many of them are carried out to sea before rescuers can reach them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
