<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alleged Bosnia Camp Heads on Trial  </HEADLINE>
   By JEROME SOCOLOVSKY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) -- Their faces still haunt. The skeletal torsos
and lifeless expressions of men lined up at an iron ore mine turned into a
Bosnian prison camp were chillingly reminiscent of the emaciated Jewish
survivors photographed at the close of World War II.
</P>
<P>
	   When war correspondents discovered the starving Bosnians at Omarska camp in
1992, the news footage jolted the world's conscience and prompted calls for
intervention to stop Balkan ``ethnic cleansing.''
</P>
<P>
	   On Monday, the images were shown to judges at the Yugoslav war crimes
tribunal, where the Serb policemen who allegedly ran the camp went on trial
before the U.N. court set up in response to the global outcry to punish the
perpetrators of Balkan atrocities.
</P>
<P>
	   It is the 7-year-old tribunal's first case to deal directly with what
prosecutors call a ``system of concentration camps'' within a deliberate
strategy to rid northern Bosnia of non-Serbs.
</P>
<P>
	   Three defendants, Miroslav Kvocka, 43, Milojica Kos, 36, and Mlado Radic,
47, are accused of running Omarska as commandants and shift commanders. The
fourth, taxi driver Zoran Zigic, 41, is accused of torturing and murdering
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
	   If found guilty, the defendants face life imprisonment in a European jail.
All four have pleaded innocent.
</P>
<P>
	   In his opening statement Monday, prosecutor Grant Niemann, a former
Australian war crimes investigator, painted a horrifying picture of Omarska and
the nearby Keraterm and Trnopolje camps, where hundreds died as a result of
murders, torture, rapes and beatings in the spring and summer of 1992.
</P>
<P>
	   New arrivals were beaten with batons and rifle butts and jammed into
stiflingly hot rooms with no beds and meager sanitary facilities, Niemann said
as he pointed to a replica of the Omarska complex.
</P>
<P>
	   Although a predominantly male prison, several dozen women were kept in the
administration building, where they were forced to clean floors covered with
blood, hair and teeth, and were raped nightly by guards, the prosecutor said.
</P>
<P>
	   Interrogations in the camp's first-aid building, known as the White House,
ended in murder almost daily.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Just about every morning ... at least five to ten dead bodies, and often
many more, were piled upon each other outside the White House to be carried away
by trucks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Niemann showed the court slides of corpses with ``blunt object injuries and
bullet wounds to the head,'' exhumed from a mass grave next to a demolished
mosque in a nearby village.
</P>
<P>
	   For all the horrors, it won't be an open-and-shut case.
</P>
<P>
	   Unlike many cases before this tribunal, in which witnesses testified to
seeing defendants commit war crimes, the case against the alleged camp bosses
rests largely on acts they didn't commit with their own hands.
</P>
<P>
	   That raises the matter of command responsibility, which has vexed war crimes
prosecutions going back to the Nuremberg trials of Nazi officials after World
War II. Who is ultimately responsible for atrocities? Commanders who give the
orders? Or those who carry them out?
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors contend Kvocka -- as Omarska commander through June 1992 and
later as deputy commander -- was ultimately responsible for much of what
happened. Kos and Radic, described as shift commanders, ordered guards to beat
prisoners and sometimes participated themselves, prosecutors maintain.
</P>
<P>
	   The three men, they say, ``exercised the power of life and death over the
detainees,'' and acted in full knowledge that all three prison camps were
integral to the Serb leadership's strategy of ``ethnic cleansing.''
</P>
<P>
	   Defense attorneys are expected to rebut the argument by claiming their
clients are scapegoats for the tribunal's inability to apprehend the alleged
architects of that strategy.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite repeated calls by the tribunal for the arrest of the most senior
figures on the Serb side, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, former Bosnian
Serb leader Radovan Karadzic and military chief Ratko Mladic remain free men.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The tribunal may not be guided by taking the line of the least resistance
and desist from prosecuting the real culprits,'' defense attorney Toma Fila said
in a pretrial brief.
</P>
<P>
	   He maintains the role of his client, Radic, ``must be considered from the
perspective of a simple man with ... his intention to preserve the bare life of
his family and of his own in a turbulent and violent time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 1638 </TRAILER>
