<HEADLINE> Austria's Haider Reportedly Resigns  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- Joerg Haider, the politician known for his
anti-foreigner statements and past praise of Nazi employment policies, resigned
Monday as head of the far-right Freedom Party, the Austria Press Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
	   The agency quoted unidentified party sources at a closed-door meeting of the
group's national leadership. Party officials would not confirm the report
pending a news conference later Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   APA said Haider, who holds no post in the national government, would
continue as governor of Carinthia province. The move was seen as an attempt to
reduce international criticism of the coalition government between Haider's
rightists and the center-right Austrian People's Party.
</P>
<P>
	   Speaking to reporters before Monday's meeting, Peter Sichrovsky, the Freedom
Party's European Union representative, said Haider had mentioned stepping down
over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Already on Saturday, he mentioned it in an internal party discussion,''
Sichrovsky said. ``He has already achieved more than anyone else, and if that is
his decision, then we must respect it.''
</P>
<P>
	   Haider has led the Freedom Party since 1986.
</P>
<P>
	   Austria has come under severe international criticism since the Freedom
Party, along with the conservative Austrian People's Party, took power earlier
this month. The 14 other European Union members have moved to isolate Austria
diplomatically, mostly due to Haider's anti-foreigner stance and remarks about
the Nazi regime.
</P>
<P>
	   Haider remains popular with many Austrians and within the party he nearly
single-handedly built up from a small, unknown group to the second-largest
political force in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
