<HEADLINE> U.S. Warplanes Bomb Iraqi System  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) -- Iraq said Monday that U.S. and British jets bombed
civilian targets while patrolling the northern no-fly zone, but reported no
damage or casualties.
</P>
<P>
	   The planes targeted ``civilian and service installations'' in the area, a
spokesman for the Iraqi Air Defense Force said, without specifying the sites.
</P>
<P>
	   Iraqi gunners opened fire on the planes, which entered northern Iraqi
airspace in 14 waves, the spokesman said in a statement, which was carried by
the official Iraqi News Agency. He also said the planes penetrated Iraqi
airspace in the south, but reported no incidents there.
</P>
<P>
	   Reacting to the Iraqi statement, a spokesman for Operation Northern Watch in
the southern Turkish base of Incirlik said the allied planes had fired only on
the Iraqi air-defense system and only in self-defense.
</P>
<P>
	   The Iraqi forces fired anti-aircraft artillery from a site west of Bashiqah,
250 miles north of Baghdad, according to a statement from the Germany-based U.S.
European Command.
</P>
<P>
	   All allied planes left the area safely, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. and British planes have been enforcing no-fly zones in northern and
southern Iraq since shortly after the 1991 Gulf War to protect Shiite Muslims
and Kurds from the forces of President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
	   Iraq, which does not recognize the zones, has challenged the planes since
December 1998 by targeting the aircraft with surface-to-air missiles and
anti-aircraft artillery.
</P>
</TEXT>
