<HEADLINE> Detained Reporter Flown to Moscow  </HEADLINE>
   By NABI ABDULAYEV Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MAKHACHKALA, Russia (AP) -- Radio Liberty correspondent Andrei Babitsky,
whose detention by Russia sparked international concern, was being flown from
the capital of Dagestan to Moscow on Monday, the radio station reported.
</P>
<P>
	   The move came hours after acting President Vladimir Putin sought to defuse
the controversy by saying the reporter should be freed. But a Radio Liberty
spokesman said the station did not know whether Babitsky would be released once
he arrived in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
	   The spokesman, who did not give his name, said Babitsky was taken from the
Interior Ministry offices in Makhachkala, where he had been held since Friday,
and put on a plane for Moscow. He said he did not know at which of the capital's
airports the plane was to land.
</P>
<P>
	   Babitsky's wife and lawyer, both in Makhachkala, were not informed of his
departure, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
	   Spokesmen for the Interior Ministry in Moscow and Makhachkala declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
	   Babitsky, whose reporting from the rebel side in Chechnya angered Russian
officials, was detained in Chechnya in January and turned over to rebels in
exchange for captured Russian soldiers. Many of Babitsky's colleagues doubted
the government's portrayal of the exchange, and feared he had been killed.
</P>
<P>
	   Babitsky resurfaced Friday in the custody of officials in Makhachkala, the
capital of the Russian republic of Dagestan, which borders Chechnya. He was
charged with carrying a forged Azerbaijani passport, and officials also took up
earlier charges of Babitsky's alleged links with Chechen rebels.
</P>
<P>
	   Babitsky's lawyers have pressed for his release, citing poor health. But
investigators have turned down the plea.
</P>
<P>
	   Putin stepped into the case Monday, telling the Interior Ministry and the
prosecutor-general's office that Babitsky should not be held in custody,
Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
	   But echoing the government's contention that some accounts of the war in
Chechnya have been politically motivated, Putin accused Babitsky of trying to
sell the rebels' point of view.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He handled this task pretty well,'' Putin was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
	   Another of Babitsky's lawyers, Genri Reznik, said Putin's involvement was
certain to help the reporter's case, but added that there should have been no
need for such high-level interference.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Does the head of state need to interfere for this question to be solved
according to law?'' Reznik said on the Echo of Moscow radio station. ``Don't you
think that this is a situation from a psychiatric asylum?''
</P>
<P>
	   Foreign officials have pressed Russia to clear up the case, saying
Babitsky's detention adds to concern over alleged human rights violations in
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
	   Reznik suggested Russian officials were trying to smear Babitsky to justify
their handling of the case. The government would like to show that Babitsky ``is
such a terrible person, that he is generally an enemy ... and that toward him
such actions were justified,'' Reznik said.
</P>
<P>
	   Putin insisted that investigators handled the case strictly according to the
law, Interfax reported. However, he said he told Interior Minister Vladimir
Rushailo that ``it is inexpedient to hold Babitsky in custody, and I asked him
to deal with this case more carefully.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
