<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flight Cos. Fight For China Routes  </HEADLINE>
    By JUSTIN BACHMAN AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ATLANTA (AP) -- Delta Air Lines shuttles people and United Parcel Service
hauls freight to the far points of the world. Rarely do their businesses meet.
</P>
<P>
	   But now the Atlanta-based companies find themselves competing for the right
to fly to China, a gold mine of future business that American firms are
scrambling to tap.
</P>
<P>
	   Two other applicants, American Airlines and Polar Air Cargo, round out the
foursome of airlines hoping to launch China service.
</P>
<P>
	   The Department of Transportation will award a new route designation to one
of the four, along with up to 10 round-trip flights weekly. The three American
carriers that now fly to China -- Northwest, United and Federal Express -- also
have applied for the additional flights.
</P>
<P>
	   American, Delta, UPS and Polar plan to file the last of their arguments
Tuesday on why they should win the rights. Each company will then have until
March 28 to rebut its rivals' claims.
</P>
<P>
	   The DOT will award the route and flight frequencies during the summer,
spokesman Bill Mosley said Monday. The new flights are scheduled to begin April
1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
	   With two passenger carriers and two cargo carriers applying, one of the
first decisions will be which enterprise would better serve consumers.
</P>
<P>
	   "Anything that somebody can argue is in the public's interest we'll
certainly take into consideration," Mosley said.
</P>
<P>
	   Kevin Montgomery, vice president of government and industry affairs for Long
Beach, Calif.-based Polar, said the application process has been unprecedented
because of China's commercial potential. China is working to enter the World
Trade Organization and could receive permanent status as a most-favored-nation
trading partner of the United States this year.
</P>
<P>
	   Under an April 1999 aviation treaty, China and the U.S. agreed to double the
number of passenger and cargo flights among all U.S. airlines from 27 to 54 by
2001. The Department of Transportation awarded 17 additional routes to United,
Northwest and FedEx last year.
</P>
<P>
	   No future flights have been negotiated, which makes the current competition
even more crucial, spokesmen for the four applicants said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Polar's campaign has been dwarfed by spending among its larger rivals,
Montgomery said, calling it "a David and Goliath difference."
</P>
<P>
	   "Our hope is that it would be judged on the merits, not the amount of money
spent on public relations efforts," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Unlike American, Delta and UPS, Polar is seeking only six of the 10 routes.
</P>
<P>
	   Delta said it would offer the only nonstop flight from New York to Beijing,
shaving 10 hours from the usual travel time. That flight would begin in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
	   Delta and American, based in Fort Worth, Texas, also argue that they'll
carry cargo as well as people, while UPS and Polar will not transport people.
</P>
<P>
	   Scott Yohe, Delta's senior vice president of governmental affairs, said his
company considers cross-town rival UPS its biggest adversary for the routes.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're not discounting American. Obviously, Chicago is an important
gateway," Yohe said. "But we feel like UPS is, at least right now, our strongest
competition."
</P>
<P>
	   With 10 routes, UPS says it would fly six times weekly from Ontario, Calif.,
to Beijing and Shanghai and four times weekly from Newark, N.J., to Shanghai,
with a stop in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
	   American wants to fly daily from its Chicago hub to Shanghai and thrice
weekly from Chicago to Beijing. Polar wants to fly four times per week from New
York to several Chinese cities and twice weekly from Los Angeles to Beijing and
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
	   "The potential for the Chinese market is huge," said American spokesman Mark
Slitt. "If you're going to be a global player in this century then you have to
be in Asia."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 1655 </TRAILER>
