<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Census Works To Repair Image  </HEADLINE>
   By GENARO C. ARMAS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Officials with the Census Bureau -- the agency charged
with compiling accurate statistics on the population -- worked Monday to repair
the bureau's public image after it sent out 115 million census mailings with the
wrong addresses.
</P>
<P>
	   A printing glitch caused an extra digit to be printed before each
recipient's street address, Census Bureau Director Kenneth Prewitt said. For
instance, instead of reading ''10 Main St.'', the address would read ''110 Main
St.''
</P>
<P>
	   The error only affected mailings sent to households reminding them of the
upcoming head count, and they will get to the intended addresses anyway, the
bureau insisted. The actual census surveys, which will be sent out in late
March, have the correct addresses, Prewitt said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The problem is cosmetic rather than operational. In describing the problem
as cosmetic, I do not intend to trivialize it. The public image of the census is
nearly as important as the actual operations of the census,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
	   The mailings will still go through because a computer bar code imprinted on
them, which Postal Service scanners read to sort mail, contains the right
address, allowing carriers to deliver them to the proper homes, according to
officials at the Census Bureau and the Postal Service.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, Prewitt acknowledged the mistake creates a public relations problem.
Bureau officials are putting out new ads this week urging residents to open the
census letter when it gets to their home.
</P>
<P>
	   Quality-control checks by the printer, Freedom Graphic Systems of Milton,
Wis., and government officials did not catch the mistake, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Freedom Graphic Systems had a $5.9 million contract with the Government
Printing Office to produce the mailings, and it was unclear if any money would
be refunded, said Anthony Allighen, government projects coordinator at the
company.
</P>
<P>
	   ``At this point, I don't think anybody has gone that far yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The error was first discovered last week by postal workers in New England,
officials said. Until then, Census operations had been relatively glitch-free.
</P>
<P>
	   On Monday, officials noted they were ahead of schedule in attracting 1.7
million qualified applicants to fill more than 860,000 temporary jobs -- mostly
workers who will go door-to-door this summer to get information from people who
did not mail back their surveys.
</P>
<P>
	   This is the first time the bureau is using an informational mailing in
advance of the questionnaire to publicize the census, which occurs every ten
years.
</P>
<P>
	   Congressional overseers differed on how the public would react to the error.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The Census Bureau sends an advanced notification letter with the hopes of
raising public awareness that the Census is coming, and oddly enough, this error
may help dojust that,'' said Rep. Carolyn Maloney, D-N.Y., ranking member of the
House Census subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
	   Subcommittee Chairman Rep. Dan Miller, R-Fla., said he has asked the General
Accounting Office and the Commerce Department's Inspector General's Office to
evaluate the long-term implications of the error.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 1707 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000228.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Davis Etkin admits to bribery, defrauding the government  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   SCHENECTADY, N.Y. (AP) - The former chief of the Off-Track Betting Corp.
covering 17 eastern New York counties pleaded guilty Monday to diverting funds
to pay for a lavish lifestyle and other wrongdoings.
<P>
	   Davis Etkin, 72, of Niskayuna faces 1 1/3 to 4 years in prison for charges
of defrauding the government and 2 1/3 to 7 years for bribing a witness, both
felonies. He must also pay restitution, the amount of which will be determined
following a hearing scheduled to begin March 24.
</P>
<P>
	   As part of a plea agreement before Judge Guy Tomlinson in Schenectady County
Court, Etkin admitted to diverting an undisclosed amount of corporate assets for
his own and others' personal use and participating in an attempt to bribe a
witness who was to testify against him.
</P>
<P>
	   "Guilty," Etkin, himself a licensed lawyer, said in response to each charge,
fidgiting slightly and looking mostly at the floor or at his son sitting on a
side row of the courtroom. Through his attorney, he insisted on phrasing such as
"diverting property" and "improperly charging items to OTB," rather than
stealing.
</P>
<P>
	   His son, 39-year-old Mark Etkin, has already been sentenced to three months
in jail and five years probation for offering witness Cheryl Flahive $2,100 to
lie before a grand jury investigating his father. Flahive was paid for a no-show
job at the agency. The younger Etkin served just days of his sentence before
being released on an appeal.
</P>
<P>
	   In January 1998, Etkin stepped down after 25 years as chairman and president
of the Capital District OTB amid scathing allegations of corruption within the
agency.
</P>
<P>
	   Between 1992 and 1996, state investigators said, the corporation had $3
million in net operating losses. It also had the highest total expenses in
relation to revenues than any OTB corporation in the state, and was the only one
of the state's OTBs to lose money four years in a row.
</P>
<P>
	   A report by the state Comptroller's office contrasted questionable spending
of millions of OTB dollars with anemic returns to counties meant to share in OTB
profits. The 36-page report pointed to such apparent excesses at corporation
expense as Etkin's eight cellular phones, $750,000 in complimentary meals and
luxury box seats at sporting events.
</P>
<P>
	   "For years, Davis Etkin authorized expenditures that rewarded his family,
friends and associates, and abused his position," said state Attorney General
Eliot Spitzer, whose office prosecuted Etkin. "With this plea, however, we have
demonstrated that public officials - no matter how influential or entrenched -
will be held accountable for their actions."
</P>
<P>
	   Monday's plea deal saves members of Etkin's family from further charges
relating to the OTB scandal.
</P>
<P>
	   "Davis just wanted to put it behind him and take care of himself, take care
of his family," said Stephen Coffey, Etkin's attorney.
</P>
<P>
	   The case against Davis Etkin is part of a continuing investigation by the
attorney general's office. On Wednesday, a trial begins for three men including
an OTB official indicted on felony charges of rigging bids for work contracts on
OTB venues throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
	   Albany County Executive Michael Breslin, whose task force investigating OTB
several years ago spurred state action, said that Albany and other counties in
the region missed out on millions of dollars as a result of OTB misspending.
Monday, he said he was pleased to hear that Etkin had pleaded guilty.
</P>
<P>
	   "People said, 'Come on, Michael, you can't climb that tree," Breslin said.
"My intention all along was to get every dollar of taxpayer money back to the
taxpayer."
</P>
<P>
	   Counties and municipalities sharing revenues with the Capital District OTB
include: Clinton, Montgomery, Fulton, Greene, Columbia, Rensselaer, Warren,
Herkimer, Oneida, Franklin, Madison, Washington, St. Lawrence, Essex, Cortland
and Albany counties as well as the cities of Albany and Schenectady.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
