<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HMO Reform Bill Debate To Begin  </HEADLINE>
   By KAREN GULLO Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With Americans and presidential candidates staunchly
favoring patients' rights, lawmakers are pressing to craft compromise HMO
protections without alienating politically powerful businesses. Key work begins
this week.
</P>
<P>
	   Insurers and corporations are waging a pitched battle against the proposed
legislation, arguing that giving Americans the right to sue over denial of care
will raise premiums.
</P>
<P>
	   They've even conducted their own polls suggesting many workers would lose
coverage because companies, fearing lawsuits, would stop offering health plans.
</P>
<P>
	   Lawmakers who must reconcile two versions of the legislation -- one passed
by the House that allows lawsuits and another approved by the Senate that does
not -- are caught in the crossfire of a well-heeled business lobby and the
dynamics of presidential politics.
</P>
<P>
	   Many Republicans, particularly in the Senate, oppose giving patients the
right to sue.
</P>
<P>
	   But their task became more complicated when the party's presidential
frontrunner, George W. Bush, began running ads boasting he ``delivered a
patient's bill of rights'' in Texas ``while Washington politicians deadlocked.''
</P>
<P>
	   In fact, Bush didn't even approve his state law -- it became law without his
signature.
</P>
<P>
	   But both he and his main rival, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., have declared
their support for federal legislation that permits lawsuits. And that has upped
the ante for the party's congressional leaders.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We get the Texas model thrown up at us all the time,'' said Sen. Tim
Hutchinson, R-Ark., a member of a House-Senate conference committee that meets
Thursday to begin hammering out a compromise. ``It puts added pressure on
Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Texas law, among the strongest patient protection measures in the
country, allows patients to sue their HMO for delaying or denying care if those
decisions harmed patients.
</P>
<P>
	   Republican leaders concede a compromise will have to include some provision
for lawsuits, but the question remains how far GOP senators will go.
</P>
<P>
	   Hutchinson predicted any GOP-backed right-to-sue provision would come with
lots of restrictions.
</P>
<P>
	   One possibility, similar to a Republican House bill rejected last fall,
would:
</P>
<P>
	   --allow lawsuits only after patients go through appeal panels;
</P>
<P>
	   --cap the size of damage awards;
</P>
<P>
	   --cover only the 48 million Americans whose health plans are exempt from
state regulations.
</P>
<P>
	   If pressure from Republican presidential hopefuls isn't enough, Americans
are widely in favor of new measures against health maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
	   A recent poll by the Kaiser Family Foundation and Harvard School of Public
Health showed 72 percent of voters favored patient protections. That support
dropped to 53 percent, however, if protections drove up premiums.
</P>
<P>
	   Democrats have aligned themselves with the House version of the legislation,
which drew bipartisan support, and are heaping criticism on the efforts to
prevent lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The House has passed strong, effective bipartisan legislation. The Senate
has passed a weak bill that only an insurance company could love,'' said Sen.
Edward Kennedy, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
	   President Clinton has made it clear he wants a bill that would allow
patients to sue health providers. The White House also has voiced concerns about
the House version of the legislation because it includes proposals to expand
medical savings accounts.
</P>
<P>
	   Those accounts let people set aside money, tax free, to pay routine medical
bills and the premium for a high-deductible insurance. Companies with fewer than
50 workers can offer them under a pilot test set up by Congress in 1997.
Republicans want to expand that to more Americans.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We think it's premature to be expanding in this area'' said Chris
Jennings, Clinton's chief health policy advisor.
</P>
<P>
	   Both parties face pressures from their traditional campaign donors. Trial
lawyers, which overwhelming favor Democrats, staunchly support the right to sue.
</P>
<P>
	   And business groups are warning that if Republicans give even limited rights
to sue, they'll end up in hot water with one of their biggest sources of
financial support.
</P>
<P>
	   ``With the control of Congress being such a thin margin, there's little room
for error,'' said Neil Trautwein, director of employment policy at the National
Association of Manufacturers. ``They can't save the store by decimating the
employer-based health care system.''
</P>
<P>
	   A third of companies in an insurance-industry sponsored survey said they
would stop offering health plans to all or some of their workers if the House
bill passed.
</P>
<P>
	   The Congressional Budget Office estimated that the House bill would increase
premiums for employer-sponsored plans by an average of 4.1 percent, while the
Senate version would result in a 1.3 percent rise.
</P>
<P>
	   Hutchinson said some lawmakers weren't buying the argument that companies
will cut off workers' health benefits.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Most members think that's a scare tactic,'' Hutchinson told a group of NAM
members last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 1721 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
