<HEADLINE> Copper Down, Gasoline, Gas Up  </HEADLINE>
    By DAVE CARPENTER AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Copper futures tumbled to nearly a four-month low Monday amid investor
uneasiness over a possible tightening of the U.S. economy that could hurt the
construction industry, the metal's mainstay.
</P>
<P>
	   In other markets, gasoline and natural gas prices jumped sharply and wheat
fell.
</P>
<P>
	   Copper hit a 26-month high last month on the New York Mercantile Exchange
thanks to the new housing boom, the economy's zoom and an increase in aluminum.
But prices have fallen 10 percent since then as the rosy glow on construction
has faded somewhat.
</P>
<P>
	   Higher interest rates and comments by Federal Reserve chairman Alan
Greenspan that more can be expected have put steadily increasing pressure on
copper.
</P>
<P>
	   On Monday, copper for May delivery fell 3.35 cents, or 4 percent, to 79.40
cents a pound after sinking to a 3 1/2-month low of 79.15 cents a pound.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts said there was little fresh news to cause the plunge. But when
other metals sank lower, copper jitters made it a prime candidate to be sold.
</P>
<P>
	   "There's a little bit of interest rate fear that's been kind of weighing
down the markets for a couple of weeks," said Bill O'Neill, senior futures
strategist for Merrill Lynch. "It's an accumulation of economic pressures and
concerns which have gradually been taking their toll."
</P>
<P>
	   Continuing high global inventories also are putting pressure on copper
prices.
</P>
<P>
	   Elsewhere on the New York Merc, March unleaded gasoline leaped 6 percent
higher, settling up 5.12 cents at 91.38 cents a gallon, on tight supplies ahead
of Tuesday's contract expiration.
</P>
<P>
	   Stronger cash prices pushed April natural gas up 6.9 cents to $2.686 per
1,000 cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
	   Other energy commodities retreated. April crude oil fell 22 cents to $30.13
a barrel, March heating oil fell 1.21 cent to 81.67 cents a gallon and, in
London, April Brent crude from the North Sea fell 7 cents to $27.41 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
	   Wheat prices declined by 1 percent on the Chicago Board of Trade on the
outlook for more wet weather in much of the U.S. winter wheat belt. Other grains
and soybeans were mixed.
</P>
<P>
	   Wheat for May delivery fell 2 1/2 cents to $2.56 3/4 a bushel; May corn fell
 3/4 cent to $2.20 3/4 a bushel; May oats rose  1/2 cent to $1.15 1/2 a bushel;
May soybeans rose  3/4 cent to $5.06 1/4 a bushel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
