<HEADLINE> Interest Rates Mixed in T-Bill Sale  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    WASHINGTON (AP) -- Interest rates on short-term Treasury securities were
mixed in Monday's auction.
</P>
<P>
	   The Treasury Department sold $9 billion in three-month bills at a discount
rate of 5.670 percent, up from 5.640 percent last week. An additional $8 billion
was sold in six-month bills at a rate of 5.765 percent -- unchanged from last
week's rate which was the highest since Feb. 7.
</P>
<P>
	   The three-month rate was the highest since May 22, 1995, when the bills sold
for 5.72 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors -- 5.831
percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling for $9,856.70 and
6.022 percent for a six-month bill selling for $9,708.50.
</P>
<P>
	   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the average yield
for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index for making changes in
adjustable rate mortgages, fell to 6.22 percent last week from 6.23 percent the
previous week.
</P>
</TEXT>
