</P>
<P>
	   Personal Income Rises in January
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Personal income grew 0.7 percent last month,
outpacing a 0.5 percent rise in spending, the Commerce Department
said today. Personal income includes wages, interest and government
benefits. Cost-of-living adjustments to Social Security payments
and other government benefits programs; pay raises for federal
workers and military personnel; and federal subsidy payments to
farmers contributed to the higher income.
</P>
<P>
	   Citigroup Co-CEO Reed To Retire
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Citigroup Inc.'s co-chairman and co-chief
executive, John S. Reed, will retire in April. Sanford I. Weill,
66, who has shared the top post with Reed, 61, will become the sole
chairman and CEO. However, he too announced that he planned to
leave the company. He said he will work with the board of directors
to find a successor within two years. One person who doesn't want
the job is Former Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, who joined
Citigroup in October. He says he wants to continue as chairman of
the executive committee of Citigroup's board. Citigroup stock was
up 1 3/8 at 49 3/8.
</P>
<P>
	   More Consumers Prefer Cell Phones
</P>
<P>
	   NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Thousands of consumers are untangling
themselves from the cords that once connected them to the outside
world. Now when they make a phone call, they use a wireless. And
wireless companies gathered this week for the Cellular
Telecommunications Industry Association say people are beginning to
embrace the idea of using a mobile phone as the primary phone.
About 2 percent of 86 million wireless subscribers use it as their
primary phone, according to the Yankee Group research firm.
</P>
<P>
	   Columbia Accepts $6B NiSource Bid
</P>
<P>
	   SPRINGFIELD, Va. (AP) -- Columbia Energy Group accepted a $6
billion takeover offer from NiSource Inc. today in a deal that
would create the largest gas company east of the Rockies. The
combined company would have 4.1 million gas, electric, water and
propane customers from the Midwest to New England. The merger, if
approved by shareholders, comes four months after Columbia rejected
a slightly higher offer from NiSource, which attempted a hostile
takeover. The agreement is worth $70 a share in cash to Columbia
shareholders, plus a security worth $2.60 per share.
</P>
