<HEADLINE> Lawmakers say Pataki underestimated state revenues  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Gov. George Pataki underestimates revenues in his
proposed budget by as much as $1.15 billion, state lawmakers announced Monday as
they released their revenue forecasts for the next state fiscal year.
<P>
	   The Democrat-controlled Assembly said Pataki's nearly $78 billion executive
budget underestimates state revenues by at least $1.15 billion. In total, the
Democratic Assembly predicted $1.25 billion in surpluses and reserves when they
added in what they called overestimated Medicaid and public assistance spending.
</P>
<P>
	   The Republican Senate said it found an additional $940 million in revenue
coming into the state that is not reflected in Pataki's spending plan.
</P>
<P>
	   When Pataki released his executive budget for fiscal 2000-01 in January,
both chambers said they would increase his spending on education and other
areas. The Assembly and Senate will likely use their revenue estimates to
justify that spending in this year's budget showdowns.
</P>
<P>
	   "Our forecast is based on the fact that New York's economy continues to grow
and expand, new jobs are being created, businesses and individuals are enjoying
a greater success and prosperity than they have in many years," Senate Majority
Leader Joseph Bruno said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bruno's Senate Republicans are expected to outline a series of tax cut
proposals this week totaling more than $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver also credited the strong economy in New York
and across the nation for the state having the extra money. "The strength of New
York's economy is suggestive of the national expansion, which is now the longest
in our history," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Technically, the Legislature and governor are supposed to come to an
agreement on available revenues by March 10 each year, but all sides have
thumbed their noses at that requirement. In addition, for the last 15 years,
lawmakers have been unable to reach a budget agreement before the start of the
state's fiscal year on April 1.
</P>
<P>
	   Assembly Minority Leader John Faso, R-Columbia, also said he believes Pataki
underestimated the state's growth. His estimate shows about $608 million in
extra revenues.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm hopeful that there will be agreement to use these resources wisely so
we can reach agreement on a prudent and balanced budget by the April 1
deadline," Faso said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
