<HEADLINE> Leadership Change at Citigroup  </HEADLINE>
    By NOELLE KNOX AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- The crowded executive suite at Citigroup Inc. is emptying
out. John S. Reed said Monday he will retire in April as co-chairman and
co-chief executive officer of the nation's largest financial services company.
His partner may not be far behind.
</P>
<P>
	   Sanford I. Weill, 66, who will become the sole chairman and CEO, said he
wants the board to find a successor within two years.
</P>
<P>
	   While there are a handful of Citigroup senior executives who will be
elbowing for the top job, one of the most likely candidates already has bowed
out.
</P>
<P>
	   Robert Rubin, 61, the former treasury secretary who joined the company in
October as the chairman of the board's executive committee, said Monday, "I will
not be CEO."
</P>
<P>
	   Shares of Citigroup rose by nearly 3 percent, or by $1.37 1/2, to $49.37 1/2
as of the 4 p.m. EST close of the New York Stock Exchange as investors applauded
the thinning ranks at the top.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's better to have one boss than two," said James Schmidt, head of the
financial team at John Hancock Funds, which owns about 1 million shares of
Citigroup. "Up to now, the two were sharing power, but one was more equal than
the other."
</P>
<P>
	   Weill has been calling the day-to-day shots since July, while Reed has
focused on the company's Internet strategy. Reed and Weill joined forces in 1998
when they combined Citicorp and Travelers Group to form a global financial giant
that could offer consumers one-stop shopping. But Reed, a staid banker, often
clashed with Weill, a Wall Street dealmaker.
</P>
<P>
	   Reed, now 61, said Monday he had planned to retire at 60, but stayed to help
shepherd the integration of the companies that now include Citibank; Travelers
insurance and the Salomon Smith Barney brokerage and investment banking house.
</P>
<P>
	   While rumored for months, Reed said he first discussed his departure with
Weill in January. The final decision was made Sunday at a board meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   "It was pretty clear, I was the one who most wanted to retire," Reed told
reporters in a conference call. He plans to leave as of the April 18
shareholders meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   Monday's announcement came less than a week after Citigroup's chief
financial officer, Heidi G. Miller, said she was leaving to join the Internet
company Priceline.com.
</P>
<P>
	   Reed, who was named CEO in 1984, ends a 35-year career at the bank. He has
seen a complete transformation of the industry, from the toaster-giveaway days
of regulated interest rates to fashioning the merger that brought the end to
Depression Era prohibitions against the combination of banks, brokerage and
insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
	   As a banker, Reed was quick to embrace automated teller machines, credit
cards and electronic banking, said Donald G. Ogilvie, executive vice president
of the American Bankers Association.
</P>
<P>
	   Under Reed's watch, Citigroup has prospered, with earnings from operations
soaring almost 57 percent last year to almost $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   Reed also has profited, earning $9.5 million in salary and bonus, plus $16
million in stock in 1998, the most recent figures available. He will leave with
more than 4.7 million shares of Citigroup's stock.
</P>
<P>
	   "John is going to be one of the biggest shareholders," Weill joked. "We want
to keep him happy so he doesn't complain."
</P>
<P>
	   But Weill wasn't always so concerned with Reed's mood. The two have very
different management styles. Reed has confessed to early friction in their
relations, but later said they had learned to get along.
</P>
<P>
	   Weill began his career as a messenger at the investment firm Bear Stearns
Cos. in 1955. Five years later, he borrowed $200,000 and with three friends
formed a brokerage that, through acquisitions, became Shearson Loeb Rhoades. In
1981, he sold Shearson to American Express. Two years later he was president of
American Express.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1985, Weill quit as it became clear he would not succeed James Robinson
III as CEO. A year later, he started the company that would become Travelers.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors were not surprised to see Weill strengthen his grip on Citigroup,
nor were they disappointed.
</P>
<P>
	   "Sandy has a history of delivering to shareholders. He doesn't get bogged
down in bureaucracy. He's a doer," said Schmidt, the portfolio manager at John
Hancock.
</P>
<P>
	   The question Monday, however, was, Who will be the next "doer" at Citigroup?
</P>
<P>
	   Among the senior ranks, analysts handicapping the race named Michael
Carpenter, head of the Citigroup's investment bank; Pete Dawkins, vice chairman
of Citibank's private bank; Tom Jones, head of Citigroup's global investment
management and private banking group; Bob Lipp, head of Citigroup's global
consumer business; and Victor Menezes, head of Citibank's corporate bank.
</P>
<P>
	   "Sandy has a couple of years to groom that leader," said Scott Birnbaum, a
vice president at Mercer Management Consulting. But he also said Weill could
fill the post by acquiring another financial services company, such as American
Expesss, which has a strong candidate in CEO Kenneth I. Chenault.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 1754 </TRAILER>
