<HEADLINE> Democrat Fund-Raiser Case Criticized  </HEADLINE>
   By PETE YOST Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Prosecutors brought charges against a low-level
Democratic fund-raiser because of her longtime association with Vice President
Al Gore, a defense lawyer suggested Monday in federal court.
</P>
<P>
	   The Justice Department countered that Los Angeles fund-raiser Maria Hsia
``used 40 to 50 people'' to hide the true sources of more than $100,000 in
campaign donations to the 1996 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
	   ``She cannot try to get away with it, when she is the one who orchestrated
the entire scheme,'' prosecutor Eric Yaffe told the jury in closing arguments at
the trial, now in its fourth week.
</P>
<P>
	   Yaffe said Hsia, an immigration consultant, used a series of ``conduits'' to
make political donations because she ``wanted to maintain herself as a mover and
a shaker in Democratic Party circles'' by being seen as a major fund-raiser. She
was trying to promote her ``business interests,'' Yaffe said.
</P>
<P>
	   The focus of closing arguments was a 1996 fund-raising event that Gore
attended at a Buddhist temple in California, a politically embarrassing episode
for the vice president.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Why is Maria Hsia here?'' asked defense attorney Nancy Luque.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors brought the case because of Hsia's ``relationship with the vice
president'' which ``goes back to 1989. ... That is the only thing I can think
of,'' said Luque.
</P>
<P>
	   She did not elaborate on why prosecutors might have been motivated to bring
a criminal case that would inject Gore's name into the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore attended the April 29, 1996, Buddhist temple event in Hacienda Heights,
Calif. When controversy later erupted about illegal reimbursements to donors,
the vice president said that he hadn't known it was a fund-raising event. On
various occasions, Gore has said he thought it was community outreach,
finance-related or donor maintenance.
</P>
<P>
	   The day after Gore went to the temple, Hsia handed Democratic Party
fund-raising figure John Huang an envelope containing $100,000, according to
Huang's testimony at the trial. The donations were made possible because the
temple reimbursed many of the donors.
</P>
<P>
	   Luque said there is no evidence that Hsia was aware of the reimbursements.
Prosecutor John McEnany pointed out that copies of the illegally reimbursed
checks turned up in Hsia's office.
</P>
<P>
	   Hsia's fund raising dates back to the late 1980s when she raised money for
Gore, who was trying to replenish his Senate campaign coffers after he
unsuccessfully sought the Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
	   Luque said even if the jury believes that Hsia was behind some of the
reimbursements, she did not commit the crime with which she is charged five
times -- causing illegal statements to be filed with the Federal Election
Commission about the true source of campaign donations.
</P>
<P>
	   FEC forms don't even ask for the true source of donations, so ``I guess they
don't care,'' Luque said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 1801 </TRAILER>
