<HEADLINE> Thousands Commemorate Kosovo Deaths  </HEADLINE>
   By ELENA BECATOROS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LIKOSANE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- About 5,000 ethnic Albanians gathered on a
hillside overlooking this Kosovo village on Monday to commemorate the 1998
Yugoslav crackdown which triggered the province's conflict and brought NATO-led
troops to the region.
</P>
<P>
	   As a sign the violence is not over, a Serb bus in northern Kosovo ran over a
land mine that French peacekeepers fear could have been intended for them. The
nearly empty bus was damaged, but no one was injured.
</P>
<P>
	   On Feb. 28, 1998, ethnic Albanian rebels of the Kosovo Liberation Army fired
on a vehicle carrying Serb policemen, killing two and injuring two others.
Within an hour, a Serbian special anti-terrorist unit was sent into Likosane and
the neighboring village of Cirez, where the unit's members believed the
guerillas were being sheltered.
</P>
<P>
	   When the anti-terrorist unit left, more than 20 ethnic Albanians were dead.
The raid is generally regarded as the start of the 18-month Serb crackdown,
which ended when Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic accepted a Kosovo peace
plan to end 78 days of NATO air raids.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The Serbs killed many,'' Xhevded Ahmeti told the crowd gathered near the
grave site Monday. ``This came as a test for Albanians to see if they could
organize and fight.''
</P>
<P>
	   Alban Rama, 20, whose brother Zullnet was killed by Serbs just weeks before
NATO-led peacekeepers entered Kosovo in June, explained ethnic Albanians' mixed
views of the incident.
</P>
<P>
	   ``On this day, as much as we feel sad, we also feel joy,'' he said.
``Because this was the day for the beginning of the road to freedom.''
</P>
<P>
	   Despite the presence of peacekeepers in Kosovo, ethnic violence continues,
predominantly revenge-minded attacks against Serbs.
</P>
<P>
	   The Serb bus struck a land mine Monday near the ethnically tense northern
city of Kosovska Mitrovica. A French army spokesman, Lt. Matthieau Mabin, called
the placing of the mine near the Serb village of Zvecan ``terrorism.'' He noted
that peacekeepers use the road every day, suggesting that they could have been
the target.
</P>
<P>
	   Kosovska Mitrovica, about 20 miles north of Kosovo's provincial capital of
Pristina, is divided into ethnic Albanian and Serb parts and has been the scene
of ethnic unrest over the past months.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, the Yugoslav army on Monday issued a statement denying it had
strengthened its presence near the border between Montenegro and Albania, which
was recently reopened over objections by the federal government in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
	   Also on Monday, the NATO-led Kosovo force, or KFOR, announced maneuvers next
month involving a 2,000-strong ``strategic reserve force,'' which will be sent
into the province for the exercise. The force, made up of troops from Argentina,
Italy, the Netherlands, Poland, Romania and the United States, is to be deployed
on March 19.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 1802 </TRAILER>
