<HEADLINE> 2 Die in Highway Rock-Throwing  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DARMSTADT, Germany (AP) -- Assailants threw stones at cars from a pedestrian
bridge over a German highway, killing two people and injuring five others,
police said Monday. Four U.S. teenagers were detained as suspects.
</P>
<P>
	   The boys, aged 14 to 18, were apprehended at a U.S. military housing area in
this southwestern city, and one of them has admitted taking part in the attacks
late Sunday, police said.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors will seek an arrest warrant Tuesday on charges of murder and
attempted murder, a police statement said. Police said witnesses told them the
teenagers, whose names were withheld, had talked about throwing rocks from the
bridge.
</P>
<P>
	   A 20-year-old woman was killed when a baseball-sized rock smashed through
her windshield Sunday morning. Her 75-year-old grandparents riding in the car
were injured, the grandmother seriously, police said.
</P>
<P>
	   A short time later, a 41-year-old woman was killed when a rock splintered
her windshield from the same bridge.
</P>
<P>
	   In all, six cars were hit by stones thrown from the bridge over a period of
about 15 minutes police said. Three other people in the other cars received
minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors had offered a $5,000 reward for information leading to the
culprits.
</P>
<P>
	   Police said they suspected the stones had been taken from a nearby
construction site, and concentrated their search for the assailants in
surrounding neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
	   German and U.S. military police cars with megaphones drove through
residential areas Monday, including the U.S. housing area, asking anyone to come
forward who might have information or seen someone on the bridge.
</P>
<P>
	   A special police team was set up in Darmstadt, 12 miles south of Frankfurt,
to investigate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
