<HEADLINE> Amtrak To Expand Rail System  </HEADLINE>
   By LARRY MARGASAK Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Amtrak riders in Texas, Mississippi and New England may
be the first beneficiaries of an expanded rail system, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Providing details on timing, officials said that by next spring, the
Chicago-San Antonio Texas Eagle might be making daily trips instead of running
four days a week.
</P>
<P>
	   Two other major changes could be launched by the spring: a Meridian,
Miss.-Dallas leg of the New York-New Orleans Crescent; and the chance for
passengers in Connecticut, Massachusetts and Florida to travel the north-south
route without transferring in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Over the next three years, Amtrak officials told a news conference,
passengers will see a much different rail system -- one that will deliver more
mail and other commercial items, run on improved rail beds and be coordinated
with local efforts to get passengers from stations to their homes.
</P>
<P>
	   The effort to expand the rail network in 21 states rather than contract the
system is part of a grand design to have Amtrak run its daily operations without
federal subsidies by 2003.
</P>
<P>
	   However, Amtrak will continued to need government help to purchase and
improve equipment. President Clinton on Monday proposed spending $989 million in
the next fiscal year for this purpose -- an increase of 73 percent over current
levels.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There has never been a better time to expand our investment in Amtrak and
the nation's passenger railways,'' said Clinton, who met with Amtrak board
members.
</P>
<P>
	   Adopting a page from the airlines, the new system would have feeder routes
that would connect to major hubs.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to expansion on individual routes, the program calls for a
transcontinental train that would have limited stops and be designed for the
comfort of leisure travelers.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We want to grow this railroad for the traveling public,'' said Amtrak's
board chairman, Gov. Tommy Thompson of Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
	   Rail officials could not say when most of the improvements would begin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
