<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tougher Tax Shelter Rules Imposed  </HEADLINE>
    By MARTIN CRUTSINGER AP Economics Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration stepped up its attack on
corporate tax shelters Monday, imposing tougher disclosure requirements aimed at
making it easier to uncover illegal schemes estimated to cost the Treasury $10
billion annually.
</P>
<P>
	   The disclosure requirements will apply both to corporations and the tax
accountants and lawyers who market the schemes.
</P>
<P>
	   The administration also said it would ask Congress to stiffen penalties for
violation of disclosure requirements, and it announced an immediate move to shut
down a popular shelter known as a "debt straddle."
</P>
<P>
	   Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, who disclosed the proposals in a speech
to the Federal Bar Association, said the comprehensive package was aimed at
addressing "what may be the most serious compliance issue threatening the
American tax system today."
</P>
<P>
	   Tax shelters are complex plans developed by tax accountants and lawyers and
sold to corporations as a way to avoid paying taxes. The administration
estimates that illegal shelters the government has uncovered and closed over the
past decade should result in $80 billion in increased tax revenues in the next
10 years.
</P>
<P>
	   "These transactions have no goal other than to reduce a corporation's tax
liabilities. In doing so, they undermine the integrity of the tax system,"
Summers said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Treasury Department said it was putting into effect immediately three
new disclosure regulations to require corporations to report use of certain
shelters to the IRS when it files a tax return.
</P>
<P>
	   Promoters of certain shelters would have to disclose these shelters to the
government and also keep a list of businesses using the shelters that would have
to be provided to IRS agents upon request.
</P>
<P>
	   The disclosure requirements would be triggered for tax-avoidance schemes
with characteristics including a fee charged by the promoter of more than
$100,000 or confidentiality protections offered to businesses that participate.
</P>
<P>
	   Jonathan Talisman, acting assistant Treasury secretary for tax policy, said
the administration hoped that just the existence of the disclosure rules would
act as a deterrent for businesses tempted to use them.
</P>
<P>
	   The disclosure requirements come under a 1997 law passed by Congress at the
administration's urging to crack down on shelters. The administration said it
would propose new legislation this year to stiffen penalties in the tax-shelter
area including doubling the penalty from 20 percent to 40 percent for corporate
tax underreporting.
</P>
<P>
	   "Better late than never," said House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill
Archer, R-Texas. But he chided the administration for taking so long to produce
regulations needed to implement disclosure provisions of the 1997 law.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm pleased that the Treasury Department has finally used the authority
Congress gave it three years ago to identify and register corporate tax
shelters," Archer said in a statement. "We must stop abuses and shut down
illegal tax shelters."
</P>
<P>
	   The administration said the tougher penalties it is seeking in the new
legislation could raise $23 billion for the government over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
	   The "debt straddle" tax shelter the administration moved against Monday
creates an artificial tax loss by setting up two debt instruments, with the
interest on one dropping to zero while the interest on the other doubles.
</P>
<P>
	   Summers said the debt straddle was best described as a "heads I win, tails I
win" strategy to avoid paying taxes.
</P>
<P>
	   The new regulations, which will be published in the Federal Register, were
put into operation immediately on a temporary basis and could be modified, based
on public comments in coming weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 1821 </TRAILER>
