<HEADLINE> Senegal Holds Presidential Elections  </HEADLINE>
   By GLENN McKENZIE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DAKAR, Senegal (AP) -- International observers gave a thumbs up Monday to
Senegal's presidential elections, saying scattered violence and logistical
problems failed to tarnish voting in one of Africa's oldest democracies.
</P>
<P>
	   The head of observers from French-speaking nations, however, declined to
predict whether the count -- still underway -- would be entirely fair, or the
results accepted by the 2.7 million registered voters in this country of 10
million people.
</P>
<P>
	   ``First comes gestation and then birth,'' said Ide Oumarou, leader of the
French-speaking delegation. ``We can say the mother is healthy for now.''
</P>
<P>
	   Oumarou said observers noted relatively few problems in Sunday's ballot,
which he called smooth and fair.
</P>
<P>
	   While many African countries hold elections, very few are considered truly
free and fair. In West Africa, where votes often take place against the backdrop
of military coups and civil wars, Senegal is one of few countries to hold
regular ballots.
</P>
<P>
	   Results were trickling in Monday from Sunday's vote -- the country's most
contentious in decades -- which pitted President Abdou Diouf against seven
challengers.
</P>
<P>
	   Not enough ballots had been counted to suggest a clear trend, but top
contender Abdoulaye Wade was already warning that one of Africa's most stable
countries would explode in popular revolt if the president retains power.
</P>
<P>
	   Diouf ``is aware if he declares himself winner, there will be clashes in the
country, demonstrations and violence,'' Wade told reporters. ``He will have to
establish an emergency state and call in the army.''
</P>
<P>
	   Scattered attacks by separatist rebels marred voting in the southern
Casamance region, and there was at least one brawl reported Sunday between rival
political supporters in the capital, Dakar.
</P>
<P>
	   If Senegal plunges into violence so soon after the December military
takeover in nearby Ivory Coast -- another traditional bastion of African
stability -- Western diplomats worry it could trigger a flight of development
aid and trade from the continent.
</P>
<P>
	   Both Diouf and Wade claimed to be ahead Monday, though both also conceded
they might not win an outright majority.
</P>
<P>
	   If there is no clear winner, the top two contenders will face off in a
second round -- the first runoff election in Senegal, where the ruling Socialist
Party has held power since independence from France in 1960.
</P>
<P>
	   Khalifa Sall, a Cabinet minister and senior Socialist Party official,
conceded the president had a poor showing in Dakar, but said provisional results
put him in the lead in 19 of the country's 31 regions.
</P>
<P>
	   An official in Wade's camp, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said his
candidate was leading in the country's two biggest cities -- Dakar and nearby
Thies -- which account for 40 percent of voters.
</P>
<P>
	   There was no official confirmation of their claims. Official tallies were
released haphazardly to radio stations by village and city block -- sometimes a
few dozen voters at a time.
</P>
<P>
	   The provisional outcome is expected Wednesday, but will have to be confirmed
by the high court next week, Oumarou said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 1822 </TRAILER>
