<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Presidential Personality Poll Held  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican George W. Bush is the hubby of choice in the
presidential race. Rival John McCain is the top pick for dad. If people faced a
big exam and didn't know their stuff, they'd most want to look over Democrat Al
Gore's shoulder.
</P>
<P>
	   Those are among the findings in a survey by Republican pollster Frank Luntz
that looked beyond the horse race and asked questions such as: Whom would you
want as your companion if stuck at home for a week? (Answer: McCain, picked by
31 percent, followed by Bush at 24 percent).
</P>
<P>
	   The survey was done for YROCK.com, a Web site for young Republicans. Luntz
said it was done using traditional polling methods. As it turned out, only 27
percent of respondents were under 40.
</P>
<P>
	   The questions were anything but traditional. Offered a choice between
walking five miles to get home or hopping a motorcycle ride with one of the
candidates, a majority chose either riding with McCain or walking alone.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore's Democratic rival, Bill Bradley, was not tops in any category --
either for better or worse. But he was statistically tied with McCain as the one
least likely to be audited by the IRS, a risk felt to be greatest for Bush.
</P>
<P>
	   All the candidates are married. But, asked to choose, women picked Bush as
the candidate they'd most want to wed, 29 percent to 23.5 percent for Gore.
McCain was favored as the respondents' choice for father, 36 percent to 24
percent for Bush.
</P>
<P>
	   While Gore was chosen as the best one to crib from on a tough exam, he,
McCain and Bush were statistically tied as the candidate who would be the best
adviser, or ``lifeline,'' for a contestant on ``Who Wants to be a Millionaire?''
</P>
<P>
	   Luntz said he randomly sampled 800 likely voters by telephone on Wednesday
and Thursday, after McCain's wins in the Michigan and Arizona GOP primaries. The
poll had a margin of error of 3.5 percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
