<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Fall As Dow Industrials Soar  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Bonds fell Monday amid a big run-up in the Dow industrials,
as traders sought to lock in gains from last week's rally in bond prices.
</P>
<P>
	   The price of the 30-year Treasury bond fell 11/16 point, or $6.87 1/2 per
$1,000 in face value. The yield, which moves in the opposite direction of price,
rose to 6.19 percent from 6.14 percent late Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   Bonds had gained in recent days due to increased volatility in stocks as the
Dow Jones industrial average last week sank below 10,000 for the first time in
more than 10 months. Because of their security, liquidity and promise of a fixed
annual return, government bonds are a traditional haven for funds in times of
financial market unrest.
</P>
<P>
	   But with the Dow up 176.53 to 10,038.65 on Monday, traders were shifting
money out of bonds back to stocks.
</P>
<P>
	   Elsewhere in the bond market, prices of short-term Treasury securities fell
3/16 point to 9/32 point and intermediate maturities fell 7/16 point to 21/32
point, according to Bridge Telerate.
</P>
<P>
	   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 5.83 percent, with the discount up
0.06 percentage point from Friday to 5.66 percent. Six-month yields were 6.03
percent as the discount was up 0.06 percentage point to 5.77 percent. One-year
yields were 6.19 percent, with the discount rising 0.05 percentage point to 5.85
percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the discount is the
interest at which they are sold.
</P>
<P>
	   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, rose
to 5.75 from 5.68 3/4 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Bond Buyer index of municipal bonds was fell 1/32 to 92 21/32. The yield
to maturity of the index was 6.18 percent, up from 6.17 percent on Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
