<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supreme Court upholds 'three strikes' law for violent criminals  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Turning back a plea from a robber who claimed he is
being treated like a murderer, the state Supreme Court on Monday upheld a New
Jersey law mandating life sentences for those convicted three times of serious,
violent crimes.
<P>
	   The court, in a 5-0 ruling, said the "Three-Strikes" law, enacted in 1995,
is constitutional. The court also upheld the sentence of Gregory "Red" Oliver,
46, of Paterson, making him the first criminal to receive a life sentence under
the "Three-Strikes" law.
</P>
<P>
	   The ruling affects other sentences under the statute. The state attorney
general's office says at least five other three-time offenders have been
sentenced to life in prison, under the law. Another 10 who were convicted of
three lesser offenses were given extended sentences.
</P>
<P>
	   "New Jersey's Three-Strikes Law is consistent with contemporary standards of
decency," Justice Daniel J. O'Hern wrote in the decision, noting that at least
two dozen other jurisdictions have similar laws.
</P>
<P>
	   The decision also says lawmakers were careful to make sure the law was fair.
</P>
<P>
	   "New Jersey has more finely tuned its law by limiting the number and types
of violent offenses that fall within the purview ...," the decision reads.
"Thus, one cannot be sentenced to life in prison under New Jersey's
Three-Strikes Law for passing a bad check or stealing a loaf of bread."
</P>
<P>
	   The law requires that judges hand down life sentence after the third
conviction on serious, violent crimes considered first-degree offenses,
including murder, aggravated manslaughter, kidnapping, rape, carjacking and
first-degree robbery. Those convicted cannot be eligible for parole unless they
are at least 70 years old and have served at least 35 years. The law also
increases mandatory time for those convicted three times of second-degree
crimes.
</P>
<P>
	   Oliver had argued that the law treats robbers the same as murderers. He was
convicted of armed robbery three times dating back to 1979. The final conviction
was for a December 1995 robbery of Leon "Baldy" Johnson. Oliver was convicted of
robbing Johnson of drugs and money and fracturing his skull with a lead pipe in
a Paterson crack den.
</P>
<P>
	   Robert L. Sloan, a public defender representing Oliver, said a life sentence
for three robbery convictions is "disproportionate, especially in comparison to
a murder sentence."
</P>
<P>
	   "My main argument was that the life sentence, without parole, was so
disproportionate to the offense that it amounted to cruel and unusual
punishment," said Sloan. "You're putting this on par with other offenses that
are far more severe. I can only assume the court felt that setting sentences for
crimes was a legislative judgment."
</P>
<P>
	   The court also turned back Sloan's argument that one of Oliver's robbery
convictions should not have been counted under the "Three-Strikes" category.
</P>
<P>
	   Chief Justice Deborah Poritz and Justice Peter Verniero did not participate
in the ruling. Poritz was state attorney general while the "Three Strikes" law
was being drafted and for a year after it was signed into law. Verniero replaced
Poritz as attorney general while it was being implemented.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-28-00 1843 </TRAILER>
