<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge says hospital can offer medicine to subway pusher Goldstein  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - A Manhattan judge Monday gave hospital officials
permission to offer antipsychotic medicine to Andrew Goldstein, the former
mental patient who pushed a woman to her death beneath a subway train.
<P>
	   State Supreme Court Justice Carol Berkman, who let Goldstein stop taking his
medicine earlier this month, modified her order after he punched a psychiatric
social worker during interviews twice in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   The social worker, Hillel Bodek, was preparing a report for Goldstein's
second murder trial for pushing Kendra Webdale, 32, in front of an oncoming
subway train last year. Bodek was not injured by the punches.
</P>
<P>
	   On Feb. 10, Berkman granted a defense motion to stop Goldstein's medication.
His lawyers said they wanted him to be unmedicated when doctors examine him and
when the jury sees him for his second murder trial.
</P>
<P>
	   Goldstein stopped taking the medicine the next day. Berkman's latest order
differs from the earlier one in that doctors now are allowed to offer the
medication to Goldstein, but he can refuse to take it if he wants to.
</P>
<P>
	   Goldstein, 30, is a schizophrenic who has been in and out of mental
hospitals for the past 12 years. He says he was having a psychotic episode when
he pushed Webdale to her death under an N train in the subway station at 23rd
Street and Broadway on Jan. 3, 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite agreement that Goldstein is mentally ill, Berkman found him fit to
stand trial last fall for the murder of Webdale, from Fredonia, N.Y., a town
near Buffalo. In that trial the jury deadlocked 10-2 for conviction. Jury
selection for his retrial began last week.
</P>
<P>
	   Berkman said that since her first order to stop medicating Goldstein, he
"has requested medication on several occasions." But the medicine was withheld
until he could discuss the matter with his lawyer, Kevin Canfield.
</P>
<P>
	   Berkman said the defense request to stop medication appears to be a
litigation tactic. But she said she "recognizes that the defendant has a right
to have the jury see him in his unmedicated state if possible."
</P>
<P>
	   Canfield said he understood it would be four to six weeks before Goldstein
started deteriorating but it seems to have happened in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   Berkman said Bodek's report said Goldstein's mental condition has
deteriorated but that the condition is not such that he should be medicated by
force because he is a danger to himself or others, nor has it reached a point
that a new competency examination is warranted.
</P>
<P>
	   Canfield said he is concerned that the judge's modified order will result in
staff at Bellevue Hospital Center, where Goldstein is being kept, trying to
convince him to take the psychoactive medicine.
</P>
<P>
	   Canfield also complained to the judge that Bodek, whom Goldstein apparently
sees as a friend, was trying to convince the defendant to resume his
antipsychotic medication.
</P>
<P>
	   Goldstein wants to testify, said Canfield, but he will be unable to do so if
he is "doped up. The drugged Goldstein is there but that's not the real
Goldstein."
</P>
<P>
	   Canfield said he asked to have Goldstein's testimony taken now on videotape
in his undrugged state. The defendant then could take his medicine and avoid
problems related to his mental illness during the trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-28-00 1859 </TRAILER>
