<HEADLINE> Aetna Heeds Gore on Baby's Care  </HEADLINE>
   By PEGGY ANDERSEN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SEATTLE (AP) -- Aetna U.S. Healthcare has decided to continue skilled
nursing care for a baby whose case caught Vice President Al Gore's attention,
the company's chief medical officer said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Evaluation of Ian Malone's case was speeded up due to Gore's interest, Dr.
Arthur Leibowitz said in a telephone interview from Aetna offices in Blue Bell,
Pa.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I don't make it a habit of routinely conducting these high-level reviews
on Sunday,'' Leibowitz conceded.
</P>
<P>
	   But he said the same decision would have been made even if the case had not
become an issue in the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   During a visit Sunday, Gore -- who made the family a symbol of his call for
stronger appeal rights for those refused coverage by HMOs -- met privately with
Ian's parents, Christine and Dylan Malone, and promised to call Aetna on their
behalf.
</P>
<P>
	   Dylan, a newspaper graphic artist who was a volunteer for Gore's 1988
presidential campaign, did not immediately return a call for comment Monday from
The Associated Press. Gore campaign officials also did not return a telephone
call.
</P>
<P>
	   But Christine Malone told The Seattle Times that Aetna ``cracked under
pressure.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``We think he saved Ian's life,'' she said of Gore.
</P>
<P>
	   The baby, now about 5 months old, has brain damage caused by a difficult
birth, his parents say. He suffers seizures, can't swallow and is prone to
choking.
</P>
<P>
	   The 12-hour-a-day, in-home nursing care costs about $300 a day, the Malones
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Leibowitz said a reviewer recommended in January that the in-home care be
terminated next month and that the family care for Ian full time.
</P>
<P>
	   But after reviewing the case, Leibowitz said that he and Aetna's senior
medical director decided on Sunday to overrule the reviewer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
