<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Columbia Accepts $6B NiSource Bid  </HEADLINE>
    By PAUL TOLME AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SPRINGFIELD, Va. (AP) -- Columbia Energy Group accepted a $6 billion
takeover offer from NiSource Inc. on Monday in a deal that would create the
largest gas company east of the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
	   The combined company would have 4.1 million gas, electric, water and propane
customers from the Midwest to New England.
</P>
<P>
	   The merger, if approved by shareholders and regulators, comes four months
after Columbia rejected a slightly higher offer from NiSource, which attempted a
hostile takeover. The agreement is worth $70 a share in cash to Columbia
shareholders, plus a security worth $2.60 per share.
</P>
<P>
	   NiSource, based in Merrillville, Ind., will also assume $2.5 billion of
Columbia's long-term debt.
</P>
<P>
	   As an alternative, a percentage of Columbia shareholders can choose to
receive $74 a share in the new holding company's stock if NiSource's stock is
trading at more than $16.50 in the 30 days before the merger's closing, the
companies said.
</P>
<P>
	   Herndon-based Columbia, which has $7 billion in assets and is involved in
virtually all phases of the natural gas and propane businesses, rejected a $6.1
billion, $74 a share bid in October to look for a better deal.
</P>
<P>
	   But no better offers emerged from the dozen parties Columbia spoke with, and
utility stock prices fell in the succeeding months.
</P>
<P>
	   Shares of Columbia rose $2.31 1/4 to $59.37 1/2 in trading at 4:30 p.m. on
the New York Stock Exchange, off their 52-week high of $66.31 1/4. Shares of
NiSource fell $2.56 1/4 to $13, closing at a 52-week low.
</P>
<P>
	   Michael Heim, an analyst with A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons, Inc., declined to
second-guess Columbia's decision to reject the $74-a-share offer. But falling
utility stocks suddenly made the deal more attractive, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   "But you do have to say, if they had taken the $74 last fall, they could
have saved a lot of headaches," Heim said.
</P>
<P>
	   The deal will benefit NiSource because some Midwestern markets such as
Chicago have a surplus of natural gas, and Columbia's pipe system will allow
NiSource to move that supply into markets in the East where it is needed, Heim
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Columbia officials said NiSource does not intend any significant layoffs,
but that it was too early to say what the merger would mean to Columbia
employees.
</P>
<P>
	   The kind words of both companies' executives contrasted sharply with the
bitter takeover fight of last year, when NiSource officials questioned whether
Columbia's board was looking out for the best interest of its shareholders.
</P>
<P>
	   Columbia, in turn, said NiSource had a woeful environmental record and was
in too poor a financial shape to buy anyone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 1906 </TRAILER>
