<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain, Bush Trade Barbs  </HEADLINE>
   By MIKE GLOVER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   VIRGINIA BEACH, Va. (AP) -- Accused of dividing his party and helping the
Democrats, John McCain said Monday he was instead trying to expand the GOP to
become ``a party as big as the country we serve.''
</P>
<P>
	   Republican presidential rival George W. Bush strongly disagreed, saying of
McCain, ``He is a person who obviously wants to divide people into camps.''
</P>
<P>
	   The comments followed McCain's speech here -- in the headquarters city of
Pat Robertson's Christian Coalition -- accusing some in his party of pandering
to Christian right leaders ``on the outer reaches of American politics.''
</P>
<P>
	   The biting remarks were designed to appeal to moderates voting in Virginia,
Washington state and North Dakota on Tuesday, as well as in crucial contests
next week on ``Super Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush, campaigning in Washington, said repeatedly that his rival was trying
to divide the party.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Senator McCain is someone who likes to castigate, not someone who likes to
lead,'' Bush said. ``It's important to unite our party and lead it to victory.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush supporter Dick Armey, the Republican leader in the House, took a
similar slap at McCain: ``His was not the speech of a coalition-builder and a
unifier, nor was it worthy of a Republican presidential candidate.''
</P>
<P>
	   But McCain defended his loyalty.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I have been accused of consorting with the wrong sort of people,'' he said
in his speech, a reference to independents and Democrats from whom he has sought
support in open GOP primaries.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I have always acted in what I believe to be the best interests of my
country,'' he said. ``And I always believed that what is good for America is
good for the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``Some prefer to build walls and exclude newcomers from our support,'' he
said. ``Apparently appeals to patriotism can only be heard by card-carrying
Republicans, and only certain Republicans at that.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush also said the McCain camp was trying to divide the party along
religious lines by making telephone calls in primary states linking Bush to
anti-Catholic sentiments at Bob Jones University, a South Carolina school
accused of religious bigotry. The McCain campaign said calls like those made
before Michigan's primary were being made in Washington state, but not in
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Senator McCain is running a stealth campaign, saying one thing and doing
another. He's playing the religious card,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain said the Bush people were the religious dividers, telephoning voters
to ``distort by pro-life positions and smear the reputations of my supporters.''
</P>
<P>
	   The GOP race has focused on religious issues in recent days, with Bush
expressing his regrets on Sunday to Catholic leaders for his visit to Bob Jones
on Feb. 2.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain said Bush waited too long.
</P>
<P>
	   ``His words are fine,'' said McCain. ``To me they should have been said
three weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
	   There also were reverberations from McCain's decision not to take part in a
debate on Thursday. McCain blamed Bush, arguing that Bush was initially evasive
about accepting the debate invitation.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain said, given the delay, he scheduled events in New York that can't be
changed.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush said, ``I'm sorry that we're not going to have the debate in Los
Angeles. I would be glad to spend the entire time on education.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain, in his speech Monday, came to the heart of the religious
conservative movement to criticize its ``self-appointed leaders,'' but he
clearly was aiming at a broader audience.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I am a Reagan Republican who will defeat Al Gore,'' McCain said.
``Unfortunately George Bush is a Pat Robertson Republican who will lose to Al
Gore.''
</P>
<P>
	   After his speech at a high school in Virginia, where polls put Bush ahead,
McCain headed to Washington where the two are in a tight race.
</P>
<P>
	   In California, polls show Bush leading McCain by as much as 20 percentage
points among likely Republican voters who will choose that state's delegates
March 7, although it put them neck-and-neck in the open primary's popular vote,
which includes independents and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
	   After discussing education with teachers in Bellevue, Wash., Bush said he
was the candidate who wants to stick to issues.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Ronald Reagan didn't point fingers,'' Bush told reporters. ``He never
played to people's religious fears like Senator McCain has shamelessly done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
