<HEADLINE> Ex-La. Gov.'s Trial Continues  </HEADLINE>
   By NATALIE GOTT Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- A half-dozen contractors and laborers who worked at
residences of former Gov. Edwin Edwards or his family testified Monday that they
were paid in stacks of $100 bills.
</P>
<P>
	   Federal prosecutors allege Edwards, his son Stephen and five other men
manipulated and profited from the awarding of riverboat casino licenses before
and after Edwards left office in January 1996.
</P>
<P>
	   The prosecutors focused Monday on evidence that appears to suggest Edwards
always had plenty of cash; they hope to show he spent more money than he
legitimately made in the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
	   Since the trial began Jan. 10, one former casino owner and a former casino
consultant have testified they made large cash payments in return for Edwards'
help in getting licenses or fending off competition.
</P>
<P>
	   Landscaper Eduardo Jenkins said Monday he was paid $152,000 for installing a
swimming pool and other work at Edwin Edwards' home in 1995. About $80,000 was
paid in banded bundles of $100 bills, including a $50,000 down payment he picked
up at the Governor's Mansion, Jenkins testified.
</P>
<P>
	   Contractor Phillip Haddad testified he was paid with a $218,000 check and
$60,000 in cash when he sold a house to Edwards' son David in 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   Jarrod Clayborne, owner of an interior design store, said he received
$131,000 in cash from Edwards between 1995 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   Edwards' daughter Anna testified that Edwin Edwards came by his fondness for
cash honestly. She said the ex-governor's father raised his sons to be wary of
banks after seeing people lose their savings during the Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
	   Edwards' attorney, Dan Small, raised the possibility Edwards won the cash at
casinos.
</P>
<P>
	   Small asked carpenter David Kleinpeter, who had testified he was paid $800
in cash before Edwards tore up the invoice, whether $100 bills are a common form
of payment from casinos. ``I would imagine,'' Kleinpeter said, adding, ``I have
personal knowledge of $5 and $10, but not $100.''
</P>
<P>
	   Edwards, 72, who served four terms as Louisiana governor, could face 350
years in prison and $7.2 million in fines if convicted on the racketeering
charges. Stephen Edwards could get 305 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
