<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate panel approves dorm sprinkler bill  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - A Senate committee Monday took the first votes on a
bill to install fire suppression sprinklers in every dorm room in New Jersey by
2002.
<P>
	   The committee in unanimous votes set the program deadline at 24 months and
set the cost to the state at $50 million. Experts were on hand to dispute both
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
	   But Jane Kenny, commissioner of the Department of Community Affairs, said
the administration endorses both aspects of the proposal and has funded the
project in the current budget proposal.
</P>
<P>
	   The 5-0 votes came with the release of a study by the New Jersey Educational
Facilities Authority showing that 36,600 beds in college dorm rooms - about 71
percent of the total - have no sprinklers.
</P>
<P>
	   This includes eight colleges and universities where none of the dorm rooms
have sprinklers, including Rider, Kean and Seton Hall, site of the Jan. 19 fire
that claimed three lives and left six students critically injured, four of them
with extensive burns.
</P>
<P>
	   The set of bills passed by the Senate Law and Public Safety Committee would
update a 1991 law that required sprinklers in all new dorm rooms. The bill would
expand that law to require sprinklers in every room in every dorm in New Jersey
regardless of whether the building is old, new, public or private.
</P>
<P>
	   The $50 million fund would provide partial loans at discount interest rates.
Public colleges would be obligated to repay 50 percent of the debt, and the
state would cover the rest, turning half of the loan into what would in effect
be a cash grant.
</P>
<P>
	   For private institutions, the state would cover a third of the debt, leaving
the rest to the college to pay from its tuition or endowment sources. The
spending bill now heads to the budget committee, the other bills to the full
Senate.
</P>
<P>
	   The Department of Community Affairs calculated the installation cost
according to the number of square feet in dorm rooms and the number of beds in
them, deriving a figure of a $6 cost per square foot.
</P>
<P>
	   But Victor Cantillo, director of the Education Facilities Authority, said
colleges and universities estimated installation costs up to $14 a square foot,
reporting a total cost of $85 million to install sprinklers in all unprotected
dorm rooms.
</P>
<P>
	   Industry experts told lawmakers on Monday that a sudden rush by colleges to
find contractors for these projects could drive up their asking prices, and thus
could push the final cost to $100 million or more.
</P>
<P>
	   Rutgers University fire chief Joseph Zuccarello told the lawmakers the
university has a plan to fit sprinklers into some 100 dorms and student houses
over the next seven to 10 years, and that he was unsure how much that could be
accelerated.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. Louis Kosco, R-Bergen, said Rutgers could do the work more quickly by
simply dividing it into multiple projects and hiring more firms, but Zuccarello
said it was not that simple, in part because of design problems and in part
because of the availability of contractors.
</P>
<P>
	   Shawn Love, regional manager for Grinnell Fire Protection Systems, which he
called one of the nation's largest installation contractors, said many firms
that install sprinkler systems are small and are booked up because of the
booming construction market.
</P>
<P>
	   Grinnell has the contract to install sprinklers in every room of Seton Hall
University's dorms by September, and at its peak Love said the firm will have 20
workers at the job site.
</P>
<P>
	   Love said he doubts there are 20 firms in New Jersey that could bring that
kind of manpower to bear on such a project. Richard Hodavance, business manager
for a union representing sprinkler contractors, agreed.
</P>
<P>
	   As a result, Love said he does not see how two dozen universities can be
expected to get this work done in hundreds of buildings as quickly as the
senators wish. "I think 24 months is a little bit too aggressive," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
