<DOCNO> APW20000228.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki and Moynihan: Bush letter to Cardinal should put issue to  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   WASHINGTON (AP) - Gov. George Pataki said Monday that George W. Bush's
appearance at Bob Jones University was a mistake, but that the Texas governor
had made amends with his letter to Cardinal John O'Connor.
<P>
	   A top New York Democrat, Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, agreed with
Republican Pataki.
</P>
<P>
	   "Governor Bush did the right thing," Pataki, head of Bush's New York
campaign, said. "I think that should be the end of it."
</P>
<P>
	   Moynihan, who held a brief news conference with Pataki in the senator's
Capitol office, agreed that Bush's letter should put the matter to rest.
</P>
<P>
	   "I thought it was a handsome letter," Moynihan said.
</P>
<P>
	   Both Pataki and Moynihan are Catholic.
</P>
<P>
	   A spokesman for O'Connor said the cardinal was aware of Bush's letter but
had not commented on it yet.
</P>
<P>
	   New York backers of Sen. John McCain, including Staten Island Borough
President Guy Molinari, have said they plan to make Bush's visit to Bob Jones
University an issue with New York's Catholic voters who make up 46 percent of
the GOP enrollment in the state.
</P>
<P>
	   Bob Jones, a conservative Christian school in South Carolina, has come under
fire for banning interracial dating and spreading anti-Catholic views. Leaders
at the school have criticized the Pope and labeled the Catholic church a
"Satanic cult.
</P>
<P>
	   In his letter to O'Connor, made public Sunday, Bush wrote that he deeply
regretted "causing needless offense" by not clearly "disassociating myself from
anti-Catholic sentiments and racial prejudice."
</P>
<P>
	   The 80-year-old O'Connor wields considerable power as leader of New York's
1.4 million Catholics.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush made the visit to Bob Jones as he sought to appeal to South Carolina's
conservative Republican voters. Until Sunday's letter to the cardinal, Bush had
said he had nothing to apologize for.
</P>
<P>
	   A pair of statewide polls out Monday showed Bush and McCain running
neck-and-neck among New York's GOP voters. Despite the tight poll numbers,
Pataki on Monday predicted Bush would win.
</P>
<P>
	   "As long as it is on the issues and it is on the records and the visions of
the candidate, Governor Bush will win." Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
	   Calling Bush "an inclusive tolerant person," Pataki lambasted McCain,
charging that the senator had injected religion into the race. McCain has
acknowledged that his camp made phone calls to Michigan Catholics bringing up
Bush's visit to the university. McCain won last week's Michigan primary.
</P>
<P>
	   Like Pataki, New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and some other prominent
Republicans, who are still backing Bush, have said his visit to Bob Jones
University was a mistake. The visit prompted Rep. Peter King, a Long Island
Republican and Roman Catholic, to abandon Bush and become the co-chairman of
McCain's New York campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   Appearing Monday night on MSNBC's "Hardball with Chris Matthews" Pataki was
asked if he would appear at Bob Jones.
</P>
<P>
	   "If I did go I would make it very plain what my views are," Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think you have an obligation to do that. Gov. Bush has said you have an
obligation to do that. He admitted making a mistake."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-28-00 1942 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000228.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Committee hears new Public Records bill but withholds vote  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The momentum to rewrite New Jersey's 37-year-old
Public Records Law began to build Monday as lawmakers on the Assembly State
Government committee held a friendly hearing on the issue.
<P>
	   The news of the day came from the prime sponsor, Assemblyman George Geist,
R-Gloucester, in announcing that Assembly Speaker Jack Collins would cosponsor
his bill, A-1309, a key step toward winning approval, at least in the lower
house.
</P>
<P>
	   But the committee took no vote, and a few members raised concerns about some
parts of the bill while sounding supportive of the overall idea.
</P>
<P>
	   The Public Records Law mandates that any document required under statute
shall be maintained as a public record. Thus it does not apply to vast banks of
information at all levels of government, from consulting reports to land
appraisals to bill receipts, that may not be specifically mentioned in one state
law or another.
</P>
<P>
	   William "Skip" Hidlay, executive editor of the Courier-Post of Cherry Hill,
told lawmakers there are no penalties in the old law to pressure local officials
who blithely ignore legitimate requests for records.
</P>
<P>
	   Hidlay, Richard Bilotti, publisher of The Times of Trenton, the New Jersey
Press Association and the Society of Professional Journalists testified in favor
of the measure, which "declares it to be the public policy of this state that
government records shall be made readily accessible for inspection, copying or
examination by the citizens of this state ..."
</P>
<P>
	   Testifying for the New Jersey Press Association, attorney Thomas Cafferty
said the old law "is woefully inadequate ... in large part because of the law's
limited and confusing definition of what is a public record."
</P>
<P>
	   Hidlay said research by reporters for his newspaper and others in the
Gannett newspaper group showed a majority of public officials in hundreds of
town halls and school board offices dragged their feet or refused to comply with
requests for such basic items as budgets, payroll reports and contracts with
school executives.
</P>
<P>
	   News executives were joined Monday by ordinary citizens who told the
lawmakers of their frustration in seeking records in their hometowns.
</P>
<P>
	   Many of their stories alleged that local officials were violating the law as
it exists now without an amendment to toughen it. But Hidlay said these
violations occurred because the old law lacks penalties for those who choose to
ignore it.
</P>
<P>
	   Assemblywoman Rose Heck, R-Bergen, said she had questions about a provision
of the bill that would require records to be produced within seven business
days. She said many towns have minimal staffs and need to be protected from a
flood of paperwork inquiries.
</P>
<P>
	   The bill would apply to computer data records as well as paper files, and
would set uniform photocopying costs statewide. It would also create a $1,000
fine for public officials or employees who refuse to comply, and would limit
legal expenses for the public by allowing them to take complaints to municipal
court.
</P>
<P>
	   The League of Municipalities opposed the bill on many points, charging that
a fine would "discourage well-qualified professionals from public service and
create an atmosphere of official trepidation."
</P>
<P>
	   The League also said complying with large requests would increase municipal
costs, and that files with information about such things as dog permits, home
expansions and burglar alarm installations should remain secret.
</P>
<P>
	   A different version of the bill that died last year raised fears it would do
more harm than good by inviting state bureaucrats to label volumes of government
information as secret. Cafferty said those worrisome provisions have been
deleted from the current bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-28-00 1946 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000228.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air Force Hero Pleads Innocent  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HURLBURT FIELD, Fla. (AP) -- An Air Force helicopter pilot, honored as a hero
for leading a daring rescue off the coast of Iceland six years ago, pleaded
innocent at his court-martial Monday to charges he molested two girls.
</P>
<P>
	   Col. James A. Sills, 48, is charged with a series of indecent acts involving
the girls, including exposing himself and sodomy, between 1988 and 1994 while he
was stationed in Florida, Illinois and Iceland. The charges did not indicate
Sills' relationship to the girls.
</P>
<P>
	   He also is charged with having an unprofessional relationship with a
secretary, assaulting his estranged wife, and lying during a security clearance
interview when asked if he had ever engaged in ``deviant sexual behavior.''
</P>
<P>
	   Sills' lawyer has said the charges are unfounded and the result of bitter
divorce proceedings. Sills made no comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   His court-martial is expected to last a week. If convicted, he could face 63
years in prison.
</P>
<P>
	   Sills, a 25-year Air Force veteran, shared the 1994 MacKay Trophy for the
most meritorious Air Force flight of the year. He commanded two helicopters that
rescued six seamen from freezing waters off Iceland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 1947 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000228.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: McCain Trails Among GOP  </HEADLINE>
   By WILL LESTER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. John McCain has grown more popular with the public
as Gov. George W. Bush's popularity has slipped, but the Arizona senator faces
an uphill climb to get the Republican presidential nomination, polls suggest.
</P>
<P>
	   Two-thirds of Americans have a favorable view of McCain, according to a
CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll released Monday, while about a fifth have an
unfavorable view. Just under six in 10 said they have a favorable view of Bush,
the Texas governor, while a third view him unfavorably.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain's popularity has been rising in the CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll in the
last couple of months while Bush's popularity has been slipping.
</P>
<P>
	   But Bush still leads McCain in the voting preferences of Republicans and
those leaning Republican, 57 percent to 33 percent, nationally.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain's challenge to Bush has raised public interest in the campaign,
according to Thomas Patterson, acting director of the Shorenstein Center on the
Press, Politics and Public Policy. The Center is conducting an ongoing voter
survey that has found interest in the election surging, with more than half of
Americans paying at least some attention to the campaign. Before the New
Hampshire primary on Feb. 1, six of 10 said they were paying little or no
attention.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The excitement surrounding the McCain candidacy is a major reason for the
shift,'' Patterson said.
</P>
<P>
	   But McCain is fast approaching a day of reckoning for his candidacy, despite
the public enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
	   After contests Tuesday in Virginia, Washington state and North Dakota,
McCain will face a tougher challenge in California, New York and other states
where only GOP votes will determine who gets delegates to the national
convention. Bush generally leads McCain among Republicans.
</P>
<P>
	   The biggest prize, 162 delegates from California on March 7, could prove a
major obstacle for McCain, who remains 20 points behind Bush among California
Republicans in a new Field poll.
</P>
<P>
	   When McCain and Bush are measured on public perception of their leadership
qualities, two-thirds said McCain is ``sincere and authentic'' and a ``strong
and decisive leader.'' Just over half said Bush is ``sincere and authentic'' and
six in 10 said he was a ``strong and decisive leader.''
</P>
<P>
	   More people said McCain was not a typical politician, 48 percent, than
typical, 42 percent, while just a third said Bush is not a typical politician.
</P>
<P>
	   On personal traits, half said Bush is smug, people were split on whether he
says one thing and does another and more than half said he goes too far in
criticizing his opponents. More than half said McCain is not smug, that he does
not say one thing and do another and about half said he does not go too far in
criticizing opponents.
</P>
<P>
	   The CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll of 1,004 adults taken Friday through Sunday
has an error margin of plus or minus 3 percentage points, larger for subgroups
like Democrats and Republicans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 1949 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000228.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polls: McCain Trails Among GOP  </HEADLINE>
   By WILL LESTER Associated Press Writer
