<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Complaint Filed Vs. GM Arbitration  </HEADLINE>
    By JUSTIN HYDE AP Auto Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DETROIT (AP) -- Michigan's attorney general has threatened to sue General
Motors Corp., saying the automaker's employee discount program for new vehicles
illegally limits how far warranty claims can be pursued.
</P>
<P>
	   Attorney General Jennifer Granholm filed a complaint Monday saying GM's
program illegally forces warranty claims to be decided in binding, out-of-court
arbitration and limits the damages that can be awarded.
</P>
<P>
	   She said if claims are filed in court, the vehicle owner could face legal
action or, if they are a GM employee, even be fired. The automaker has 10 days
to respond.
</P>
<P>
	   But GM said its program was legal, and that no employee would be fired for
filing claims outside arbitration. It also said no warranty cases had been
brought under arbitration since March 1, 1999, when it became mandatory.
</P>
<P>
	   "We do not force our employees to choose this program," said GM attorney
Steve Cernak. "They get a substantial discount, and as part of that program,
they agree to resolve warranty claims in this way."
</P>
<P>
	   Discount programs are one of the most beloved perks for U.S. automakers'
employees and their immediate families, often knocking thousands of dollars off
the price of a new car or truck.
</P>
<P>
	   GM imposed mandatory arbitration on its program in 1999, Cernak said, to
resolve warranty claims more quickly and cheaply for both sides. He said no
cases have been brought because such claims are settled before they reach that
stage.
</P>
<P>
	   Cernak said DaimlerChrysler AG had a similar clause in its programs.
</P>
<P>
	   DaimlerChrysler spokesman Jay Cooney said the automaker asks that in
exchange for a discount on a car, employees agree to settle any disputes before
an independent, third-party arbiter. But Cooney said Chrysler does not assess a
penalty, such as termination, if an employee chooses to file a lawsuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
