<HEADLINE> Boeing, GE Developing New Airliners  </HEADLINE>
    By JIM KLAHN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SEATTLE (AP) -- Boeing will begin development of two new long-range versions
of its popular twin-engine 777 models, industry sources confirmed Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Officials from Boeing and General Electric, which builds the GE-90 engine
for existing 777-200 and -300 aircraft, were expected to announce development
and production of the 777-200X and -300X at a Tuesday news conference in New
York.
</P>
<P>
	   Officials at Seattle-based Boeing and Fairfield, Conn.-based GE declined
comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   A news release said Tuesday's announcement would deal with "major product
development." Scheduled to attend were Phil Condit, Boeing president and chief
executive officer; Jack Welch, GE president and CEO; Alan Mulally, president of
Boeing Commercial Airplanes; and Jim McNerney Jr., GE Aircraft Engines president
and CEO.
</P>
<P>
	   An industry source confirmed the executives planned to announce development
and production of expanded versions of the 777 models, equipped with a larger
version of the GE-90 engine.
</P>
<P>
	   It will cost Boeing at least $1 billion to develop the long-range models,
but it needs them to battle Airbus Industrie in the Asia-Pacific market, the
Seattle Post-Intelligencer reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The newer 777's would carry 300 to 375 passengers for distances up to 10,100
miles and be capable of flights lasting up to 18 hours.
</P>
<P>
	   Airbus has a long-range version of its four-engine A-340, and is developing
the larger A340-500 and A340-600 models.
</P>
<P>
	   Boeing's plans were first reported Monday in The Wall Street Journal, which
said the company has about 30 orders for the expanded 777's, valued at more than
$5.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   Quoting industry executives, the Journal said Japan Air Lines and the
aircraft-leasing unit of GE are among a half-dozen buyers for the new airplanes.
It said first deliveries were expected in September 2003.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
