<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study finds fewer than third of college students have sprinklers in  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Two of three students living on New Jersey college
campuses occupy dorm rooms without fire suppression sprinklers, according to a
state study done in the aftermath of last month's fatal fire at Seton Hall
University.
<P>
	   The New Jersey Educational Facilities Authority, the state's lead agency in
the construction of new college buildings, released the results Monday to a
Senate committee. The lawmakers approved legislation to mandate sprinklers in
every dorm room in New Jersey and to provide $50 million in state financing to
pay for their installation.
</P>
<P>
	   The study found only about 15,290 beds in student dormitories in New Jersey
were in rooms equipped with sprinklers. That's about 29 percent of the total of
51,913 beds in the dorms at colleges and universities, both public and private.
</P>
<P>
	   Of the medium-sized and larger universities, three - Rider, Kean and Seton
Hall, site of the Jan. 19 fire that claimed three lives - have no sprinkler
coverage in any individual dorm rooms, although some buildings do have
sprinklers in common areas.
</P>
<P>
	   Rutgers University has sprinklers covering 32 percent of its dorm room beds,
Princeton University 14 percent. Of other large schools, The College of New
Jersey had the highest percentage of its rooms equipped with sprinklers,
covering 82 percent of its beds.
</P>
<P>
	   Public colleges average 39 percent sprinkler coverage of dorm beds while at
private colleges only 13 percent of the beds had sprinkler coverage in those
rooms.
</P>
<P>
	   The Educational Facilities Authority survey was one that colleges and
universities were required to answer since the authority has provided financing
to virtually all of them.
</P>
<P>
	   It pinpointed student-occupied rooms specifically, rather than asking a more
general question as to whether sprinklers existed at any location within a
residential building. By counting beds, it got an accurate proportion of
students with and without fire suppression coverage because the sizes of dorm
buildings, rooms and suites vary extensively.
</P>
<P>
	   For instance, in the aftermath of the Seton Hall tragedy, officials, when
asked about sprinklers, said that four out of six dormitories had them. But
these sprinklers were installed only in common areas. The survey released Monday
said none of Seton Hall's six dormitories has sprinklers in students' rooms.
</P>
<P>
	   William Cane, executive director of the state Division of Fire Safety, said
a 1991 law required every new dormitory to include sprinklers in every room. As
with any such update to safety codes, however, the law did not apply to existing
buildings, only to new construction or buildings facing substantial renovation.
</P>
<P>
	   Cane said while hallway sprinklers might have knocked down the Seton Hall
fire, which occurred in a third-floor lounge area, dorms need sprinklers in
every room to be safe since the greatest fire risk exists within students'
rooms.
</P>
<P>
	   "Partial coverage does not provide safety," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Cane's supervisor, Department of Community Affairs Commissioner Jane Kenny,
testified, "All students deserve this protection, and all of their parents
deserve to sleep at night without worry."
</P>
<P>
	   Educational Facilities Authority director Victor Cantillo said colleges and
universities estimated that $85 million would be needed to install sprinklers,
and industry experts said a sudden rush to do the projects could drive the costs
higher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-28-00 2007 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
