<HEADLINE> New Charges Against 'Sammy the Bull'  </HEADLINE>
   By ALISA BLACKWOOD Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PHOENIX (AP) -- Former Mafia hitman Salvatore ``Sammy the Bull'' Gravano,
arrested last week for allegedly masterminding a statewide drug ring, was
charged Monday with racketeering, conspiracy and money laundering.
</P>
<P>
	   Attorney General Janet Napolitano filed a new complaint, charging Gravano,
three family members and 42 others with a total of 181 counts. They had all
initially been arrested on a single count of conspiracy to distribute a
dangerous drug.
</P>
<P>
	   Four of the charges are felonies carrying maximum 12 1/2-year prison
sentences -- if the suspect has no prior convictions.
</P>
<P>
	   Gravano, the confessed killer of 19 whose testimony helped put New York
crime boss John Gotti behind bars, was arrested Thursday. He was being held on a
$5 million cash bond.
</P>
<P>
	   Gravano is also charged with possession of dangerous drugs for sale, illegal
enterprise and participating in a criminal syndicate.
</P>
<P>
	   His attorney, Larry Hammond, was not commenting on the charges Monday,
according to an assistant.
</P>
<P>
	   Gravano's wife, daughter and son were also named in the new complaint.
</P>
<P>
	   The ecstasy drug ring, which allegedly started as a small-scale operation,
was selling 20,000 to 30,000 pills a week once Gravano put his weight behind it,
authorities said. The designer drug sells for $20 to $30 per pill.
</P>
<P>
	   Authorities say Gravano helped turn the drug ring into a $500,000-a-week
operation.
</P>
<P>
	   Ecstasy is a hybrid of the hallucinogen mescaline and the stimulant
amphetamine, chemically known as MDMA. The drug is popular at rave clubs and
underground parties with high energy music and lights displays, according to
drug enforcement officers.
</P>
<P>
	   Gravano escaped charges for the 19 murders he admitted to by testifying
against Gotti, the so-called ``Teflon Don.'' He was released in 1995, given a
new name through the witness protection program and underwent plastic surgery.
</P>
<P>
	   Gravano, also known as Jimmy Moran, dropped out of the program by early 1997
and has since been living what appeared to be a clean life in the Phoenix suburb
of Tempe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 2009 </TRAILER>
