<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Parents of Crash Victims Sue Van Co.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- The parents of two of the four college students killed when
their track team's van overturned on a highway sued Ford Motor Co. Monday,
claiming the van had defects.
</P>
<P>
	   In the federal lawsuit, the families of Samuel Sturns and Jerome Jackson
claim Ford's 15-passenger vans, like the one carrying the Prairie View A&AMP;M track
team Feb. 10, exhibit stability problems when heavily loaded.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is the fifth incident in two months where college kids have been
seriously injured or killed in vehicles that they and their families trusted
were safe,'' said Jay English, an attorney for the families.
</P>
<P>
	   Ford spokeswoman Susan Krusel said she had not seen the lawsuit and would
not comment. She said the model involved ``is as good or better than a secure
vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
	   A preliminary report found speeding may have been a factor in the crash. The
report concluded that the van was speeding, veered onto the shoulder to avoid
another vehicle preparing to turn, then rolled when the driver tried to bring it
back on the road.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
