<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elderly Man Charged in Wife's Death  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- An elderly man charged with killing his terminally ill wife
apparently committed suicide by taking sleeping pills and drinking alcohol,
authorities said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Thomas May, 76, of San Diego was found Saturday at a motel in Santa Maria,
230 miles north of his home.
</P>
<P>
	   The retired Navy commander was scheduled to stand trial this spring on
murder charges for giving his 69-year-old wife, Hazel, a fatal dose of
medication last year and placing her in their car with the engine running and
the garage door closed.
</P>
<P>
	   He sat with her in the car and passed out from the fumes, but awoke about
five hours later and called his daughter, who alerted authorities.
</P>
<P>
	   May pleaded innocent, saying his wife, who was in the advanced stages of Lou
Gehrig's disease, had asked for his help to commit suicide. Prosecutors said
they did not believe Mrs. May had wanted to die.
</P>
<P>
	   While awaiting trial, May was free on $100,000 bail.
</P>
</TEXT>
