<DOCNO> APW20000228.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Journal Register Co. to sell newspapers in Illinois, Missouri and  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Journal Register Co. said Monday it plans to sell
its newspapers in Illinois, Missouri and Ohio to boost its stock.
<P>
	   An industry analyst predicted the move will benefit the company by allowing
it to reduce its debt and putting it in position to acquire other newspapers
near its base in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
	   The Ohio properties to be sold are four daily newspapers with total daily
circulation of 125,825 and Sunday circulation of 140,532: The News-Herald (Lake
County), The Morning Journal (Lorain), The Times Reporter (Dover-New
Philadelphia) and The Independent (Massillon).
</P>
<P>
	   The Missouri and Illinois properties include the Suburban Newspapers of
greater St. Louis, the largest weekly newspaper group in the United States with
distribution of approximately 1.7 million, and The Telegraph (Alton, Ill.), a
seven-day newspaper with daily circulation of 28,048 and Sunday circulation of
30,110.
</P>
<P>
	   The company said the sale will demonstrate Journal Register's underlying
value, which the board of directors said is not reflected in its stock price.
</P>
<P>
	   "The sale of our Midwest properties will increase our financial flexibility
and enable us to further realize shareholder value," Robert Jelenic, Journal
Register chairman, president and chief executive officer, said in a prepared
statement.
</P>
<P>
	   Shares of the Trenton-based Journal Register Co. closed at $12.50, up 62 1/2
cents a share on the New York Stock Exchange - near its 52-week low of $11.37
1/2 and well below the 52-week high of $23.
</P>
<P>
	   The company will not sell any newspaper unless it gets "satisfactory
agreements with respect to price and terms," said Jean B. Clifton, Journal
Register executive vice president. Clifton said the company intends to use the
proceeds initially to reduce debt and for other corporate purposes, including
the company's share buyback program.
</P>
<P>
	   "Overall, it looks like a good move," said industry analyst Asa W. Graves of
First Union Securities Inc. Besides allowing Journal Register to shrink its debt
and buy back more stock, the sale will enhance the company's ability to acquire
newspapers near its remaining Northeastern properties, Graves said.
</P>
<P>
	   "One thing they're very good at is taking small, stand-alone organizations
and combining that in an existing cluster," Graves said.
</P>
<P>
	   Although The New York Times Co. and The Thomson Corp. also announced plans
earlier this month to sell newspapers, sellers can still command a premium
because buyers would be interested in adding to nearby existing operations to
gain economies of scale, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   If all of its newspapers in the three states are sold, Journal Register will
be left with 20 daily newspapers with total daily circulation of approximately
483,000 and Sunday circulation of approximately 449,000, and 143 non-daily
publications with total distribution of more than 2.2 million clustered in five
areas in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
	   Journal Register's properties include the New Haven Register, Connecticut's
second-largest daily and Sunday newspaper, and 194 non-daily publications. The
company had 1999 total revenues of $470 million.
</P>
<P>
	   It operates in seven regions: Connecticut; Philadelphia and its surrounding
areas; Ohio; the greater St. Louis area; central New England; and the
Capital-Saratoga and Mid-Hudson regions of New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Journal Register's announcement is the third large newspaper company
divestiture announcement this month.
</P>
<P>
	   On Friday, The New York Times Co. said it plans to sell seven of its smaller
newspapers and the nine telephone directories that are part of its Regional
Newspaper Group.
</P>
<P>
	   The Thomson Corp. of Canada announced Feb. 15 that it was selling its U.S.
newspapers, made up mainly of 49 local and regional dailies with circulations of
less than 50,000. Thomson is also putting up for sale five dailies in Canada and
more than 75 non-daily newspapers, most of which are based in the United States.
Its U.S. newspapers have been grouped into 21 regional clusters, the largest
being in Ohio, Wisconsin and Indiana.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-28-00 2047 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000228.0245 </DOCNO>
