<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Panel OKs Dorm Sprinkler Bill  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- A Senate committee Monday endorsed a bill requiring
every college dorm room in New Jersey to be equipped with fire suppression
sprinklers.
</P>
<P>
	   Seton Hall University, the site of a Jan. 19 fire that claimed three lives
and left six students critically injured, had no sprinklers in its dorm rooms.
</P>
<P>
	   The bill passed by the Law and Public Safety Committee calls for the state
to spend $50 million for the sprinklers, part of which would be a loan schools
must repay, and set the deadline at two years. The full Senate will vote on the
proposals later.
</P>
<P>
	   A 1991 law required room-based sprinklers in new school dormitories, but
they were not required in older buildings. A study released Monday by the New
Jersey Educational Facilities Authority showed 36,600 beds in college dorm
rooms, or 71 percent of the state's total, are in rooms that are not equipped
with sprinklers.
</P>
<P>
	   Seton Hall has hired a contractor to install sprinklers in its dorms by
September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 2049 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
