<HEADLINE> Monday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press Note: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Canadian Budget Unveiled
<TEXT>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- Canadian families expecting tax breaks got an average of $500
worth this year in Monday's budget, where Finance Minister Paul Martin surprised
everyone by ending income-eroding bracket creep.
</P>
<P>
	   Martin unexpectedly re-indexed income taxes to inflation to end the
insidious creep, in which personal incomes rising with inflation pushed
Canadians into higher tax brackets while reducing the value of their tax
credits.
</P>
<P>
	   The budget also came up with about $4.5 billion more for Canada's rusting
military, health, research and roads, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
	   Provinces will get about $1 billion more for health, education and social
programs while more than $3 billion is earmarked for other spending initiatives.
</P>
<P>
	   As social transfer payments to the provinces for health and education
continue to rise, they'll reach a cash total this year of $15.5 billion, still
less than before the war on the deficit began in the mid-'90s.
</P>
<P>
	   Martin is also cutting corporate taxes by seven percentage points over five
years.
</P>
<P>
	   Defense Department Gets $1.7 Billion Over Three Years
</P>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- The Defense Department got a long-awaited infusion of money
in Monday's budget but it came like a stealth bomber and barely registered as a
blip in Finance Minister Paul Martin's speech.
</P>
<P>
	   Defense will get about $1.7 billion more over the next three years, a
welcome change from almost a decade of cuts that chopped 25 per cent from the
budget and reduced the ranks to 60,000 uniforms from more than 80,000.
</P>
<P>
	   The military budget, which was close to $12 billion in 1993, is just under
$10 billion this year.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite the new money, the military rated only a single line in Martin's
24-page speech:
</P>
<P>
	   ---
Brashear Still Suffers From Headaches After Clubbing
</P>
<P>
	   VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- Donald Brashear, sidelined indefinitely
after being clubbed from behind by Boston defenseman Marty McSorley, said Monday
he was still puzzled by the attack.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I never thought I'd see a player acting like that toward another player,''
the Vancouver Canucks tough guy told a packed news conference at GM Place.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I wonder what was going through his mind to do a thing like that, but it
happened,'' added Brashear, speaking at length for the first time since he was
hit in the head a week ago in a game against the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
	   Brashear also defended his own on-ice behavior, saying fighting and taunting
is part of the game.
</P>
<P>
	   He said he still suffers from daily headaches and must remain completely
inactive for at least two more weeks before his playing status is reevaluated.
</P>
<P>
	   The rugged six-foot-two 225-pound winger also said he remembered nothing
about the incident.
</P>
<P>
	   ---
Ontario Man May Be Deported After Wartime Past Is Disclosed
</P>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- An Ontario man may be forced to leave Canada, after a court
found Monday he hid his wartime past when he entered the country from Germany 46
years ago.
</P>
<P>
	   Helmut Oberlander obtained his Canadian citizenship fraudulently by
concealing or misrepresenting his wartime service in a German unit responsible
for the murders of more than 91,000 Jews during the Second World War, ruled
Federal Court Judge Andrew MacKay.
</P>
<P>
	   The finding comes almost five years after Oberlander, now 76, was first told
his citizenship would be revoked. It is not subject to appeal.
</P>
<P>
	   Canada's immigration minister can now recommend to the cabinet that
Oberlander be stripped of his citizenship as a first step toward deportation.
</P>
<P>
	   Oberlander, who worked for years in construction in the southwestern Ontario
city of Kitchener, has been suspected of participating in the execution of Jews.
</P>
<P>
	   But the court did not make any rulings on the truth of those allegations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
