<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Urban Intelligence Criticized  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID HO Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. military lacks the intelligence information
needed to fight and function effectively in many cities around the world,
especially in developing countries most likely to harbor future conflicts,
congressional investigators warned Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Recent conflicts in Kosovo, Bosnia and Somalia have shown that poor
intelligence about local conditions can lead to greater risks for U.S. forces
and civilians, said the General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
	   ``U.S. forces currently do not have adequate information ... due to the
lower priority the intelligence community has afforded urban warfare in its
collection efforts,'' the investigators said.
</P>
<P>
	   Fighting in cities presents very different challenges to military forces
than campaigns in open areas, like the vast expanses of desert in the Persian
Gulf War. Military planners expect that future adversaries might attempt to draw
U.S. forces into dense urban areas to counter the United States' traditional
advantages of superior firepower and mobility.
</P>
<P>
	   Planners need to know in advance which streets and bridges can handle the
weight of the Army's main tanks and fighting vehicles, which tall buildings can
block communications and the location of a city's utilities, transportation and
civilians.
</P>
<P>
	   Brian E. Sheridan, assistant secretary of defense for special operations,
agreed with the investigators' findings.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There is consensus across the department that significant information and
intelligence shortfalls exist for foreign urban operations,'' he said in a
letter dated Feb. 7. He added that they don't have accurate databases and maps
for a majority of foreign cities.
</P>
<P>
	   Members of the House and Senate subcommittees on military readiness said
they had not yet read the report and couldn't comment.
</P>
<P>
	   The Defense Department is completing a study that will identify the
information holes and the specific challenges of urban warfare, Sheridan said.
</P>
<P>
	   The investigators said the military should also be working with the
intelligence community to reexamine their intelligence gathering priorities.
</P>
<P>
	   The Defense Intelligence Agency's databases are still focused on the
potential battlegrounds of the Cold War and treat developing countries as a low
priority, which leads to problems providing current information.
</P>
<P>
	   The agency was directed in 1994 to create a worldwide urban information
system, but no full-time analysts are working on the project, only four or five
contractors. With the current staff it will take another three or four years
before the system is available for use by U.S. forces, the investigators said.
</P>
<P>
	   The investigators also found that while the individual military services
have been updating their own plans and training for a shift to more urban
warfare, the different services, like the Army and Marine Corps, need to conduct
joint exercises. Training facilities are also often unrealistic because they
don't include medium-sized and tall buildings.
</P>
<P>
	   Conflicts over the last decade have shown that poor information can hinder
the military. The investigators cited these examples:
</P>
<P>
	   -- Last year in Kosovo, U.S. forces reported that before their arrival they
had outdated terrain information and lacked basic materials such as street maps
of the major cities in their sector.
</P>
<P>
	   -- In Bosnia, it took nearly 18 months to provide U.S. forces with basic
information on city layouts and the location of key facilities.
</P>
<P>
	   -- When U.S. troops went to Somalia in the early 1990s, they had only
outdated information on the country's culture, people, clan structure and the
possible threats these presented.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 2106 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
