<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press Irving Baker
<TEXT>
<P>
	   OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- Irving Baker, a longtime editor for the Omaha
World-Herald, died Sunday. He was 91.
</P>
<P>
	   Baker worked for the Omaha Bee-News and then The World-Herald. He spent his
final years at the World-Herald working on the editorial pages. He wrote a
column called ``Good Morning. ''
</P>
<P>
	   He retired in 1973.
Harold M. Mulvey
</P>
<P>
	   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) -- Harold M. Mulvey, the former Superior Court Judge
who presided over the highly-charged Black Panther trial in the early 1970s,
died on Sunday. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
	   The six-month murder trial of national Black Panther leader Bobby G. Seale
and local leader Ericka Huggins ended in a hung jury.
</P>
<P>
	   Seale, chairman of the militant group, was accused of ordering the killing
of a local Panther member, Alex Rackley, a suspected police informer.
</P>
<P>
	   Mulvey dismissed the charges against Seale and Huggins on May 24, 1971.
John Govy Prude
</P>
<P>
	   FORT DAVIS, Texas (AP) -- John Govy Prude, whose family runs a century-old
ranch that attracts thousands of tourists to the remote Davis Mountains each
year, died Thursday. He was 95.
</P>
<P>
	   At the Prude Ranch, the man known as ``Big Spurs'' embraced both the tourism
and cattle businesses, managing a small herd of about 100 while always remaining
ready to play the gracious host.
</P>
<P>
	   Prude's parents, Andrew and Ora, established the ranch in the late 1890s.
</P>
<P>
	   After the stock market crash of 1929, the family had to sell cattle and
land, diminishing the ranch to its present-day 5,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
	   The ranch was declared a Texas historical site in 1997.
Eleanor Roberts
</P>
<P>
	   BELMONT, Mass. (AP) -- Veteran Boston newspaper reporter Eleanor Roberts
died Saturday. She was 85.
</P>
<P>
	   Roberts worked for three different Boston newspapers over four decades. She
wrote about everyone from murderers to TV stars, covering hard news as well as
fashion, food and other lifestyle areas.
</P>
<P>
	   When the Boston Post folded in 1956, she joined the Boston Traveler and in
1972, she was hired by the Boston Herald American and covered news, religion and
fashion.
</P>
<P>
	   She received two awards from the New England Associated Press for spot news
and features in 1973 and retired in 1979.
</P>
<P>
	   She leaves three daughters, a son, a granddaughter and three
great-grandchildren.
Natasha Dakserhof Sazevich
</P>
<P>
	   INVERNESS, Calif. (AP) -- Natasha Dakserhof Sazevich, a descendant of
Russian nobility and longtime director of the art department at Marin Country
Day School, died of lung cancer. She was 69.
</P>
<P>
	   Sazevich's mother was Princess Marina Galitzine and her great-grandfather
was a governor-general of Moscow. Her grandfather, Prince Alexander Galitzine,
crossed Siberia with his family during the Russian Revolution. He later settled
in Seattle before moving to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
	   Sazevich led the art department at Marin Country Day School in Corte Madera
from 1982 until 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
