<HEADLINE> Senegal Leader, Rival Said in Runoff  </HEADLINE>
   By GLENN McKENZIE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DAKAR, Senegal (AP) -- Senegal's incumbent president and his main rival
appeared headed for a runoff election Monday, with partial returns showing both
candidates had failed to win an outright majority in the country's presidential
election, a senior electoral official said.
</P>
<P>
	   A provisional ballot count showed President Abdou Diouf and veteran
opposition leader Abdoulaye Wade on top among the eight candidates who competed
in the election on Sunday, said the Interior Ministry official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity. He said each failed to gain more than 50 percent of the
vote.
</P>
<P>
	   The official declined to give voting figures and said a final tally would
not be available until later in the week. Those returns must then be approved by
the country's high court next week.
</P>
<P>
	   A runoff between Wade and Diouf would be the first ever in Senegal, where
the ruling Socialist Party has held power since independence from France in
1960.
</P>
<P>
	   Senegal over the years has allowed regular elections, which the Socialist
Party easily has won. It is rare for ruling parties in Africa -- which control
campaign funds and often electoral authorities -- to lose power through the
polls.
</P>
<P>
	   Aides to Diouf released figures late Monday showing the president garnered
43 percent of some 1.6 million votes counted. Wade had 30 percent, and other
candidates were trailing with lower percentages.
</P>
<P>
	   It was not immediately possible to confirm the figures, and opposition
candidates were not available for comment. Nearly 2.7 million voters were
registered for the vote, but it was unclear how many actually cast ballots.
</P>
<P>
	   An official in Wade's camp, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said his
candidate was leading in the country's two biggest cities -- Dakar and nearby
Thies -- which account for 40 percent of voters.
</P>
<P>
	   Wade, who has accused Diouf of rigging earlier votes, warned Monday morning
that Senegal would explode in popular revolt if the president retains power.
</P>
<P>
	   Diouf ``is aware if he declares himself winner, there will be clashes in the
country, demonstrations and violence,'' Wade told reporters.
</P>
<P>
	   If Senegal plunges into violence so soon after the December military
takeover in nearby Ivory Coast -- another traditional bastion of African
stability -- Western diplomats worry it could trigger a flight of development
assistance and trade from the continent.
</P>
<P>
	   International observers gave a thumbs-up to Senegal's presidential
elections, saying scattered violence and logistical problems failed to tarnish
voting in one of Africa's oldest democracies.
</P>
<P>
	   The head of observers from French-speaking nations, however, declined to
predict whether the count would be entirely fair, or the results accepted by
voters in this country of 10 million people.
</P>
<P>
	   Ide Oumarou, leader of the French-speaking delegation, said observers noted
relatively few problems during Sunday's voting, which he called smooth and fair.
</P>
<P>
	   While many African countries hold elections, very few of those votes are
considered truly free and fair. In West Africa, where votes often take place
against the backdrop of military coups and civil wars, Senegal is one of few
countries to hold regular ballots.
</P>
<P>
	   Scattered attacks by separatist rebels marred voting in the southern
Casamance region, and there was at least one brawl reported Sunday between rival
political supporters in the capital, Dakar.
</P>
<P>
	   Both Diouf and Wade claimed to be ahead earlier Monday, though both also
conceded they might not win an outright majority.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 2107 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000228.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hog Farmers To Vote on Pork Ads  </HEADLINE>
    By PHILIP BRASHER AP Farm Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hog farmers will get a chance to vote on whether to keep
paying the fees that fund the "other white meat" advertising campaign for pork,
the government announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman said he had the legal authority to call
the referendum even though his department didn't validate sufficient signatures
on petitions that were submitted by farmers who oppose paying the fees, or
"checkoffs."
</P>
<P>
	   There has not been a referendum on the pork program since it was created 14
years ago. Opponents of the $48 million program, which pays for research as well
as advertising, say it has done little to stimulate pork consumption and mostly
benefits meat processors and large, corporate farm operations.
</P>
<P>
	   "As a matter of basic fairness, I believe that producers deserve the
opportunity to vote on this checkoff program," Glickman said in a speech to the
National Farmers Union in Salt Lake City, Utah. "It is, after all, a mandatory
assessment, akin to a tax, that all producers must pay even if they disagree
with it."
</P>
<P>
	   Glickman was immediately criticized by the National Pork Producers Council,
which receives funding from the fee and questions his authority to order a
referendum on his own.
</P>
<P>
	   The referendum hurts "bonafide pork producers who created a program that
truly works to benefit pork producers of all types and sizes," said John McNutt,
president of the council and an Iowa farmer.
</P>
<P>
	   Under government rules, Glickman would have been required to call a
referendum if the petitions submitted to the Agriculture Department last year
contained at least 14,986 signatures, or 15 percent of all producers. USDA
officials used a sampling process to validate the petitions but couldn't verify
a sufficient number of names.
</P>
<P>
	   The fee is pay 45 cents for every $100 of a pig's value when it is sold. The
money goes to the quasigovernmental National Pork Board, which contracts
promotional services through the National Pork Producers Council.
</P>
<P>
	   Opponents of the program say they get little for the fees. Pork consumption
has been relatively flat despite the advertising, rising from 51.5 pounds per
person in 1985 to 53.4 pounds last year.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is all about the democratic process ... and the right of hog farmers
and other producers to vote on whether the checkoff programs are working for
them," said Rhonda Perry, a Missouri hog producer who opposes the pork program.
</P>
<P>
	   USDA also is being petitioned to a hold a referendum on the beef promotion
program. The disputes over the two promotion programs reflect a growing division
in U.S. agriculture between the interests of large and small-scale producers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 2108 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000228.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Stocks Rise in Early Trading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks bounced back moderately early Tuesday in
reaction to an overnight recovery on Wall Street. The U.S. dollar was higher
against the yen.
</P>
<P>
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 40.12 points, or 0.20
percent, to 19,760.22 points in the first 30 minutes of trading. On Monday, the
average closed down 97.79 points, or 0.49 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar bought 109.64 yen, up 0.44 yen from late in Tokyo and also above
its late New York level of 109.37 yen overnight.
</P>
<P>
	   On the stock market, prices started higher Tuesday as investors were cheered
by gains in New York, where the Dow Jones industrial average rose 176.53, or
1.79 percent, to 10,038.65 at Monday's close.
</P>
<P>
	   "Stocks are firmer, but trading volumes are very light so far," said
Hiriochi Nishi, an equities manager at Nikko Securities.
</P>
<P>
	   Traders say that stocks are likely to remain in a narrow range Tuesday, as
players are poised to adjust positions and reshuffle portfolios before closing
their books for February.
</P>
<P>
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the first
section was down 8.17 points, or 0.47 percent, to 1,720.27 points. The TOPIX
closed up 3.94 points, or 0.23 percent, the day before.
</P>
<P>
	   In currency dealings, the dollar was steady as the euro moved higher against
the dollar.
</P>
<P>
	   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 106.37 yen in early Tuesday, up
from 105.37 yen late Monday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
	   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell to 1.8050
percent from Monday's finish of 1.8200 percent. Its price rose 0.12 point to
99.95. (km-dj)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
