<HEADLINE> 20 Argentines To Be Tried in Attack  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- Twenty Argentines will be tried as
accomplices in the 1994 bombing attack that leveled a Buenos Aires Jewish
community center and killed 86 people, authorities said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Federal Judge Juan Galeano said in his ruling that that the search for the
planners of the bombing would continue.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The investigation has not ended,'' Galeano said. ``On the contrary, we are
sending to trial those people believed to be associated with policemen whose
activity could have had an effect'' on the bombing, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors are calling for the death sentence for six of the men named
Monday: a car thief and five provincial police officers known to deal in stolen
automobiles.
</P>
<P>
	   Those men are suspected of preparing the Renault van investigators say was
later used in the attack outside the Asssociation of Argentine Jewish Mutual
Societies in downtown Buenos Aires.
</P>
<P>
	   The other 14 -- including 10 police officers -- are charged with lesser
crimes in connection with the bombing.
</P>
<P>
	   No court date has been announced.
</P>
<P>
	   Galeano, the lead investigator in the case, has blamed Iran for the bombing,
a charge Tehran has vehemently denied.
</P>
<P>
	   The attack on Jul. 18, 1994 flattened the country's largest Jewish community
center, killing 86 people and injuring hundreds of others.
</P>
<P>
	   It came two years after the bombing of the Isreali embassy, which killed 29
people in the Argentine capital. No arrests have been made that bombing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
