<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teen Accused in Shooting Apologizes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- A suburban Atlanta teen-ager accused of shooting six
classmates in the halls of his high school last spring apologized in a letter
released Monday and said he wished he ``could take every minute of it back.''
</P>
<P>
	   Portions of the letter from T.J. Solomon, 16, were read during a televised
interview with his parents. It was the first time they had spoken publicly about
their son's arrest and the shootings that wounded six students at Heritage High
School.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Sometimes it feels lonely to be in here,'' the teen-ager wrote from the
jail where he is awaiting trial as an adult. ``If I could undo what I did to get
in here, I would. I am truly sorry for what I did last year and wish that I
could take every minute of it back.''
</P>
<P>
	   Solomon summarized his emotions in the days before the May 20 attack.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It is hard to describe how dark and isolated I felt leading to the date of
my mistake,'' Solomon wrote. ``It almost made everything in my life not worth
waiting for.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I always thought to myself that if I could put everything I was feeling
away, somewhere inside of me, that I would be fine until my emotions were too
much for me to bear.''
</P>
<P>
	   Solomon's mother, Mae Dean Daniele, told Atlanta's WSB-TV it's ``hard to
think that your child can reach this type of a point in his life when it is so
meaningless to him. ... I had no idea on May 20 that my child was that ill.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I watched him walk to the school bus, and I thought we had the perfect
life.''
</P>
<P>
	   She said she was at work when she heard about the shootings and went home,
where the district attorney called her.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He said he had T.J. and explained what T.J. had done. I couldn't believe
my son could do this. The whole life I knew didn't exist,'' Daniele said.
</P>
<P>
	   Solomon's attorneys have argued that the teen-ager belongs in a mental
institution, but the Georgia Court of Appeals ruled that he was not out of touch
with reality at the time of the shootings.
</P>
<P>
	   During an August hearing to decide whether Solomon should be tried as an
adult, an agent with the Georgia Bureau of Investigation described a note found
under Solomon's bed that made references to the Columbine High School massacre
and in which Solomon apparently wrote that he had been planning the attack for
years.
</P>
<P>
	   A state-appointed psychologist also testified at the hearing that Solomon
told him six days after the shooting that he didn't want to kill anyone and
``just wanted to cause a big panic.''
</P>
<P>
	   If convicted on all counts, Solomon could be sentenced to more than 350
years in prison. A trial date has not been set.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 2120 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000228.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Ridicules GOP 'Identity Crisis'  </HEADLINE>
   By SANDRA SOBIERAJ Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DENVER (AP) -- While Bill Bradley steeled himself against potential
disappointment in the Northwest, Democratic rival Al Gore campaigned Monday as
if he were already his party's nominee, ridiculing the Republicans' ``huge
identity crisis.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley, who has invested nearly a week in Washington state in preparation
for Tuesday's nonbinding primary there, said in Seattle, ``I knew it would be
difficult and it has been.''
</P>
<P>
	   He promised to plow ahead to the March 7 ``Super Tuesday'' primaries no
matter what.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore, popping into Colorado for 16 hours, accused all the other candidates
of ignoring the state. Meanwhile, he ignored Bradley as he campaigned in
sunshine and spring-like breezes under the open-air, arched glass pavilion of
the Denver Performing Arts Center.
</P>
<P>
	   The Republicans ``don't know who they are,'' the vice president said,
offering his take on the nomination battle between John McCain and George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore said he shares McCain's views on ``some things ... campaign finance
reform and taking on the tobacco companies and taking on special interests.''
But both Republican contenders would try to destroy abortion rights, he
contended.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The Republicans want to pander to the right-wing extremists and get the
government to come in and order a woman to do what the right wing says is the
right thing,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
	   Even as he campaigned in Denver and Pueblo -- and late Monday in Phoenix --
Gore kept an eye over his shoulder on Washington state. From his Denver hotel
suite, he phoned in five drive-time interviews to radio stations in Seattle. His
campaign manager, Donna Brazile, was staying in the state until the voting gets
under way.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley has hoped for an invigorating -- if symbolic -- win in Washington on
Tuesday. He said on Monday, during a visit to a women's health center, ``If we
win overwhelmingly, it would send a message. But I didn't come here expecting we
would do that. I knew it would be difficult and it has been.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley started the day before dawn in Seattle, searching for votes among
commuters at the ferry terminal. He left state on a high note after a rainy but
spirited rally at the University of Washington that drew about 1,000 supporters.
</P>
<P>
	   He said that whatever happens on Tuesday is ``not determinate of March 7.''
</P>
<P>
	   From Washington, Bradley headed to California for a day-and-a-half courtesy
call. Gore leads by a whopping 5-to-1 margin in the latest polls gauging
California's March 7 jackpot primary.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, Bradley sounded hopeful about California.
</P>
<P>
	   ``People make up their mind in the last week. We're going to continue to
reach out as the reform candidate. Be the only reform candidate on the
Democratic side in a year where reform is a key thing. I think it's an important
consideration,'' he told KPIX-TV after arriving in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
	   After California, Bradley planned to turn his focus for the final days
before ``Super Tuesday'' to New York and New England, where he has shown
stronger appeal.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore made only a brief visit to Colorado, which has 51 Democratic delegates
up for grabs in its March 10 primary. Standing on the back of a pickup truck at
a rally in Pueblo, Colo., where a gray-haired woman held a sign saying ``Gore is
a babe,'' the vice president reminisced about visiting the city with his young
wife Tipper just after he returned from Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We put a tent in the back of our Chevrolet and camped in the Great Sand
Dunes,'' which Gore said should be made a national park.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite the brevity of his appearance, he told Denver's KMGH-TV, ``This is a
place I've spent a lot of time in. I don't know why the other candidates have
been ignoring Colorado.''
</P>
<P>
	   He confided to Seattle's KNDD that he sometimes plays the harmonica, but
declined to prove it on the air. ``It might depress the voter turnout
tomorrow,'' he quipped.
</P>
<P>
	   In Phoenix, Gore headlined a fund-raiser for the Democratic Party's national
and congressional 2000 campaigns. ``I want you to vote for good Democrats for
Congress -- House and Senate -- all the way up and down the line,'' Gore said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
