<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Envoy Pushes for Milosevic Ouster  </HEADLINE>
   By EDITH M. LEDERER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- U.N. envoy Carl Bildt warned Monday that there is
virtually no prospect for peace in the Balkans until Slobodan Milosevic is no
longer Yugoslavia's leader.
</P>
<P>
	   But Bildt told the Security Council that the international community cannot
sit around and wait for a new regime.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If we do that, we might well be faced with further conflicts,'' he said.
``We must actively seek change. We must meet the provocations that are there and
actively try to prevent existing tension from boiling over into open conflict.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bildt, a former Swedish prime minister who was the international community's
top representative in Bosnia and now serves as Secretary-General Kofi Annan's
special envoy for the Balkans, cited a number of flashpoints.
</P>
<P>
	   As long as there is no change of regime in Yugoslavia, Serbia and Montenegro
``are set on a somewhat slow but very steady collision course,'' he warned.
</P>
<P>
	   ``President Milosevic has grossly misused the federal institutions and
grossly violated the rights of Montenegro within that federation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bildt called for accelerated international help for the people of Montenegro
who suffer from ``double sanctions'' -- against Yugoslavia as a whole and de
facto sanctions from Serbia forcing them to rely on expensive food imports.
</P>
<P>
	   Southern Serbia, which is home to between 70,000 and 80,000 ethnic
Albanians, and eastern Kosovo, especially Mitrovica, are also flashpoints, he
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Belgrade must be told firmly to keep its special police out of Kosovo, he
said. At the same time, armed Kosovo Albanian groups ``that are obviously
operating across the border'' in Serbia must be told to stop, Bildt said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They are both playing with fire and that message should be loud and
clear,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The larger issue in the Balkans is the conflict between extremists who want
to destroy the fabric of societies and those who want integrated, multiethnic
communities, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Because those extremists still have the upper hand, it is imperative for the
international community to resume the search for peace starting in Kosovo, he
said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Time might not yet be ripe for more concrete moves, but time is certainly
ripe for discussion on the core issues,'' Bildt said.
</P>
<P>
	   He stressed that the international community can't make peace without
Yugoslavia nor can it talk about regional issues without taking in Serbia. But
Milosevic and other key political and military leaders indicted by the
international war crimes tribunal ``are de facto excommunicated from any sort of
dialogue or diplomatic contact,'' Bildt said.
</P>
<P>
	   Nonetheless, he reiterated that the search for peace must go on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
