<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kurdish Mayors Freed Until Trial  </HEADLINE>
   By SELCAN HACAOGLU Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DIYARBAKIR, Turkey (AP) -- Thousands of people celebrated Monday -- some
tossing red carnations and others freeing white doves -- after three mayors were
released from prison pending trial on charges of aiding Kurdish rebels.
</P>
<P>
	   The show of support in Turkey's largest Kurdish-majority city ended when
police wearing steel helmets charged into one crowd, beating people with wooden
clubs. The demonstrators fled into side streets, where they were chased by
policemen on motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
	   The mayors -- Feridun Celik of Diyarbakir, Selim Ozalp of Siirt and
Feyzullah Karaaslan of Bingol -- were arrested last week after meeting with
European officials to discuss cultural rights for Kurds. They have been charged
with aiding Abdullah Ocalan's outlawed Kurdistan Workers Party, known as the
PKK.
</P>
<P>
	   The Interior Ministry ruled late Monday night that the mayors could return
to their posts. The mayors were expected to return to their posts within the
next few days.
</P>
<P>
	   The three, however, were barred from leaving the country until their trial,
a second court announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   At a press conference in Diyarbakir, the largest city in the overwhelmingly
Kurdish southeast, Celik sounded defiant.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We want to work for our people and for Turkey. No one can stop us,'' he
said. ``If throwing us in prison will bring peace then we will serve 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
	   Ozalp echoed Celik's tone. ``If our imprisonment will bring peace, we are
ready even for death,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The three mayors belong to the pro-Kurdish People's Democracy Party. Both
the rebels and the pro-Kurdish party are demanding that Kurds are granted
cultural rights, such as the right to broadcast and teach in Kurdish.
</P>
<P>
	   The arrests triggered a wave of protests from European nations, who say
Turkey must grant cultural rights to Kurds if it ever hopes to join the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
	   The German Foreign Ministry on Monday welcomed the release of the mayors.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They are innocent,'' defense lawyer Fethi Gumus said outside the prison
before the mayors' release. ``There is no solid evidence against them, only
fictitious allegations from an informant.''
</P>
<P>
	   Informants reportedly told police that the mayors gave money and municipal
jobs to guerrillas and their relatives.
</P>
<P>
	   Celik denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
	   Judge Ethem Ucan ordered the mayors released, ruling that they were unlikely
to flee or tamper with evidence. But he said they must stand trial on charges
that could put them in prison for up to 7 1/2 years.
</P>
<P>
	   The three were barred from leaving the country until their trial, a second
court announced Monday. But the Interior Ministry ruled late Monday that the
mayors could take up their posts.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors are pushing for the closure of the party, saying it is a front
for the rebels. The PKK has said it is laying down its weapons and is looking to
become a legitimate political organization within Turkey. Turkey has said it
will never talk with the rebels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
