<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French PM Faces Political Fallout  </HEADLINE>
   By ELAINE GANLEY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PARIS (AP) -- France's Socialist Party stepped to the defense of the
country's prime minister on Monday after he drew criticism by calling Lebanese
guerrilla attacks on Israeli soldiers ``terrorist'' actions.
</P>
<P>
	   Prime Minister Lionel Jospin suffered a slight head wound Saturday after
students pelted him with stones at the West Bank's Bir Zeit University for
making the comment about the acts of Lebanese guerrillas fighting Israeli
occupation forces in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
	   The Socialist Party, to which Jospin belongs, portrayed the incident as a
step toward truth-telling in international affairs.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The Socialist Party does not regret what was said,'' First Secretary
Francois Hollande said Monday on French radio. ``This movement (Hezbollah)
needed to be characterized for what it is: a movement unfavorable to the peace
process.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``I believe,'' he continued, ``there is a moment in international life when
one must say what one thinks.''
</P>
<P>
	   Upon his return to France, Jospin also faced what Agriculture Minister Jean
Glavany said was a ``Parisian tempest over a word'' for the remark targeting
Iranian-backed Hezbollah guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
	   Opponents said he had been irresponsible in dabbling with France's delicate
Middle East diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
	   The incident unleashed passions in the Middle East. Some 5,000 people
demonstrated in Lebanon's Bekaa Valley Monday, and 150 students protested in the
southern port city of Tyre. On Sunday, some 3,000 protesters demonstrated in
Sidon.
</P>
<P>
	   Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss urged France not to equate ``the attacker
and the attacked.''
</P>
<P>
	   Chirac passed his own message to the Lebanese through the visiting deputy
speaker of the French Senate.
</P>
<P>
	   ``France's firm policy toward Lebanon has not changed,'' Gerard Larche said
after meeting Monday with Lebanese President Emile Lahoud and Hoss.
</P>
<P>
	   France, a former colonial ruler in Lebanon, has long supported Lebanon in
its effort to get Israeli troops to withdraw from the southern strip of the
country. More generally, Paris has worked to be perceived as a friend of the
Arabs without abandoning Israel.
</P>
<P>
	   Jospin's comment led to the first serious confrontation with President
Jacques Chirac, a conservative sharing power with a leftist coalition government
since 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   The French head of state, traditionally in charge of foreign policy, said by
phone to Jospin that the balance and impartiality on which French diplomacy is
built had been put in doubt.
</P>
<P>
	   Jospin was expected to come under fire during Tuesday's question period at
the National Assembly and again Wednesday at a scheduled meeting with Chirac.
</P>
<P>
	   Jospin has been seen as a likely candidate in presidential elections in
2002, possibly against Chirac.
</P>
<P>
	   Romano Prodi, the president of the European Commission, on Monday condemned
the stoning attack on Jospin, criticizing the behavior of the rioting
Palestinian students.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think this is the most horrible way of doing politics,'' Prodi, who
heads the EU's executive arm, said at a joint news conference with Israeli
Foreign Minister David Levy in Jerusalem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
