<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alleged Cuba Spy Faces Deadline  </HEADLINE>
   By TOM COHEN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TORONTO (AP) -- An alleged Cuban spy permitted into Canada after being
expelled from the United States stayed inside the Cuban Embassy on Monday as the
time limit on his two-day transit visa ran down.
</P>
<P>
	   Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy said Jose Imperatori, 46, would
become an illegal alien if he remained in Canada beyond the two-day limit
allowed by the visa granted Imperatori upon his arrival in Montreal on Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
	   As of 10 p.m. EST Monday, Imperatori remained in Cuba's embassy in Ottawa
and there was no word on when he would leave.
</P>
<P>
	   Imperatori was taken into custody by U.S. authorities and flown to Montreal
aboard a U.S. government plane late Saturday. He had been expected to leave
Canada for Havana on Sunday, but did not do so. Even his family members in Cuba
said they weren't sure when he would arrive home.
</P>
<P>
	   Axworthy said Canada wanted no role in the latest diplomatic fracas between
Cuba and the United States, and refused to specify what would happen if
Imperatori refused to leave the country.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We'll have to see if the Cuban authorities live up to their
responsibilities and their basic rules and connections of diplomacy,'' Axworthy
said. ``We were simply providing a courtesy to allow him to transfer back to
Cuba, and we expect them to recognize just exactly what it was.''
</P>
<P>
	   Imperatori's wife, Raquel Fundora, and the couple's 3-year-old son returned
to Havana from the United States on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
	   On Saturday, Imperatori resigned his consular position, giving up his
diplomatic immunity, and said he intended to defy the U.S. State Department's
expulsion order so he could contest allegations linking him with U.S.
immigration official Mariano Faget, who has been charged with spying for Cuba.
</P>
<P>
	   FBI officials escorted Imperatori, accompanied by his lawyer, from his
suburban Maryland apartment to the plane that flew him to Montreal on Saturday
night. The State Department said he was expelled for not voluntarily leaving by
the appointed time.
</P>
<P>
	   Cuban officials say that they believe the allegations are a smokescreen to
block the return of 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez to his father in Cuba.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
