<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Dead After Ind. Hostage Standoff  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Ind. (AP) -- A man shot his estranged wife outside their child's
school and took a liquor store manager hostage Monday. The man and manager were
found dead when police stormed the store after a seven-hour standoff.
</P>
<P>
	   Gregroy Miller fired a shotgun at Sue Miller, 32, as she dropped their
daughter off at Austin Middle School about 8 a.m, police said. The woman was
slightly injured and the child was not hurt.
</P>
<P>
	   Moments later, Miller's pickup truck collided with another vehicle a couple
of blocks away and Miller ran about 200 feet to the Main Package Store and took
manager Kenny Ross, 45, hostage. Five people in the other vehicle were treated
for minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
	   Miller, 34, made a 911 call from the store and was allowed to speak with his
wife. The call ended when the phone went dead, immediately preceded by the
possible sound of a shot being fired, police said.
</P>
<P>
	   Police surrounded the liquor store and negotiations began. After a long
period without any contact, state police Emergency Response Team members entered
the building about 3 p.m. and discovered the bodies of Miller and Ross. They
refused to say how the two died.
</P>
<P>
	   The Millers apparently were in the middle of getting divorced, said Sgt.
Marv. Jenkins, a spokesman for the Sellersburg post.
</P>
<P>
	   Austin is about 35 miles north of Louisville, Ky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
