<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Morris' removal from  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   COLLINGSWOOD, N.J. (AP) - Embattled Philadelphia Teamsters Local 115
chief John Morris was ejected from a hearing Monday to determine whether he
should regain control of the local.
<P>
	   Morris was ejected from the hearing after repeatedly interrupting the
proceeding and ignoring warnings, said Don Owens, a spokesman for the
International Brotherhood of Teamsters.
</P>
<P>
	   "It deteriorated into a shouting match," Owens said.
</P>
<P>
	   The hearing began in January but was adjourned without a resolution. It
resumed Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Morris, accompanied by an advisor, was escorted from the union hall by the
sergeant-at-arms and several Collingswood police officers, Owens said. The
hearing ended a short time later.
</P>
<P>
	   The interruption occurred as Local 115 President Jim Smith testified about
alleged fiscal mismanagement by Morris, Owens said.
</P>
<P>
	   At one point during the testimony, Morris "cocked his finger in the shape of
a gun and made a shooting sound," Owens said. The hearing chairman then ordered
Morris removed, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Morris could not be reached for comment after the hearing.
</P>
<P>
	   Police also had to calm a tense verbal confrontation outside the union hall
between Morris' supporters and Teamster international union members who support
his ouster.
</P>
<P>
	   Teamster international union officials expect to complete their case against
Morris when the hearing resumes Tuesday at 8:30 a.m., Owens said. Morris will
then have an opportunity to call rebuttal witnesses.
</P>
<P>
	   Security was scaled down at the Local 676 union hall in Collingswood where
about 40 union members attended the hearing before a three-member panel. Several
police officers could be seen inside the entrance to the building.
</P>
<P>
	   When the hearings began in January, Collingswood police called in nearly 100
officers, including sharpshooters on rooftops.
</P>
<P>
	   Monday's session was the third time the panel has heard testimony in Morris'
removal. The previous hearings were adjourned without resolution and scheduling
conflicts have delayed the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're very cognizant that people want this to wrap up in a timely manner,"
Owens said.
</P>
<P>
	   Morris will get an opportunity to call rebuttal witnesses in his defense. He
has blamed his ouster as a political payback for not backing Teamsters president
James Hoffa.
</P>
<P>
	   Hoffa signed an emergency order in November removing Morris as
secretary-treasurer of Local 115. Among the charges were allegations that he
bought weapons with union money and intimidated members he considered disloyal.
</P>
<P>
	   Morris, 73, won a federal court ruling that no emergency existed to remove
him without a hearing. Morris founded the 2,700-member local in 1955 and has
been at the helm since then.
</P>
<P>
	   At previous sessions of the union hearing, auditors testified about alleged
mismanagement of union funds. The two witnesses appearing before the panel this
week are expected to give testimony about intimidation, Owens said.
</P>
<P>
	   Morris has denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm fighting this thing to the end," Morris said when the hearings began in
January. "I'm going to go on to what I have to do."
</P>
<P>
	   When the testimony is complete, the panel of Teamsters officials - Charles
Byrnes, secretary treasurer of Local 926 in Pittsburgh; Denis Taylor, president
of Local 355 in Baltimore; and Ron McClain, president of Local 147 in Des
Moines, Iowa - will send a letter to Hoffa within 60 days with a recommendation
on whether a trusteeship should be imposed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
