<HEADLINE> Israeli Caricaturist 'Dosh' Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Veteran caricaturist Kariel Gardos, whose cartoon character
Srulik became a symbol of Israel as recognizable to his countrymen as Uncle Sam
is to Americans, died of cardiac arrest Monday in Tel Aviv. He was 78.
</P>
<P>
	   Known to generations of Israelis as ``Dosh,'' Gardos created the image of
Srulik as a little boy wearing a floppy sun hat, the ``kova tembel.'' It was
Srulik who reacted every morning to the political events of the previous day in
a cartoon in the daily newspaper Maariv.
</P>
<P>
	   Yosef ``Tommy'' Lapid, once an editor at Maariv and now the head of a small
opposition party in parliament, said Gardos was one of the greatest
caricaturists of the 20th century and had a profound influence on the opinions
of the Israeli public and the actions of politicians.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He created little Srulik, who became the symbol of Israel, just as
Marianne is the symbol of France or Uncle Sam is the symbol of the United
States,'' Lapid said.
</P>
<P>
	   Born in 1922 in Budapest as Karl Gardos, he survived the Holocaust and came
to Israel in 1948, where he changed his first name to Kariel.
</P>
<P>
	   He said many years later that he became a caricaturist because he did not
speak Hebrew when he arrived, and the visual medium enabled him to express
himself without knowing the language.
</P>
<P>
	   He is survived by his common law wife, Tova Pardos, a daughter and a son,
Mickey. Arrangements for his funeral were not announced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 2219 </TRAILER>
