<HEADLINE> Brokers Group Expels LT Lawrence  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    WASHINGTON (AP) -- A self-regulatory brokers' group has expelled from the
securities industry the brokerage firm LT Lawrence &AMP; Co. Inc., its chief
executive officer and its president for allegedly defrauding investors.
</P>
<P>
	   The two LT Lawrence officials have agreed to repay 300 customers a total
$275,000, NASD Regulation announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition, the firm's compliance officer has agreed in a settlement to pay
a $20,000 fine and to be suspended from the industry for 30 days. The compliance
officer, Mitchell J. Halpern, neither admitted nor denied the regulators'
allegation, made in a September 1998 complaint, that he failed to enforce rules
prohibiting fraudulent conduct.
</P>
<P>
	   NASD Regulation, the enforcement arm of the National Association of
Securities Dealers, said CEO Lawrence Principato and President Todd E. Roberti
had cheated LT Lawrence customers by charging them excessive markups in 350
stock transactions in 1996.
</P>
<P>
	   Principato and Roberti agreed in a settlement to fully reimburse 300
customers in 37 states and Britain who lost a total $275,000, NASD Regulation
said. The two, who also agreed to be barred from the industry, neither admitted
nor denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
	   "They're going on with their lives," said their attorney, Ira Lee Sorkin. He
declined further comment.
</P>
<P>
	   Markups are differentials over the prevailing market price for securities.
Regulators consider markups of more than 10 percent to be fraudulent.
</P>
<P>
	   Last July, LT Lawrence's head trader, Thomas J. Dalton, settled a related
disciplinary action by agreeing to a $40,000 fine and a three-month suspension.
He neither admitted nor denied wrongdoing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
