<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flap May Put ABC Affiliate Off Air  </HEADLINE>
    By C. BRYSON HULL Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HOUSTON (AP) -- Time Warner cable subscribers here could be cut off from
their local ABC affiliate, which has become a pawn in a battle between the media
giant and rival Walt Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
	   Disney-owned ABC threatened to pull ABC programming from the Time Warner
cable system in Houston, after the companies failed to reach a national deal
over retransmission rights.
</P>
<P>
	   Negotiations broke down over The Disney Channel, which, among other things,
ABC wants included in Time Warner's basic cable package, both parties said late
Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The cable provider balked at converting it from a pay channel, citing a
systemwide cost of $100 million which would be passed to Time Warner customers.
</P>
<P>
	   The impasse came during negotiations for a national retransmission
agreement, in which cable companies provide compensation to over-the-air
networks for the right to broadcast their programming.
</P>
<P>
	   The agreements have been mandated since Congress passed the Cable Act of
1992, which requires cable operators to carry local broadcast affiliates on
their systems.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's vitally important to us that we do get fair value for our content,"
ABC senior vice president and general counsel Alan Braverman said. "We have no
choice. The hardest thing for a broadcaster to do is to disrupt its viewers."
</P>
<P>
	   ABC's motivation is to force Time Warner back to the negotiating table,
Braverman said.
</P>
<P>
	   If no deal can be reached, KTRK-TV in Houston will go off the cable system
as of 12:01 a.m. CST Thursday, when the current retransmission agreement
expires. About 665,000 subscribers would be without ABC programming.
</P>
<P>
	   Time Warner spokesman Mike Luftman said ABC pulled a finalized deal off the
table at the last minute and changed its terms.
</P>
<P>
	   "They basically reneged. We think a deal should be a deal, and we cannot
accept a deal that will raise costs by more than $100 million nationwide,"
Luftman said.
</P>
<P>
	   The cable company cannot air ABC content once the current retransmission
agreement expires, Luftman said. The deal expired Dec. 31, but ABC extended the
deadline temporarily during negotiations.
</P>
<P>
	   ABC chose Houston because it would cause the least disruption, since cable
penetration is lower in the nation's fourth-largest city than it is in other
large markets, Braverman said.
</P>
<P>
	   "The signal is easy to pick up, and it's a market in which Direct TV and
EchoStar both allow local-to-local channels by satellite," Braverman said.
</P>
<P>
	   To that end, ABC is negotiating with satellite providers to help Houston
customers sign up for new satellite services. Braverman declined to comment on
which satellite providers could be involved.
</P>
<P>
	   Time Warner officials said Houston customers are the unfortunate victims in
a power play.
</P>
<P>
	   "I liken it to what happens when a terrorist takes hostages. They will often
pick one out and shoot them just to show they mean business," Luftman said.
"That's apparently what Disney and ABC are going to do to Houston."
</P>
<P>
	   Should KTRK go off the cable system, Time Warner plans to offer HBO Family,
normally a pay channel, in its place at no extra cost to subscribers, Luftman
said.
</P>
<P>
	   The cable company also plans to provide free antennas to customers who want
to tune in KTRK the old fashioned way -- over the airwaves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 2221 </TRAILER>
