<HEADLINE> Venezuela Has New Miss Universe Rep  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Venezuela is sending a new contestant to the Miss
Universe contest because the regular beauty queen was in such demand this year
that she caused confusion in international pageant regulations.
</P>
<P>
	   The issue is important in this Latin American country, which has won 11 top
international beauty titles in the last two decades, more than any other nation.
</P>
<P>
	   Claudia Moreno, 22, was crowned Miss Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela in a
modest ceremony in Caracas Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
	   The woman who was supposed to represent Venezuela in May's Miss Universe
pageant in Cyprus was disqualified because of the likelihood she would hold two
major international beauty titles at the same time.
</P>
<P>
	   Venezuela usually has one major national pageant. The runner-up goes to the
Miss World contest and the winner represents her nation in the Miss Universe
contest.
</P>
<P>
	   But last year, Miss World officials insisted that Venezuela send its winner
to them, too. It did, and the Venezuelan contestant, 24-year-old Martina
Thorogood, was named first runner-up in the contest in London in December.
</P>
<P>
	   Thorogood was also to have competed in the Miss Universe pageant in Cyprus.
But Miss Universe officials objected, saying Thorogood wasn't eligible because
she can't be both Miss Universe and Miss World at the same time. That could
happen if the current Miss World were to abdicate her crown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 2248 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
