<DOCNO> APW20000228.0305 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-28 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Unemployment Rate Unchanged  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's jobless rate was unchanged at 4.7 percent in January
from December's revised figure as the nation struggled to emerge from its
decade-long economic slump, the government said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, the number of unemployed people totaled 3.09 million in January, up
110,000, or 3.7 percent, from the same month in 1999, the statistics bureau of
the Management and Coordination Agency said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Unemployment has risen as companies struggling for survival cut costs by
reducing their work forces. The jobless rate stood at a record 4.9 percent in
June and July last year.
</P>
<P>
	   The government has used public spending to jump-start the economy, which it
expects to grow by 1 percent in the coming fiscal year beginning in April.
</P>
<P>
	   The number of permanent jobholders fell 520,000, or 1.1 percent on-year, to
46.36 million, declining for the 25th straight month as companies continue to
replace lifetime workers with temporary staff.
</P>
<P>
	   Temporary workers cost less in terms of pension and other benefits.
</P>
<P>
	   The number of people with temporary jobs grew by 20,000 to 5.1 million, the
agency said. The rise has continued since September 1996.
</P>
<P>
	   The Labor Ministry said the ratio of job offers to job seekers, an indicator
of demand for labor, improved by 0.02 point to 0.52 in January from December.
The ratio shows that 52 jobs were being offered for every 100 workers seeking
employment in January.
</P>
<P>
	   That was its highest level since the ratio touched 0.53 in June 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Also, the new job offers ratio showed that there were 96 new jobs for every
100 people newly seeking work, the highest level since April 1998 when the ratio
stood at 0.96. A year ago, the ratio read 0.88.
</P>
<P>
	   Overall, the total number of new job offers increased 11.7 percent on year
in January. All sectors in the economy, including retail, service,
manufacturing, transport, telecommunications and construction, posted gains.
</P>
<P>
	   The jobless rate for men fell 0.1 point in January to 4.8 percent, marking
the first decline in four months. The jobless rate for women rose 0.1 point to
4.5 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
