<HEADLINE> U.S. Admiral Meets With Chinese  </HEADLINE>
   By JOHN LEICESTER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BEIJING (AP) -- In fence-mending talks with Chinese military leaders, the
commander of U.S. Pacific forces expressed concern Tuesday about Beijing's new
threats to attack Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
	   Adm. Dennis Blair's visit comes amid rising tensions over Taiwan in the
run-up to the island's March 18 presidential election. China's newest threat of
force was made despite U.S. calls for restraint.
</P>
<P>
	   Blair's visit is aimed at repairing military channels of communication that
could help ease tensions. Beijing severed military ties after U.S. warplanes hit
China's embassy in Yugoslavia in May, and the dialogue only resumed last month.
</P>
<P>
	   Blair met Tuesday with Chinese military and government leaders, but U.S.
officials in Beijing refused to discuss the talks.
</P>
<P>
	   On Monday, the admiral met with Lt. Gen. Xiong Guangkai for ``a wide
exchange of views on international and regional security and bilateral
relations,'' China's state-run Xinhua News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
	   Xiong is a deputy chief of the general staff of the Chinese People's
Liberation Army and a key voice in making Taiwan policy. Blair also met Shi
Yunsheng, commander in chief of China's naval forces, Xinhua said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It was a chance for everyone to get to know each other,'' a U.S official
said on condition of anonymity. ``The atmosphere was very cordial. I think the
Chinese want to succeed in re-establishing a military-to-military
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
	   Taiwan was discussed, along with other Asian security concerns, the official
said. The U.S. side also ``expressed its concern about the white paper'' in
which China last week threatened Taiwan, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   For the first time, Beijing said it might attack if Taiwan indefinitely put
off negotiations on unification. The threat, contained in a government position
paper issued Feb. 21, appeared aimed at putting pressure on the three leading
Taiwanese presidential candidates, none of whom support union on China's terms.
</P>
<P>
	   China also is angry with proposed legislation in the U.S. Congress that
would increase cooperation between the U.S. and Taiwan militaries. The Clinton
administration opposes the bill and has threatened to veto it. But the measure
has nonetheless heightened suspicions in Beijing about U.S. involvement in the
Taiwan question. China fears U.S. support could embolden Taiwan to declare
formal independence -- a move Beijing says would mean war.
</P>
<P>
	   China and Taiwan split amid civil war in 1949, with the United States
supporting Chiang Kai-shek's Nationalists on the island against Mao Tse-tung's
Communists.
</P>
<P>
	   Although the United States now acknowledges China's claim to Taiwan,
Washington is obligated by law to help the island maintain an adequate defense.
</P>
<P>
	   After he concludes his meetings Tuesday, Blair is expected to travel to the
eastern city of Nanjing, headquarters for the regional military command that
would form the bulk of any Chinese attack on Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
	   Advocates say China-U.S. military contacts can help avoid miscalculations
during times of tension.
</P>
<P>
	   Four years ago, in an attempt to influence Taiwan's first direct
presidential elections, China fired test missiles near Taiwan. The United States
sent warships in response, raising tensions to their highest level in decades.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-28-00 2326 </TRAILER>
