<HEADLINE> Report: Pinochet Test Not Requested  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Gen. Augusto Pinochet has not been asked to take a second
medical examination despite last week's requests, The Daily Telegraph reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Belgium and France asked Home Secretary Jack Straw to order a second medical
assessment seven days ago, after the first assessment concluded the 84-year-old
former Chilean dictator was unfit to stand trial in Spain on torture-related
charges.
</P>
<P>
	   Spanish Judge Baltasar Garzon also requested a second exam, while
Switzerland argued ill health should not bar a trial.
</P>
<P>
	   Pinochet's lawyers have not yet been approached by Straw with a request, the
newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
	   But chief medical officer Liam Donaldson has discussed observations of the
four governments with Sir John Grimley Evans, an Oxford University professor who
led the British medical doctors in their Jan. 5 examination, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
	   Last month, Straw said he was inclined to let Pinochet return to his
homeland based on the findings of the original medical report. Lawyers Tuesday
speculated that the only explanation for the delay was that Straw was drafting
his statement to avoid a move by any of the four countries to block that
decision.
</P>
<P>
	   Straw has promised to announce his decision first in the House of Commons.
</P>
<P>
	   Pinochet was arrested in London on Oct. 16, 1998, on a warrant issued by
Garzon that accused Pinochet of human rights violations during his 17 years in
power.
</P>
<P>
	   A report by the civilian government that succeeded Pinochet says 3,197
people died or disappeared during the general's rule.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
